Formerly considered conspecific with S. melanotos.
Male_Text: From Kear (2005) dimorphic mainly in size of male. Female head and neck white (usually tinged yellow in breeding season), variable spotted with black, more thickly on nape and hind neck. Underparts metallic, blue-green, secondaries bronzy, scapulars purple. Lower parts white, and flanks black. Undertail coverts white, becoming orange-yellow in breeding season. Bill black, with fleshy proturberance or caruncle on mandible; legs dark gray: iris brown, female similar to male but much smaller, duller, less metallic above and no caruncle.
Female_Text: From Kear (2005) dimorphic mainly in size of male. Female head and neck white (usually tinged yellow in breeding season), variable spotted with black, more thickly on nape and hind neck. Underparts metallic, blue-green, secondaries bronzy, scapulars purple. Lower parts white, and flanks black. Undertail coverts white, becoming orange-yellow in breeding season. Bill black, with fleshy proturberance or caruncle on mandible; legs dark gray: iris brown, female similar to male but much smaller, duller, less metallic above and no caruncle.

Male_Text: Adult plumage is generally grayish-tan with a distinctive brown maskphoto around the eye and a small brown patch on breast. Primaries, rectrices, and rump are black. Secondaries are iridescent green  . Bill, legsphoto , and feet are pink. Upperwingphoto and underwing coverts are white, which is distinctive in flight. Eyes orange. Immaturephoto birds lack the brown eye-patch and brown patch on the breast, while the upperwing is sooty in coloration (Johnsgard 1978); eye and breast patches form at 3–5 months and five months, respectively (Kear and 2005). Aberrant gray-mantled and leucistic individuals also occur (Cramp and Simmons 1977, Campbell 1989). Males and females are very similar in appearance, however, females are smaller, with narrower neck. Legs of female are also less intensely colored in breeding season (Davies 2005).
Female_Text: Adult plumage is generally grayish-tan with a distinctive brown maskphoto around the eye and a small brown patch on breast. Primaries, rectrices, and rump are black. Secondaries are iridescent green  . Bill, legsphoto , and feet are pink. Upperwingphoto and underwing coverts are white, which is distinctive in flight. Eyes orange. Immaturephoto birds lack the brown eye-patch and brown patch on the breast, while the upperwing is sooty in coloration (Johnsgard 1978); eye and breast patches form at 3–5 months and five months, respectively (Kear and 2005). Aberrant gray-mantled and leucistic individuals also occur (Cramp and Simmons 1977, Campbell 1989). Males and females are very similar in appearance, however, females are smaller, with narrower neck. Legs of female are also less intensely colored in breeding season (Davies 2005).

Male_Text: "The plumage is very dark in wild Muscovies, primarily black with a greenish gloss, and white wing coverts (on both the upper and under surfaces of the wing). Domesticated Muscovies usually show white blotches on the body plumage. The sexes are generally similar, but females are significantly smaller than males, the plumage is duller (less glossy) and with less white in the wings, and the female lacks the crest and facial caruncles." Adult male: Overall plumage is blackish, with a metallic greenish-purple cast on the upperparts, the gloss becoming more violet on the upper back. Prominent crest on crown and rear of neck. Wing coverts, on both the upper and under surfaces of the wing, white. Adult female: Plumage similar to that of males but duller. Face fully feathered, not bare as in male.
Female_Text: "The plumage is very dark in wild Muscovies, primarily black with a greenish gloss, and white wing coverts (on both the upper and under surfaces of the wing). Domesticated Muscovies usually show white blotches on the body plumage. The sexes are generally similar, but females are significantly smaller than males, the plumage is duller (less glossy) and with less white in the wings, and the female lacks the crest and facial caruncles." Adult male: Overall plumage is blackish, with a metallic greenish-purple cast on the upperparts, the gloss becoming more violet on the upper back. Prominent crest on crown and rear of neck. Wing coverts, on both the upper and under surfaces of the wing, white. Adult female: Plumage similar to that of males but duller. Face fully feathered, not bare as in male.

Female_Text: "Female. Crown, head, and auriculars gray with bronze and purple sheens; crest with elongated feathers (not as long as in male); area around eye with white patch, tapering to rear. Upperparts olive green or gray with sheen ranging from bronze to violet; tail darker than back with greenish bronze sheen. Pattern of wing like male but with less vivid colors; upperwing greater coverts iridescent cobalt-ultramarine with black margins (tertial coverts not “pale greenish” as described by Palmer 1976), this ultramarine coloring extending to median and lower row or two of lesser coverts; tertials olive; secondaries with white tips wider on outer than inner web."

annotation: Monotypic. Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Monotypic. Spatula discors orphna recognized by AOU 1957, but validity doubtful. Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Male_Text: "Males in breeding (Alternate) plumage readily distinguished by grayish head with large white crescent in front of eye bordering base of bill; cinnamon-buffy underparts densely spotted with black; green speculum; bold white rear border to blue wing-patch; rounded white patch on rear flank behind legs; and orange legs and feet." "Green portion of secondaries forms an iridescent dark green “speculum” on wing. Overlying greater coverts dark or same with blue on outer webs. Lesser and median wing coverts mostly light turquoise-cobalt, forming a prominent blue patch on wing. "
Female_Text: "Wing similar to Definitive Basic male, except distal greater coverts with broad, dark, and narrow white barring; innermost secondaries dark brownish with broad pale margins and rounded ends; their overlying greater coverts entirely dark or edged whitish; most secondaries with outer webs sepia with greenish tinge (duller than in male); "

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Male_Text: "Male in Basic plumage much like female but with scarlet red iris (hazel in female), bright iridescent bronze-green speculum (dull, non-iridescent green in females), and white greater coverts (dark spotted or mostly dark in female) (Carney 1992). Juveniles overall pale brownish with smaller and more pointed contour feathers below; sexes similar."
Female_Text: "Male in Basic plumage much like female but with scarlet red iris (hazel in female), bright iridescent bronze-green speculum (dull, non-iridescent green in females), and white greater coverts (dark spotted or mostly dark in female) (Carney 1992). Juveniles overall pale brownish with smaller and more pointed contour feathers below; sexes similar."

annotation: Monotypic. Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Male_Text: DEFINITIVE BASIC "Male. Head and neck dark brown-black anteriorly and medially, light tan with brown shafts laterally and ventrally. Back black, some feathers with light-brown edging, others iridescent green.". DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE "Male. Distinguished from Alternate I by absence of black vermiculations on feathers posterior to vent. Innermost secondaries acutely pointed; black with greenish iridescence." . ALTERNATE I "Head and neck black with iridescent green medially. Some birds show a partial white crescent on face similar in shape and location to that found on adult male Blue-winged Teal. Back black, feathers with drab edging. Rump black with green iridescence dorsally; white laterally."
Female_Text: DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE "Female. Distinguished from Alternate I by blackish-brown mantle, individual feathers with margins that are pinkish buff fading to buff. Also less dark breast and buffy or pinkish tan underparts; feathers more spotted than streaked (Palmer 1976, PJD). Plumage acquired by partial (not remiges and rectrices) Prealternate molt. Upper surface between buffy brown and fuscous, crown and hindneck narrowly streaked with paler buff. Remaining upperparts edged, barred, and spotted with light buff, pale pinkish buff, or dull white. Tail white or brownish white; middle feathers barred and mottled with hair brown, fuscous, and drab. Wings fuscous, inner webs of primaries brownish drab, lesser wing coverts mouse gray, tips of greater wing coverts and outer webs of secondaries broadly white. Speculum metallic cossack green, bordered anteriorly by white tips of greater coverts. Head light buff; chin and upper throat unmarked, lower throat and sides of head streaked and spotted with fuscous. Remaining lower parts dull cinnamon buff anteriorly, light buff posteriorly, spotted with hair brown, fuscous, and drab. Lining of wing white or buffy white (Oberholser 1974)."

annotation: No extant subspecies. Peters (1979), Clements (2000), and Howard and Moore (2003) recognize Mareca strepera couesi, now extinct. Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Male_Text: "Rump and uppertail-coverts black, with slight green or blue iridescence"

annotation: Monotypic. Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Male_Text: "Male has chestnut head and neckphoto , with yellowish crownphoto , sometimes has metallic dark green spot behind eyesphoto and on throat, pinkish-grey breastphoto , grey-vermiculated upperparts and sides, white lower breast and belly, contrasting with black surround to white-grey tail, white upperwing-coverts, elongated grey scapularsphoto , dark green speculumphoto edged black, grey-brown primaries and dusky grey axillaries (but note that both sexes can be much paler over both this tract and underwing-coverts  ) (2); blue-grey bill with black tip, slate-grey legs and feet, and brown eyes; has female-like eclipse plumagevideo , which is rich reddish chestnut, with darker upperparts than adult female, rufous flanks and contrasting white forewing."

annotation: Monotypic. Formerly placed in the genus Anas.
Male_Text: "American Wigeon are typically quick to flush and produce a distinct, high-pitched, three-note call that is reminiscent of a squeaky toy, and they have a fast, erratic flight pattern that reveals a bold white wing patch and brilliant green speculum on drakes." "Adult male (Alternate plumage): forehead and crown white; broad dark green patch surrounding eye passing to nape; rest of head and upper neck buffy white heavily speckled with black; breast, sides, and flanks pinkish brown contrasting with white belly and sides of rump; scapulars and back pinkish brown, finely vermiculated with black; undertail-coverts black, uppertail-coverts grayish, finely barred blackish; upperwing coverts white forming large white patch on open wing, speculum dark iridescent green bordered by black. Bill bluish gray with black tip." DEFINITIVE BASIC" primaries and primary coverts grayish-brown with grayer inner webs and indistinct dusky tips, broader, glossier, and more truncate than juvenile feathers; outer secondaries (wing speculum) velvety black, tipped white, the proximal third of each feather with green iridescence forming iridescent green bar;"
Female_Text: DEFINITIVE BASIC "outer secondaries (wing speculum) black, tipped white, the outer 4–5 feathers (s1–s5) with dull green iridescence, brightening distally;"

annotation: Monotypic. Listed as a subspecies of Anas platyrhynchos by Peters (1979) and del Hoyo et al. (1992).
Male_Text: "Some males show what appears to be faint greenish iridescence on head or neck and usually have slightly upturned central tail feathers; otherwise sexes very similar. In both sexes, speculum green to greenish purple, and legs and feet pale, dull orange, usually brighter in male." DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE. Male. Head and neck: crown sepia (Color 119), forehead sepia with variable white speckling, but predominately sepia. Hind crown and nape sepia; can be glossed with dark green iridescence in some birds.
Female_Text: "Some males show what appears to be faint greenish iridescence on head or neck and usually have slightly upturned central tail feathers; otherwise sexes very similar. In both sexes, speculum green to greenish purple, and legs and feet pale, dull orange, usually brighter in male." DEFINITIVE ALTERNATIVE "Female. Head and neck: crown sepia to warm sepia (Color 221A), forehead variously speckled with white. Hind crown and nape sepia, lacking iridescent green gloss seen in males.

annotation: Monotypic. Listed as a subspecies of Anas platyrhynchos by Peters (1979) and del Hoyo et al. (1992).
Male_Text: " In males, the speculum is emerald green to blue (lighting in field may enhance blue tones), bordered anteriorly by black and faint white bars, and distally by black and bold white bars. In female, speculum similar but duller, without anterior black border and with buff trailing edge."
Female_Text: " In males, the speculum is emerald green to blue (lighting in field may enhance blue tones), bordered anteriorly by black and faint white bars, and distally by black and bold white bars. In female, speculum similar but duller, without anterior black border and with buff trailing edge."

Male_Text: "Male in Definitive Basic (breeding) Plumage has a dark green head, narrow white neck-ring, chestnut-brown breastphoto , brownish gray upperparts, grayish underparts, black rump  and undertail coverts, white outer tail  feathers and strongly recurved black central tail feathers; upperwing has iridescent blue to violet-blue speculumphoto (upperside of secondaries) bordered with white line at leading edge (tips of greater coverts) and trailing edge (tips of secondaries); underwing coverts  white contrasting with pale gray underside of remiges; billphoto yellow to olive; legs and feetphoto orange-red." "Male. Head and most of neck metallic green (can have dark violet-blue cast in sunlight); lower neck has white collar that usually is incomplete at nape; upperparts cinnamon to near black, the midportion with mixed coloring and fine dark markings; scapulars mostly light gray, vermiculated dark; rump and uppertail coverts black with dark-blue gloss; four central rectrices (r1–r2 on each side) black and strongly recurved, often forming a complete circle; next pair of rectrices (r3) medium gray; each next outer pair (r4–r8) progressively paler with fewer dark markings until outer pair mostly whitish (see Figure 58 in Pyle [4]). Upperwing lesser, median, and primary coverts and primaries medium dusky gray; greater coverts and inner secondaries (speculum) with bright blue secondary panel bordered on both sides by bold white bars, the outer web of s2 usually with some iridescent bluish, the inner secondaries (s3–s10) apart from the tertials with iridescent blue outer webs, black subterminal bands, and broad white tips (Figure 56 in Pyle [4]), and the medial greater coverts squarish with broad white subterminal bands and black tips (Figure 59 in Pyle [4]);"
Female_Text: DEFINITVE BASIC "Upperwing feathers as in Definitive Basic male except lesser, median, and primary coverts browner, the outer webs of s2–s3 only sometimes marked with blue iridescence, and the greater coverts with narrower white subterminal bands (Figure 59 in Pyle [4]); "
Notes: Shawn Billerman - examine the eclipse plumage

annotation: Formerly considered conspecific with Anas platyrhynchos.
Male_Text: "In Mexican Duck, both sexes resemble female Mallard in all plumages (Basic in fall through spring, Alternate in summer), overall showing a broken streaky pattern of buff, white, gray, or black on brown feathers, whitish outer tail feathers, contrastingly pale (whitish mottled) belly and undertail coverts, and prominent dark eyeline; upperwing has iridescent blue to violet-blue speculum (upperside of secondaries) bordered with white line at leading edge (tips of greater coverts) and trailing edge (tips of secondaries); underwing coverts white contrasting with pale gray underside of remiges." DEFINITIVE BASIC "Upperwing lesser, median, and primary coverts and primaries medium dusky gray; greater coverts and inner secondaries (speculum) with bright blue to greenish-blue secondary panel bordered on both sides by narow white bars, the outer web of s3 usually with some iridescent bluish, the inner secondaries (s3-s10) apart from the tertials with iridescent blue outer webs, black subterminal bands, and narrow white tips (Figure 56 in 1), and the medial greater coverts squarish with medium-broad white subterminal bands, extending proximally along outer web, and black tips (Figure 59 in 1); tertials brown tinged silvery gray, broad, long, and tapering to a fine point."
Female_Text: "In Mexican Duck, both sexes resemble female Mallard in all plumages (Basic in fall through spring, Alternate in summer), overall showing a broken streaky pattern of buff, white, gray, or black on brown feathers, whitish outer tail feathers, contrastingly pale (whitish mottled) belly and undertail coverts, and prominent dark eyeline; upperwing has iridescent blue to violet-blue speculum (upperside of secondaries) bordered with white line at leading edge (tips of greater coverts) and trailing edge (tips of secondaries); underwing coverts white contrasting with pale gray underside of remiges." "Definitive Basic Plumage best separated from Formative Plumage by wing and tail feather criteria: upperwing lesser and median coverts without pale fringes; speculum brighter by sex (Figures 56 and 59 in 1); outer primaries broader, grayer, glossier, and more abraded; tail without notched and abraded juvenile rectrices" "Female. Similar to Definitive Basic male except crown, upperparts, and sides of face browner, less grayish; upperwing lesser, median, and primary coverts browner, the outer webs of s2-s3 only sometimes marked with blue iridescence, and the greater coverts with narrower white subterminal bands (Figure 59 in 1); tertials browner with rusty edging and tertial coverts with pale brown tips; underpart feathers with darker centers and broad cinnamon to rusty fringing."

Male_Text: DEFINITIVE BASIC "Speculum iridescent ultramarine-violet; includes all secondaries except outermost one; lateral borders black; innermost secondaries shorter, more rounded than in Alternate plumage." DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE "Male. Sepia plumage, especially on anterior body, which contrasts with light head and neck. Typically, no internal markings on feathers on anterior dorsum; lyre-shaped markings on forward sides; flank-feathers unmarked, with cinnamon borders. Crown and upper nape are variable from solid sepia to army brown, narrow streaks, often iridescent green; natal-brown stripe through eye; remainder of head and most of neck from buff-brown to grayish, usually with irregular, fine, natal-brown streaking."
Female_Text: DEFINITIVE BASIC "Female. Feathers shorter, with more rounded ends than in Alternate plumage. Head and neck whitish buff, with shorter drab-gray streaks that give washed-out appearance. Feathers on sides and underparts have pale margins, contrasting with plain, van dyke-brown centers; no internal V-marking on breast feathers. Scapulars same as on male. Wing same as on male, except iridescent area does not extend to the most distal 2 or 3 secondaries; innermost secondaries have rounded ends and no cinnamon margin; greater coverts nearly plain.
Notes: Cayuga duck bred from the American Black Duck is entirely iridescent(M&F)

Male_Text: "Speculum is iridescent blue green (may appear iridescent blue, green, or purple depending on angle light), lacks anterior white edge, and lacks or has very thin, posterior white edge." "Speculum is iridescent blue green (may appear iridescent blue, green, or purple depending on angle light), lacks anterior white edge, and lacks or has very thin, posterior white edge."
Female_Text: "Tertials. Blackish brown with a slight greenish black metallic sheen, a very thin buffy brown edge and virtually no interior pattern."

Male_Text: "Unmistakable, with white cheek and throat patches contrasting with dark brown crownphoto and nape, with breast and underparts pale brown spotted black, upperparts  medium brown, dark brown and elongated tertials with buff fringes, iridescent green speculum  with narrow black subterminal band and broader buff terminal edge, and pale buff tail  and tail-coverts; red spot  at base of otherwise of dark bluish-grey bill  ; legs and feet dark grey; eyes red to red-brown."
Female_Text: " Female  slightly duller especially on crown  and back, with shorter tail and red spot on bill is smaller and less colourful (orange-red) (2)."

annotation: Recognized as a monotypic by AOU (1957), Clements (2000), and Howard and Moore (2003). Subspecies Anas acuta acuta, A. a. eatoni, and A. a. ...
Male_Text: "Malephoto unmistakablephoto in breeding plumage, which has chocolate-brown nape, throat and head, contrasting with white stripephoto on neck-sides  and largely grey-vermiculated upperparts and flanks, with foreneck, breast and central underparts  white, becoming yellow-buff ventrally  , black tail-coverts, brownish-gray primaries, grayish-brown wing-coverts  with buff fringes to greater coverts, metallic green to bronze speculum  that becomes blacker inwards and has black subterminal band  and broad white trailing edge, gray underwing  with darker coverts, gray scapulars and tertials with black central stripes, and two central rectrices highly elongated  and slender, black with pale grey fringes." " primaries and primary coverts sepia with grayer inner webs and indistinct dusky tips, broader, glossier, and more truncate than juvenile feathers; outer secondaries (wing speculum) partly metallic bronzy greenish to coppery with subterminal black band and white terminal band (Pyle 2008);"
Female_Text: "Female has grayish-brown headphoto and neck, finely flecked and mottled darker, slightly paler and finely mottled neck and underparts  , brownish flanks with darker crescentic markings, brownish-gray upperparts with scalloped effect, gray-brown wings with pale tips to greater coverts and duller, and bronze-brown speculum  with broad white trailing edgephoto ; bill duller than male with less obviously dark culmen." "; primaries and primary coverts as in male; outer secondaries (wing speculum) with brownish, gray-brown, or partly bronzy or greenish outer web with narrow black subterminal band and broad white tips both webs (Pyle 2008)"

Male_Text: "Black and metallic green speculumphoto ; bordered by a tan stripe on leading edge and a white stripe on trailing edge. Adult male has cinnamon headphoto with iridescent green stripephoto running through the eye to a small crest at the back bordered buff. Breast pinkish with small black spots" DEFINITIVE BASIC. "Speculum green" DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE. "Head feathers chestnut with an iridescent green crescent around eye that tapers to a short crest at back of head. Chin patch black. Dorsal feathers off-white with black vermiculation. Scapulars long and black along outer web, forming a black horizontal bar. Breast pinkish cinnamon with black spots. Short, white, vertical bar along sides just below leading edge of folded wing. Sides whitish with black vermiculation as in dorsal feathers. Belly white. Undertail-coverts black with a triangular creamy yellowish patch along each side. Tail dark gray with unnotched feathers. Innermost secondaries and greater coverts of wing gray, with covert adjoining speculum possessing a black band along outer edge."
Female_Text: "Black and metallic green speculumphoto ; bordered by a tan stripe on leading edge and a white stripe on trailing edge" DEFINITIVE BASIC.  Wing as in male Definitive Basic, but innermost secondaries shorter and broader. Innermost secondaries blackish to olive brown with buffy edges. Secondary-coverts tipped with buff becoming brownish buff toward outer wing. Median upper-coverts more brown than in male, with light buffy edges. Wing-lining and axillars all white." DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE. "The secondary next to the speculum has a brown stripe along the outer web."

Male_Text: "Male. Prealternate I molt incomplete, all feathers replaced except wing. Prealternate I molt begins in fall and Alternate I plumage usually complete by Jan or Feb, when birds are 6.5–8 mo old, but later in some individuals. Alternate I (first winter) plumage similar to but less brilliant than Definitive Alternate (adult) plumage. Head iridescence and vermiculations on flank and scapulars are more subdued than in adults."
Notes: Iridescence is described within the Juvenile Alternate I molt but not in the description of adults; Ask Shawn to confirm

Male_Text: "Male. Head, neck, breast, and all upperparts glossy black, with (usually) inconspicuous narrow, dark-chestnut collar around lower neck (collar incomplete dorsally); head and upper neck with ultramarine-violet sheen, lower back with metallic sheen, and chin often with white spot; rectrices glossy black. Upperwing coverts dark olive brownish to blackish with some greenish sheen, the smaller proximal lesser coverts plainer; primaries grayish fuscous, darker on outer webs and at tip; most outer secondaries (s1-s9) pearl gray, becoming darker near their ends and tipped with white; next 2 secondaries proximally (s10-s11) evenly gray but with more extensive white ends; tertials elongated and somewhat curved and black, or nearly black with greenish sheen when new; tertial coverts broadly rounded, similar in color and sheen, and sometimes with light flecking on smallest feathers."

"For non-breeding males, rounded head shape and bill pattern are particularly useful in identification; compared to A. collaris in these plumages, present species may show whitish foreflanks, but these are distinctly S-shaped in A. collaris, which species is shorter-tailed and longer-bodied; white at base of bill in female plumages can recall either larger and bulkier A. marila or similar-sized A. affinis, while birds showing white undertail-coverts can recall same-sex A. nyroca or A. baeri, but this areas is rarely as strikingly white as in A. nyroca and both these other species lack any crest, have distinctively peaked crown, and different eye colours. Long crest of malephoto unique among pochards; also separable from male of A. collaris by billphoto pattern and lack of collarphoto ; has female-like eclipse plumage  , but has darker head  , breast  and upperparts  than latter, pale brown breast-sides and flanks, not white around base of bill and whiter underparts. Femalephoto very variable, but is generally dark brown with paler flanks; can have some white on chin, around billphoto and on undertail-coverts (latter especially in autumn); has short crestphoto , yellow eye and white area on underparts which does not reach as far as flanks. Juvenile resembles female, but young male has darker head and foreneck, with somewhat vermiculated back patterning, and becomes much like adult male by Dec, albeit with duller iris, greyer flanks and narrower flight and tail feathers."

"Breeding malephoto has headphoto and neck black glossed greenphoto or purple, breast, upper mantle, rump and tail-coverts black or blackish, lower mantle and scapulars vermiculated white and black (appearing greyish), sides and belly white faintly vermiculated grey, wing-coverts black tinged brownish, speckled white, with broad white band over secondaries and most of primaries; underwing and axillaries whitish becoming paler towards trailing edge; eyes golden-yellow." "Male. Plumage of head, neck, upper back and breast black; head with predominantly greenish iridescence, occasionally white chin spot, more rarely a paler neck ring. "
Female_Text: "Female. Head and neck vary from buffy brownish to dark brown to essentially black with greenish sheen, except a wide white facial front extending around base of bill; often scattered white feathers elsewhere on head and neck."

Male_Text: "The male's breeding plumage is characterized by a slaty blue bill; black head with purple/green iridescence; black neck, breast, and upper mantle; white flanks and belly; gray-flecked lower mantle; and black vent and undertail region. " DEFINITIVE BASIC "Male. Head and neck black with violet iridescence, some with small white chin spot; upper back and rump black; mantle and scapulars white with coarse blackish-brown vermiculations; tail blackish brown."

". Alternate (breeding)-plumaged malephoto unmistakable with white headphoto , green feathers on loresphoto , forehead and crown-sides. Distinct black spot surrounding the eye and a second black spotphoto in front of wings. Throat and chinphoto dark iridescent blue (M. Johnson pers. comm.), with dark collar connected to upper mantle and back; buff chest, upper belly and flanks. Rest of underparts dark, becoming black-brown on undertail, with white upperwing-covertsphoto , blackish primariesphoto and iridescent purple-blue secondaries broadly tipped whitephoto , and underwing white with grayer flight feathers; bill, legs and feet blue-grey, eyes red-brown." DEFINITIVE BASIC "Deep iridescent cobalt-ultramarine on outer portion of outer web, remainder white. " DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE "Outer webs white and inner webs blackish. Middle scapulars long lanceolate and white on inner web and iridescent cobalt-ultramarine on outer webs."
Female_Text: DEFINITIVE BASIC "Cobalt-ultramarine iridescence of outer webs of secondaries duller than in male, giving way to dark sepia with little or no iridescence on speculum of outer secondaries."

Male_Text: "Adult male in breeding (Definitive Alternate) plumage (observed late fall through midsummer) is distinctivevideo : forehead, crown, and nape pearl blue (light grayish blue); cheeks iridescent pale green, separated from pale blue nape by narrow black and white lines; bill  reddish orange, with large swollen yellow-orange frontal lobe that is outlined with black. "DEFINITIVE BASIC "Male. Forehead, crown, and nape pearl gray, palest anteriorly; pearl-gray area margined with white band from anterior corner of eye to nape; nape feathers elongated (rear feathers sometimes tipped dark gray), forming short, rounded, puffy crest. Swollen frontal lobe of bill outlined in black. Cheek feathers stiff and plush, pale green and iridescent, extending back to white margin of nape where border may be dark."
DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE "Male. Crown to below eye and narrow band along lower margin of frontal lobes black, with some ultramarine-violet iridescence. "

annotation: Monotypic. Howard and Moore (2003) list subspecies H. h. histionicus and H. h. pacificus but validity doubtful.
Male_Text: ". Alternate plumage of malephoto is unmistakablephoto : Body plumage slate bluevideo ; white bandsphoto bands and collarsphoto , bordered with black lines, on chest and neck; large white crescent in front of eye; small white circular photo white circular patch near ear; white vertical stripe along side of neck  ; black streakvideo , bordered by white and amber lines, on top of head; iridescent blue secondaries; brown underwingphoto ; rich dark-slate-blue belly and bluish upper breastvideo ; chestnut-brown flanksphoto ; darker bluish upper backvideo and mantle and white scapulars. " DEFINITIVE BASIC "Male. Dark plumage. Head and neck dark brown to black. White patch in front of eye smaller and divided in 2 by brown eye-stripe; auricular patch retained. Foreneck, breast, sides, flanks, and mantle dark brown. Belly, rump, back (including scapulars), and mantle brown-black to black. Wing dark bluish gray; greater coverts tipped white, creating white band; white flecks on some upperwing coverts. Primaries and rectrices black; secondaries iridescent dark cobalt blue (no. 68), inner-most tertials white with black margins; outermost tertials black. Tail feathers sharply pointe"

"Male. Feathering almost entirely black, with some cobalt-ultramarine gloss; forecrown and nape with large, bold white patches (size and shape vary), that of forecrown squarish or triangular and that of nape rectangular to ovate (Figs. 88 and 90 in Pyle 2008)"

annotation: Formerly considered conspecific with Melanitta fusca.
Formerly considered conspecific with Melanitta fusca.

Male_Text: "Present Sep-May or Sep-Aug. Male uniformly black with some gloss or with cobalt or ultramarine violet sheen. In unworn plumage sheen on head and neck becoming turquoise or emerald on forward mantle. Feathers on sides and flanks long, black terminally with sooty bases and rounded ends when fresh, narrowing to a point when worn. Tail blackish with rounded ends. Wings and wing-lining black, innermost secondaries distally rounded. Underwing primary coverts with a pale sheen similar to inner webs of primaries. See Palmer 1976 for information on variation in texture of body feathering."

DEFINTIVE BASIC "Male. Head and throat black with blue, green, and purple iridescence; large white wedge extends from the eye to the back and top of the head; crown and occipital feathers elongated (> 15 mm) forming broad rounded crest; back and rump black; central scapulars black; outer scapulars white with black edge on outer web; uppertail coverts light gray." DEFINITIVE ALTERNATE "Male. Similar to Definitive Basic female but head darker with some feathers tinged glossy purple; crown and occipital feathers less elongated; white auricular patch averages larger; foreneck, rump, and uppertail coverts grayish dusky."

Males: head and upper neck black, glossed green; large oval (sometimes round) white loral spot between eye and upper mandible; lower neck, upper mantle, sides of breast, and underparts white; thighs mottled brown. Outer webs of elongated feathers on lower flanks broadly edged black. Lower mantle, inner scapulars, back, rump, and uppertail-coverts black. Outer scapulars white centrally, the shorter ones with black outer webs, the longer ones edged black on both webs. Wings and tail of males same as in Definitive Basic plumage (described above); may be sexed accordingly (Palmer 1976, Cramp 1977).

Adult sexes are strongly dimorphic in size and plumage most of the year. Breeding (Definitive Alternate) male has striking pattern of iridescent, purplish-black head with bright, white crescent-patch between bill and eye; brilliant white sides, breast, belly, and secondaries contrasted against black back, wings, and tail. DEFINTIVE ALTERNATE "Male. Head and extreme upper neck black, glossed ultramarine-purple; large white crescent located between eye and side base of bill. Feathers on rear portion of head somewhat elongated, creating a distinctly hooded appearance, which enlarges apparent size of head. Mantle mostly black with some sheen as on head, with black extending down forward sides over front end of folded wing. "

DEFINITIVE BASIC "Male with large, black-bordered, white crest; rest of head and neck black with greenish sheen; back black; breast white with 2 black stripes extending down the foresides; abdomen white; sides and flanks rufous or tawny with vermiculated gray and black; uppertail coverts brownish gray with narrow buffy edging; undertail coverts white, speckled, or mottled dusky. "

DEFINITIVE BASIC "Male. Head and upper neck almost black with glossy greenish sheen, the feathers at rear of crown and on nape slightly elongated and smoothly contoured, without obvious crest, but exaggerating size of head. Nape white or creamy, sharply demarcated from greenish-black head and upper neck. Back primarily glossy black, the center of back to tail medium gray with black shaft streaks, darkening toward tail. Inner scapulars black; lateral (nearest wing) scapulars white or creamy. Sides of body and rump, breast, belly, and undertail coverts creamy white with salmon tinge, the belly sometimes mottled gray; flanks finely vermiculated gray; underwing coverts white, some lesser and median coverts with some gray mottling; distal underwing greater and primary coverts washed grayish." " Malephoto in Definitive Alternate plumagephoto (acquired in autumn) has iridescent, greenish-black headphoto with rounded crest, brilliant white neck, underparts  , and secondariesphoto contrasting with black upperwingsphoto , gray back and tail, and long narrow scarlet-orange billphoto .

In Definitive Alternate (breeding  ) plumage (fall-early summer), malephoto has dark head  that is dark metallic green in the face and black elsewhere; elongated feathers at rear of head form long, shaggy, double-pointed crest  . Dark head bordered below by white collar around neck  , and reddish-brown breast  speckled with black. Tuft of feathers at sides of breast black with large white centers forming band of white patches that lie over forewing at rest. Sides and flanks grayish; remaining underparts white. Back black with dull greenish sheen, outer scapulars white, and rump through tail grayish. Wings black with white patches across inner wing (secondaries and coverts). Bill long, narrow, and serrated with a hooked tip; red with black tip. Feet red-orange." Head, upper neck, and central hindneck black, glossed with green on sides of crown, faintly purple elsewhere. Feathers of occipital region form an erectile 2-part crest. Narrow crescent below eye and remainder of neck white. Mantle, inner and longer scapulars, and sides of breast black; other scapulars predominantly white, vermiculated dark grey on outer web; rump, and flanks vermiculated dark gray and white; uppertail coverts dark ash, tail dark slate, both sometimes with tips and edges of feathers vermiculated like rump. Sides of breast in front of wing with large white spots. Breast cinnamon-rufous to brownish, the feathers in center narrowly bordered with black laterally, on sides of chest more broadly; sides and flanks white, coarsely vermiculated black; belly to undertail coverts white, except some lateral coverts may be vermiculated black.

"Sexes alike. Upperparts brownish olive, becoming more grayish on head and neck; tail much darker, with greenish gloss and pale tip; underparts olive-brown to ashy olive, paler than back; becoming fulvescent on flanks, buffy brown on undertail coverts; center of lower breast and belly variable, from fulvous white, drab, and pale smoky gray to ochraceous white or pale-rufescent brown."
Female_Text: "Sexes alike. Upperparts brownish olive, becoming more grayish on head and neck; tail much darker, with greenish gloss and pale tip; underparts olive-brown to ashy olive, paler than back; becoming fulvescent on flanks, buffy brown on undertail coverts; center of lower breast and belly variable, from fulvous white, drab, and pale smoky gray to ochraceous white or pale-rufescent brown."Scapulars, upperwing coverts, secondaries, back, rump, and uppertail coverts deep olive to dark greenish olive; hindneck and interscapulars slightly more brownish olive; pri-maries olive-brown, edged on outer web with deep olive; rectrices dark greenish olive with an oil-green gloss and rounded tips; central tail feathers (R1) with narrow ashy tips; others with broad white tips (Ridgway and Friedmann 1946, Delacour and Amadon 1973).
