Male_Text: " Glossy black above  with bluish sheen. Whitish flecked black  on neck  , breastphoto and upper belly, with brown flanks and lower belly, and black tailphoto has white band near base. Small red dewlap, white iris  , yellow billvideo and red legs. Sexes alike except in measurements (male has taller horn, longer wings, tail and tarsi) (1); formerly alleged differences now attributed to different ages of birds. Juvenile similar, but duller with truncated horn (first appears at four months old and reaches 3·5 cm tall after 12 months) (1)"
Female_Text: " Glossy black above  with bluish sheen. Whitish flecked black  on neck  , breastphoto and upper belly, with brown flanks and lower belly, and black tailphoto has white band near base. Small red dewlap, white iris  , yellow billvideo and red legs. Sexes alike except in measurements (male has taller horn, longer wings, tail and tarsi) (1); formerly alleged differences now attributed to different ages of birds. Juvenile similar, but duller with truncated horn (first appears at four months old and reaches 3·5 cm tall after 12 months) (1)"

Male_Text: " Feathering of body metallic-iridescent, dark in males, lighter in females, with differences among subspecies" "Male. Head and neck without feathers (see Bare Parts); feathers of remainder of upperparts and underparts glossy Vandyke brown and greenish with little or no mikado brown, the feathers wide and flared at tip, showing iridescent sheen varying from purple to green to red depending on incidence of light, with distinct jet black tips (Pyle 2008, Fig. 153); upperwing greater coverts form distinctive and enlarged speculum, bright coppery brown or "iridescent bronzy vinaceous brown" (Ridgway and Friedmann 1946); rectrices broad, Vandyke brown with indistinct dusky bars basally, distinct broad blackish subterminal bands, and deep russet tips. Primaries and outer 7 secondaries barred black and white (p5 usually has 21 white bars), the medial and inner secondaries progressively more mikado brown and pale pinkish buff mixed with barring; inner two tertials with slight white barring basally. Underwing greater coverts Vandyke brown variably barred white."
Female_Text: "" Feathering of body metallic-iridescent, dark in males, lighter in females, with differences among subspecies"Female. Similar to Definitive Basic male but duller overall; head and neck with downy brown feathering; feathers of remainder of upperparts and underparts duller brown and greenish washed mikado brown, the feathers not as wide and flared, showing duller iridescent sheen, with less-distinct blackish subterminal bands and with deep russet tips (Pyle 2008, Fig. 153); upperwing greater coverts duller coppery brown; rectrices duller and with less distinct blackish subterminal band."

Male_Text: "A large, colorful gamebird with iridescent plumage of blue, green, and bronze and a featherless powder-blue head speckled with red and orange fleshy nodules. Males possess a unique cap-like crown that enlarges during breeding season. The tarsus is deep red; the males also have long, slender spurs that may be in excess of 5 cm with a sharp tip, a feature lacking in females. Beards are absent in both sexes. Wing feathers barred black-and-white with the wing coverts a rich bronze color. Tail feathers a finely barred gray-brown-black ending with a distinctive eye-spot pattern of blue encircled by black with a gold tip. Differentiation between sexes less obvious than Wild Turkey (Meleagris gallopavo) in field conditions due to similar plumage and absence of beards. The remaining body structure is similar to that of Wild Turkey, although approximately half the size." "Feathers are of iridescent green, bronze, blue, and black. Breast feathers possess a narrow band of gold. Tail feathers have distinguishing eye-spot, leading to the species designation of ocellata, from the Latin root oculus for “eye.” Primary flight feathers have black and white barring; secondaries contain more white coloration; wing coverts of bronze. Distinction between the sexes is not as clear as Wild Turkey (Meleagris gallopavo) although female plumage is less brilliantly colored. A distinctly keeled chest is present in adult males."
Female_Text: "A large, colorful gamebird with iridescent plumage of blue, green, and bronze and a featherless powder-blue head speckled with red and orange fleshy nodules. Males possess a unique cap-like crown that enlarges during breeding season. The tarsus is deep red; the males also have long, slender spurs that may be in excess of 5 cm with a sharp tip, a feature lacking in females. Beards are absent in both sexes. Wing feathers barred black-and-white with the wing coverts a rich bronze color. Tail feathers a finely barred gray-brown-black ending with a distinctive eye-spot pattern of blue encircled by black with a gold tip. Differentiation between sexes less obvious than Wild Turkey (Meleagris gallopavo) in field conditions due to similar plumage and absence of beards. The remaining body structure is similar to that of Wild Turkey, although approximately half the size." "Feathers are of iridescent green, bronze, blue, and black. Breast feathers possess a narrow band of gold. Tail feathers have distinguishing eye-spot, leading to the species designation of ocellata, from the Latin root oculus for “eye.” Primary flight feathers have black and white barring; secondaries contain more white coloration; wing coverts of bronze. Distinction between the sexes is not as clear as Wild Turkey (Meleagris gallopavo) although female plumage is less brilliantly colored. A distinctly keeled chest is present in adult males."

Male_Text: "Definitive Basic (adult) male has brownish-gray, reddish-brown, or tawny-brown upperparts, mottled, spotted, and vermiculated with dusky brown, buff, and black. A narrow pale-buff eye-line runs from lores to just behind eye. Back feathers usually have small, heart-shaped white or buff spots. Wings similar to rest of upperparts but usually with pale-buff streaks in feathers; outer webs of primaries barred with whitish and dark brown. Tail has broad pale bands, which, depending on color morph, are light brown, reddish brown, or gray and separated by narrow black bands and fine blackish vermiculations; prominent dark subterminal band of black or blackish brown is complete or nearly complete. On each side of neck is a tuft of long feathers that are most often partially concealed but that can be erected into a ruff; these feathers are usually glossy black with a slight bluish sheen or, less frequently, a rich brown, chestnut, or auburn tipped with black."
Female_Text: "Definitive Basic (adult) male has brownish-gray, reddish-brown, or tawny-brown upperparts, mottled, spotted, and vermiculated with dusky brown, buff, and black. A narrow pale-buff eye-line runs from lores to just behind eye. Back feathers usually have small, heart-shaped white or buff spots. Wings similar to rest of upperparts but usually with pale-buff streaks in feathers; outer webs of primaries barred with whitish and dark brown. Tail has broad pale bands, which, depending on color morph, are light brown, reddish brown, or gray and separated by narrow black bands and fine blackish vermiculations; prominent dark subterminal band of black or blackish brown is complete or nearly complete. On each side of neck is a tuft of long feathers that are most often partially concealed but that can be erected into a ruff; these feathers are usually glossy black with a slight bluish sheen or, less frequently, a rich brown, chestnut, or auburn tipped with black." Female. Similar to male but crest and ruff smaller, feathers of back and rump more washed with brown and with smaller spots, and breast more extensively tawny or hazel (Ridgway and Friedmann 1946). Tail shorter; subterminal dark band usually broken or blotchy, especially central 2 rectrices. One white or whitish dot on dorsal surface of rump feathers; males have 2 or more dots (Roussel and Ouellet 1975).

Male_Text: "Adult male characterized by olive crown, often bordered at sides by white eyebrows and feathers on sides of occiput, immediately above auricular region, elongated to form hornlike or earlike tufts; iridescent purplish head and neck; red orbital region more or less bare; white collar (interrupted or absent in some races); maroon breast, tending toward orange on flanks; golden-yellow mantle; gray rump, with olive or blue tinge and green gloss; pale tail with broad, black bars; pale-gray upperwing coverts; large, round, subterminal pale-buff marks on scapulars; narrow breast feathers with deep indentation and narrow, dark edging; yellowish flanks that contrast with dark breast and belly; and conical spur a little below middle of tarsi (Ridgway and Friedmann 1946, Cramp and Simmons 1980a, Johnsgard 1999). Long tail (41-51 cm; nearly twice as long as wing), flat or slightly compressed, excessively graduated, rectrices (18) tapering toward acuminate or subacuminate tips; always with transverse markings (Ridgway and Friedmann 1946)."

annotation: Monotypic. Formerly known as Common Peafowl.
Male_Text: "A very large, ornately photo colored pheasant. Male (peacock) larger than female (peahen)—100–115 cm long to end of tail, but 195–225 cm long to end of full train; female about 95 cm long. Male also heavier (4–6 kg) than female (2.75–4 kg; Baker 1928). Wingspan 80–130 cm. Fan-shaped set (crest) of spatula-tipped wirelike feathers on top of headphoto , together with brilliant glistening blue neck and breast, and sweeping metallic bronze green train (uppertail-coverts), boldly ocellated with “constellation” of purplish black markings often referred to as eyespots or ocelli, make the cock unmistakable. Female is mostly brown and relatively drab looking, with white bellyphoto . It lacks the sweeping train of adult males, though it does have elongated uppertail-coverts; females are similarly crested. " "The well-known adult plumage is that of the3-yr-old or older male (Howman 1993), readily recognized by its fan-shaped crest of spatula-tipped wirelike feathers, the brilliant glistening blue neck and breast, and the sweeping metallic green, blue, and copper train (uppertail-coverts), which is boldly ocellated with purplish black–centered coppery discs or eyespots (see below). These males usually have about 200 variously elongated uppertail-coverts, each with 1 eyespot (Ali and Ripley 1969, Ridley 1985). Scapulars and upper surface of wings closely barred with black and buff. Primaries and their coverts chestnut (Ali and Ripley 1969). Secondaries and their coverts black, with some iridescent blue and green. Back covered with scalelike bronze green feathers, marked with black and copper (Caum 1933). Breast and belly green, shading to black posteriorly. Rectrices under train gray, with dark and buff mottling on vanes lateral to rachis. Crus covered with buff feathers, marked with thin wavy dark barring."Ocelli, or eyespots, on terminal portion of feathers of train are 40–50 mm long and 30–40 mm wide, have iridescent deep blue center patch, surrounded by roughly concentric areas of bluish green, then copper; barbs extending beyond ocellus are wirelike and not interlocking, and they form a squared-off end on the feather (DAJ). Heavier males have greater proportion of feathers with eyespots (Petrie et al. 1996).
Female_Text: "Adult female lacks the sweeping train, but is crested similar to male; head and nape rusty brown. Throat and below cheeks pale buff. Rest of upperparts brown, faintly mottled; tail dark brown. Lower neck metallic green, fading into dark brown feathers with buffy tips on breast to pure buff color over belly. Primaries brown, with rusty tinge; secondaries darker, with some mottling, especially on coverts; crus like those of male."

Male_Text: "Malephoto unmistakable, with appearance of scaling of different colours over most of dark green plumage, looks blackish over headphoto , neck and mantle, back, rump, tail and wings glossy blue-black, back with yellow-edged hackles and orange-red fringesphoto to lesser and median wing-coverts; multicoloured combvideo (green at base, becoming mauve and finally red on outer edge, which is not toothed) and hackles distinctive (narrow, lanceolate and elongated); single large throat lappetvideo , which is red at base becoming pale yellow, then blue and purple at outer edge. Male lacks distinct eclipse plumage. Femalephoto differs from those of other Gallus by combination of scaly upperparts, barred wings and lack of bold pattern on breast; head and neck dull brown, upperparts blackish brown with buff shaft-streaks and fringes, tail also blackish brown with metallic green and pale buff edges to rectrices, throatphoto whitish, breast pale brown and rear underparts greyish or warm buff, finely scaled darker. Male has single, sharp spur, female usually none. Juvenile resembles female, but young male soon acquires adult male features; first-year male differs from adult in having comb and throat lappet smaller, tail shorter and spurs less developed."
Female_Text: "Malephoto unmistakable, with appearance of scaling of different colours over most of dark green plumage, looks blackish over headphoto , neck and mantle, back, rump, tail and wings glossy blue-black, back with yellow-edged hackles and orange-red fringesphoto to lesser and median wing-coverts; multicoloured combvideo (green at base, becoming mauve and finally red on outer edge, which is not toothed) and hackles distinctive (narrow, lanceolate and elongated); single large throat lappetvideo , which is red at base becoming pale yellow, then blue and purple at outer edge. Male lacks distinct eclipse plumage. Femalephoto differs from those of other Gallus by combination of scaly upperparts, barred wings and lack of bold pattern on breast; head and neck dull brown, upperparts blackish brown with buff shaft-streaks and fringes, tail also blackish brown with metallic green and pale buff edges to rectrices, throatphoto whitish, breast pale brown and rear underparts greyish or warm buff, finely scaled darker. Male has single, sharp spur, female usually none. Juvenile resembles female, but young male soon acquires adult male features; first-year male differs from adult in having comb and throat lappet smaller, tail shorter and spurs less developed."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Francolinus.

Male_Text: "Bill dark gray; underwing coverts white; tail with blue-black subterminal bandphoto ; outer rectrix white on proximal 2/3 of outer vane; rump gray or white. Wings usually with two dark bars on greater coverts and inner secondaries; underwing white. Basic color bluish grayphoto in most, darkest on head and rump, palest on wing-coverts; color bluish black in some, rusty red in a few, and a fraction mostly white or grizzled; many with albinotic feathers almost anywhere. Neck and upper breast suffused with purple and green iridescence, with each feather bifurcated. Irisphoto varies from golden orange to orange to red-orange; orbital skin blue-grey; bill black, cere whitephoto ; legs red or purplish red. Femalevideo slightly duller grey with less neck iridescence." Present primarily Oct–Sep in North American populations. Based on blue-bar or “wild” phenotype. Head, neck and chest dark gray, the neck feathers with glossy yellowish, greenish, and reddish-purple iridescence; mantle bluish-gray; rump white or grayish-white; tail bluish gray with white outer vane to basal 2/3 of outer rectrices and bluish-black subterminal band across all feathers. Upperwing bluish gray with two bluish-black bands across greater coverts and across tertials and innermost six secondaries; primaries and primary coverts brownish gray. Breast and belly dark to medium gray; undertail coverts blackish gray; underwing coverts white. Other phenotypes and intergrades can be similar to wild blue-bar but with variably increased amount of dusky bluish in plumage, or show completely different white and/or red plumages (see Systematics)
Female_Text: "Bill dark gray; underwing coverts white; tail with blue-black subterminal bandphoto ; outer rectrix white on proximal 2/3 of outer vane; rump gray or white. Wings usually with two dark bars on greater coverts and inner secondaries; underwing white. Basic color bluish grayphoto in most, darkest on head and rump, palest on wing-coverts; color bluish black in some, rusty red in a few, and a fraction mostly white or grizzled; many with albinotic feathers almost anywhere. Neck and upper breast suffused with purple and green iridescence, with each feather bifurcated. Irisphoto varies from golden orange to orange to red-orange; orbital skin blue-grey; bill black, cere whitephoto ; legs red or purplish red. Femalevideo slightly duller grey with less neck iridescence." Present primarily Oct–Sep in North American populations. Based on blue-bar or “wild” phenotype. Head, neck and chest dark gray, the neck feathers with glossy yellowish, greenish, and reddish-purple iridescence; mantle bluish-gray; rump white or grayish-white; tail bluish gray with white outer vane to basal 2/3 of outer rectrices and bluish-black subterminal band across all feathers. Upperwing bluish gray with two bluish-black bands across greater coverts and across tertials and innermost six secondaries; primaries and primary coverts brownish gray. Breast and belly dark to medium gray; undertail coverts blackish gray; underwing coverts white. Other phenotypes and intergrades can be similar to wild blue-bar but with variably increased amount of dusky bluish in plumage, or show completely different white and/or red plumages (see Systematics)

Male_Text: "Adult male: Forecrown drab purple; crown and nape gray, glossed with bronze and metallic green. Hindneck, upper back, scapulars, and lesser wing coverts reddish brown, more or less washed with gray. Side of head and upper foreneck gray. Lower back, rump, and uppertail coverts neutral gray. Rectrices brownish gray. Greater wing coverts and inner secondaries grayish brown. Alula, primaries and outer secondaries fuscous, narrowly edged with grayish white. Throat grayish white; breast reddish brown, washed more or less with purple, this wash sometimes extending to the flanks and belly; belly (usually), flanks, and undertail coverts grayish white to pale gray. Axillars and under wing coverts bluish gray. Adult female: Similar to adult male, but duller, and less extensively reddish brown.
Female_Text: "Adult male: Forecrown drab purple; crown and nape gray, glossed with bronze and metallic green. Hindneck, upper back, scapulars, and lesser wing coverts reddish brown, more or less washed with gray. Side of head and upper foreneck gray. Lower back, rump, and uppertail coverts neutral gray. Rectrices brownish gray. Greater wing coverts and inner secondaries grayish brown. Alula, primaries and outer secondaries fuscous, narrowly edged with grayish white. Throat grayish white; breast reddish brown, washed more or less with purple, this wash sometimes extending to the flanks and belly; belly (usually), flanks, and undertail coverts grayish white to pale gray. Axillars and under wing coverts bluish gray. Adult female: Similar to adult male, but duller, and less extensively reddish brown.

Male_Text: "Head purplish to reddish brown; neckvideo feathers blackish with white subterminal spots  , fringes iridescent purple; mantle, back, rump and wing-coverts reddish purple; upper breastphoto and hindneck golden brown with white subterminal spots fringed with coppery gold; lower breast and belly whitish, feathers fringed with purplish brown; primaries black, outermost webs white-fringed; uppertail-coverts purplish brown, undertail-covertsphoto white with dark edges; tail black; eye-ring red, irisvideo pale brown with outer ring of blue or dark purplish; billvideo bright red, tip white or yellowish; legs lavender to purplish red. Femalephoto similar but purplish chestnut replaced by dull brown on back, rump, scapulars and lesser wing-coverts; crown and sides of head less purplish brown; scaly markings less highly glossed. Juvenile male duller than adult with scaling and spotting almost absent; female similar to male but general colour more greyish brown.

"A slate-colouredvideo pigeon, darker on primariesphoto and tail, paler below; headphoto , upper neck and breast suffused with drab purple; nape purple-brown forming a shield or patch; hindneckphoto metallic purplish changing to green or violet, these feathers with dark brown edges producing a scaly effect; iris is a ring of yellow bordered by a ring of scarlet; orbital skinvideo red; billphoto red, white or yellowish at tip; legs red. Female similar to male but duller. Juvenile has feathers fringed with buff; purple and wine red areas of adult are reddish brown, while grey areas are replaced with brownish slate."
Female_Text: "A slate-colouredvideo pigeon, darker on primariesphoto and tail, paler below; headphoto , upper neck and breast suffused with drab purple; nape purple-brown forming a shield or patch; hindneckphoto metallic purplish changing to green or violet, these feathers with dark brown edges producing a scaly effect; iris is a ring of yellow bordered by a ring of scarlet; orbital skinvideo red; billphoto red, white or yellowish at tip; legs red. Female similar to male but duller. Juvenile has feathers fringed with buff; purple and wine red areas of adult are reddish brown, while grey areas are replaced with brownish slate."

Male_Text: "Adults uniformly dark slate-gray (appearing black at a distance) with a contrasting white cap on top half of head, yellowish-white iris, and patch of iridescent dark greenish feathers with black edges on sides of neck and uppermost back. Bill red with white tip. Sexes similar, although female typically duller overall with more grayish crown, brownish tinge to upperparts, and dull (almost colorless) neck patch."

"Head purple-gray (often paler, even whitish, on chin and throat); hindneck with white crescent subtended by distinct patch of greenish-bronze iridescent feathers, each sharply edged with dark, producing squamate pattern; remaining upperparts varying shades of gray to brownish gray (sometimes glossed with bronze); rump and wing coverts (edged whitish) slightly paler. Underparts contrast somewhat paler against upperparts; pinkish buff to purplish gray on breast, becoming paler (more light purplish buff) toward belly and whitish on undertail. Tail dark gray at base and pale gray to gray-brown on distal half, these areas divided by a dark band; because upper and undertail coverts cover base of tail, how-ever, tail appears dark-based with broad, pale band across tip. Bill yellow with black tip (all yellow Costa Rica southward); feet yellow. Sexes similar in appearance but females duller overall, with narrower white crescent and less extensive iridescence on hindneck." Male. Head of male light purple or vinaceous to pinkish brown to dark purple, darkest dorsally, blending into lighter purple-pink or even ash gray in malar and throat region. Conspicuous white crescent on nape; bordered posteriorly on hindneck by large area of bronzy, iridescent dark green, with individual feathers appearing distinctive, extending onto upper back. Back dark olive brown to grayish brown, perhaps with slight dark green tinge on anterior back (RBCM), blending into a neutral gray or deeper blue gray on rump and uppertail coverts. Breast is purplish pink to vinaceous, blending posteriorly to a light gray, or whitish, on belly, sides, flanks, and undertail coverts, and may blend anteriorly to a lighter grayish chin. Basal half of upper surface of tail neutral gray (much of this hidden under uppertail coverts), bordered by distinct dark gray to dull black broad band on midtail; distal half of tail pale gray to brownish gray, perhaps palest on outermost rectrices. Undersurface of rectrices distinctly lighter than upper surface. Upper wing coverts bluish gray to brownish gray, with white to buff feather edging, especially on greater coverts and tertials. Brownish-gray secondaries blending distally to darker gray and then dusky to dark reddish-brown or brownish-black primaries, primary coverts, and alula. Median- and greater coverts, tertials, and scapulars contrast with paler back. Underwing pale neutral gray.
Female_Text: "Head purple-gray (often paler, even whitish, on chin and throat); hindneck with white crescent subtended by distinct patch of greenish-bronze iridescent feathers, each sharply edged with dark, producing squamate pattern; remaining upperparts varying shades of gray to brownish gray (sometimes glossed with bronze); rump and wing coverts (edged whitish) slightly paler. Underparts contrast somewhat paler against upperparts; pinkish buff to purplish gray on breast, becoming paler (more light purplish buff) toward belly and whitish on undertail. Tail dark gray at base and pale gray to gray-brown on distal half, these areas divided by a dark band; because upper and undertail coverts cover base of tail, how-ever, tail appears dark-based with broad, pale band across tip. Bill yellow with black tip (all yellow Costa Rica southward); feet yellow. Sexes similar in appearance but females duller overall, with narrower white crescent and less extensive iridescence on hindneck." Female. Similar to male except general coloration duller or paler; more brownish and grayish dorsally, especially head and neck, breast less vinaceous (difference appearing in Basic I plumage; see above); crescent on nape narrower, relatively little iridescence on hindneck less greenish and less ex-tensive.

Male_Text: "Adult plumagevideo reminiscent of juvenile P. fasciata; present species has proportionately longer tail; head, neck and underparts drab vinaceous, underpartsphoto tinged with pink; hindneck metallic green or bronze; rest of upperparts brownish grey; primaries dusky; basal portion of tail grey, terminal portion brownish grey, with dusky slate band across centre; undertail-coverts brownish white; iris brilliant orange; orbital skin red; bill and cere black; legs red. Female similar but back, scapulars and wing-coverts suffused with olive or brown; underparts more vina­ceous, metallic hindneck less brilliant. Juvenile with grey of head and neck suffused with brown; foreneck to breast greyish brown passing to fawn or cinnamon on belly."
Female_Text: "Adult plumagevideo reminiscent of juvenile P. fasciata; present species has proportionately longer tail; head, neck and underparts drab vinaceous, underpartsphoto tinged with pink; hindneck metallic green or bronze; rest of upperparts brownish grey; primaries dusky; basal portion of tail grey, terminal portion brownish grey, with dusky slate band across centre; undertail-coverts brownish white; iris brilliant orange; orbital skin red; bill and cere black; legs red. Female similar but back, scapulars and wing-coverts suffused with olive or brown; underparts more vina­ceous, metallic hindneck less brilliant. Juvenile with grey of head and neck suffused with brown; foreneck to breast greyish brown passing to fawn or cinnamon on belly."

Male_Text: "In all plumages, a key feature is the scaling on underparts, extending from throat to lower breast, with finer scaling on the crown and nape; this scaling is sometimes faint on immatures and is not noticeable at a distance. Bill distinctly bicolored, with a dark tip and a bright orange-red-pink base. Bright-chestnut primaries and wing-lining visible in flight. Throughout species' range, adult upperparts vary from pale grayish brown to medium dark brown; forehead, face, sides of neck, breast, and underparts pinkish brown to pinkish gray. Crown, nape, and hindneck vary from bluish gray to grayish pink. Wing-coverts, tertials, and outer secondaries gray or pinkish brown with dark iridescent spotting; scapulars and inner secondaries without spotting. Irides dark red, orange, or pinkish. Feet and legs pinkish, but male's become brighter during breeding. Female plumage grayer overall and breast scaling less distinct, but may extend farther ventrally. Nape and hindcrown of female grayish brown, but bluish in male. " The forehead, auriculars, throat, breast, and belly rosy pink, pinkish gray, or mauve. Crown, nape, and hindneck blue-gray or pinkish gray. Prominent dark scaling across breast, with finer scaling on crown and nape. Breast-scaling caused by dark feather centers and margins, upper scaling due to dark feather margins only (Goodwin 1983b). Upperparts grayish brown or drab brown. Lesser, median, and greater wing coverts, tertials, and outer secondaries are pinkish or pale gray with violet or blue-violet iridescent spots that usually appear black. No spotting on scapulars or inner secondaries. Primaries chestnut with blackish outer webs and broad dark-brown to black tips. Underwing and axillaries bright chestnut. Central pair of rectrices grayish brown or drab brown, outer rectrices black with increasing amount of white at tips. Under tail-coverts grayish with broad pale or white tips. Sexes dimorphic. Male deeper vinaceous pink on forehead and neck and bluish gray on nape and hindcrown. Wing-spotting iridescent dark blue purplish. Female lacks rosy color to head and neck; in general, paler underneath than male. Wing-spotting paler coppery brown in female
Female_Text: "In all plumages, a key feature is the scaling on underparts, extending from throat to lower breast, with finer scaling on the crown and nape; this scaling is sometimes faint on immatures and is not noticeable at a distance. Bill distinctly bicolored, with a dark tip and a bright orange-red-pink base. Bright-chestnut primaries and wing-lining visible in flight. Throughout species' range, adult upperparts vary from pale grayish brown to medium dark brown; forehead, face, sides of neck, breast, and underparts pinkish brown to pinkish gray. Crown, nape, and hindneck vary from bluish gray to grayish pink. Wing-coverts, tertials, and outer secondaries gray or pinkish brown with dark iridescent spotting; scapulars and inner secondaries without spotting. Irides dark red, orange, or pinkish. Feet and legs pinkish, but male's become brighter during breeding. Female plumage grayer overall and breast scaling less distinct, but may extend farther ventrally. Nape and hindcrown of female grayish brown, but bluish in male. " The forehead, auriculars, throat, breast, and belly rosy pink, pinkish gray, or mauve. Crown, nape, and hindneck blue-gray or pinkish gray. Prominent dark scaling across breast, with finer scaling on crown and nape. Breast-scaling caused by dark feather centers and margins, upper scaling due to dark feather margins only (Goodwin 1983b). Upperparts grayish brown or drab brown. Lesser, median, and greater wing coverts, tertials, and outer secondaries are pinkish or pale gray with violet or blue-violet iridescent spots that usually appear black. No spotting on scapulars or inner secondaries. Primaries chestnut with blackish outer webs and broad dark-brown to black tips. Underwing and axillaries bright chestnut. Central pair of rectrices grayish brown or drab brown, outer rectrices black with increasing amount of white at tips. Under tail-coverts grayish with broad pale or white tips. Sexes dimorphic. Male deeper vinaceous pink on forehead and neck and bluish gray on nape and hindcrown. Wing-spotting iridescent dark blue purplish. Female lacks rosy color to head and neck; in general, paler underneath than male. Wing-spotting paler coppery brown in female

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Claravis.

Male_Text: "Foreheadphoto with stiffened hair-like feathers, dull black to greyish black; rest of crownphoto and napevideo drab brown becoming grey at sides and rear; metallic bronze or bronze-green on side and hindneck; small nape crest; reddish buff on median line of throat and broad malar stripe extending across face and below eye; rest of face, neck and underpartsphoto grey; iridescent reddish purple mantlevideo and lesser wing-covertsphoto becoming bluish purple on scapulars, lower mantle and inner secondaries; primariesvideo chestnut with blackish inner webs; rest of upperparts and tail greenish black with some purple iridescence; bellyvideo and flanks chestnut; iris red with edge of eyelids scarlet; orbital skin grey; bill black; legs and feet pink. Female sometimes indistinguishable from male, but occasionally paler and browner than male on neck and belly. Juvenile duller than adult, most feathers edged rust."
Female_Text: "Foreheadphoto with stiffened hair-like feathers, dull black to greyish black; rest of crownphoto and napevideo drab brown becoming grey at sides and rear; metallic bronze or bronze-green on side and hindneck; small nape crest; reddish buff on median line of throat and broad malar stripe extending across face and below eye; rest of face, neck and underpartsphoto grey; iridescent reddish purple mantlevideo and lesser wing-covertsphoto becoming bluish purple on scapulars, lower mantle and inner secondaries; primariesvideo chestnut with blackish inner webs; rest of upperparts and tail greenish black with some purple iridescence; bellyvideo and flanks chestnut; iris red with edge of eyelids scarlet; orbital skin grey; bill black; legs and feet pink. Female sometimes indistinguishable from male, but occasionally paler and browner than male on neck and belly. Juvenile duller than adult, most feathers edged rust."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts rufous-chestnut, paler on the forecrown and on the wings; nape, sides of neck, and back glossed with reddish purple. Throat and sides of the head pinkish cinnamon; sides of the head, below the auriculars, crossed by a reddish purple stripe. Breast vinaceous-fawn, turning to buff on belly. Sides and flanks cinnamon-buff to clay. Undertail coverts cinnamon-buff. Underside of wing cinnamon-rufous."
Female_Text: "Adult female: Similar in pattern to male, but duller. Forecrown and sides of head dull cinnamon; sides of the head, below the auriculars, crossed by an olive stripe. Most of upperparts otherwise olive; primaries and greater wing coverts dusky, edged with cinnamon. Rectrices olive, except for blacker outer rectrices. Throat buffy white. Breast dull cinnamon to wood brown, changing to buff on belly; undertail coverts more cinnamon. Sides and flanks olive-brown. Underside of wing dull cinnamon-buff to dull rufous."

Male_Text: "Forehead and face greyish white becoming greyish mauve on crown, then iridescent purple or amethyst on hindneck and mantle; rest of upperparts  brown suffused with purple iridescence, absent from primaries, outer secondaries and outer wing-coverts; throat and breast white tinged purple; pale malar stripe running to below the eye; flanks buff, belly  and undertail-coverts white; underwing mottled white, black and chestnut; iris orange-brown or yellow-brown; bill and cere carmine; feet and legs coral red. Female duller; purple gloss only on hindneck and upper back; face and throat pale grey; neck and breast brownish with purple tinting; iris brown."
Female_Text: "Forehead and face greyish white becoming greyish mauve on crown, then iridescent purple or amethyst on hindneck and mantle; rest of upperparts  brown suffused with purple iridescence, absent from primaries, outer secondaries and outer wing-coverts; throat and breast white tinged purple; pale malar stripe running to below the eye; flanks buff, belly  and undertail-coverts white; underwing mottled white, black and chestnut; iris orange-brown or yellow-brown; bill and cere carmine; feet and legs coral red. Female duller; purple gloss only on hindneck and upper back; face and throat pale grey; neck and breast brownish with purple tinting; iris brown."

Male_Text: This is a beautiful quail-dove when seen well, being dark gray above with a conspicuous blue and purple iridescence, becoming paler below, with a bright white forehead and paler gray crown; seen briefly, however, the overall impression is simply of a mid-sized, largely dark pigeon. " Foreheadphoto greyish white merging gradually to grey on crown, occiput and nape; slight purplish iridescencevideo on back of head; throatvideo medium grey becoming darker on breast and cream on centre of belly; rufous vent and undertail-coverts; chestnut underwing, basal parts of inner webs and narrow fringe on outer primary webs; glossy purple mantlephoto and sides of breast becoming bluish purple on lower back, rump and uppertail-coverts; dark brownish grey, tail grey. Female slightly duller with reduced bloom during breeding season (2); also shorter-winged and shorter-legged than males (3). Juvenile has brownish-grey forehead and pale grey throat; duller and dark brown upperparts fringed buff, and chestnut-brown underparts; orbital skin dull reddish purple, and legs and feet dull red (2). "
Female_Text: This is a beautiful quail-dove when seen well, being dark gray above with a conspicuous blue and purple iridescence, becoming paler below, with a bright white forehead and paler gray crown; seen briefly, however, the overall impression is simply of a mid-sized, largely dark pigeon. " Foreheadphoto greyish white merging gradually to grey on crown, occiput and nape; slight purplish iridescencevideo on back of head; throatvideo medium grey becoming darker on breast and cream on centre of belly; rufous vent and undertail-coverts; chestnut underwing, basal parts of inner webs and narrow fringe on outer primary webs; glossy purple mantlephoto and sides of breast becoming bluish purple on lower back, rump and uppertail-coverts; dark brownish grey, tail grey. Female slightly duller with reduced bloom during breeding season (2); also shorter-winged and shorter-legged than males (3). Juvenile has brownish-grey forehead and pale grey throat; duller and dark brown upperparts fringed buff, and chestnut-brown underparts; orbital skin dull reddish purple, and legs and feet dull red (2). "

Male_Text: " Crown, nape and head-sides slate-grey, with striking white forecrownvideo , neck-sides  suffused reddish purple or violet, this colour sometimes extending onto and across breast, upperparts slightly darker with a metallic purplish-blue sheen, underpartsphoto grey, becoming rufous on lower belly and undertail-coverts  ; eyes red, bill reddish becoming paler, more yellowish at tip, and legs and feet reddish. Juvenile browner than adult, lacking reddish or purple sheen on mantle and neck sides. Distinguished from formerly conspecific but wholly allopatric G. caniceps by white forehead; also darker overall, with richer and very lustrous iridescence on mantle and back (1). No other quail-dove on Hispaniola has white forecown."
Female_Text: " Crown, nape and head-sides slate-grey, with striking white forecrownvideo , neck-sides  suffused reddish purple or violet, this colour sometimes extending onto and across breast, upperparts slightly darker with a metallic purplish-blue sheen, underpartsphoto grey, becoming rufous on lower belly and undertail-coverts  ; eyes red, bill reddish becoming paler, more yellowish at tip, and legs and feet reddish. Juvenile browner than adult, lacking reddish or purple sheen on mantle and neck sides. Distinguished from formerly conspecific but wholly allopatric G. caniceps by white forehead; also darker overall, with richer and very lustrous iridescence on mantle and back (1). No other quail-dove on Hispaniola has white forecown."

Male_Text: "Chestnut-brown abovephoto , with bronze-green or amethyst iridescence on crown, nape and hindneck; mantlevideo , back, rump and inner wing-coverts with purple or purplish-red iridescence  ; inner secondaries and tips of primaries dusky olive brown; throat white, deep brown malar stripe below broad white facial stripe  from bill to and beyond eye to nape; sides of neck and breast mauve-pink or pinkish grey becoming white on belly and dusky brown on flanks; iris red, orange or yellow; orbital skin red; bill dull red at base, brownish at tip; legs and feet red or pinkish. Femalevideo similar, but malar stripe duller; wing-coverts, rear scapulars and edges of rectrices greyish brown; darker below, notably on breast. Juvenile very different from adult: above rufous-cinnamon; cinnamon-buff tips on feathers of scapulars, interscapulars and wing-coverts; head and neck duller than adult, with pale-tipped feathers; breast and foreneck drab, edged cinnamon."
Female_Text: "Chestnut-brown abovephoto , with bronze-green or amethyst iridescence on crown, nape and hindneck; mantlevideo , back, rump and inner wing-coverts with purple or purplish-red iridescence  ; inner secondaries and tips of primaries dusky olive brown; throat white, deep brown malar stripe below broad white facial stripe  from bill to and beyond eye to nape; sides of neck and breast mauve-pink or pinkish grey becoming white on belly and dusky brown on flanks; iris red, orange or yellow; orbital skin red; bill dull red at base, brownish at tip; legs and feet red or pinkish. Femalevideo similar, but malar stripe duller; wing-coverts, rear scapulars and edges of rectrices greyish brown; darker below, notably on breast. Juvenile very different from adult: above rufous-cinnamon; cinnamon-buff tips on feathers of scapulars, interscapulars and wing-coverts; head and neck duller than adult, with pale-tipped feathers; breast and foreneck drab, edged cinnamon."

Male_Text: " Body plumage is an overall brown with a green-dominated iridescence and shades of blue and violet on the nape, neck, and upper back, cinnamon-red flight feathers, and a distinctive horizontal white line (bridle) below the eye. Sexes similar, but female reportedly less iridescent." n general, adult is brown with reddish patches in the wings. The distinctive field mark is a white horizontal stripe below the eye, extending from the hinge of the beak across the auriculars to the edge of the nape (1). The crown is brown, but transitions to iridescence down the nape and neck, and into the upper back feathers. Iridescencephoto is primarily greenish on the head, nape, and upper neck, transitioning to blues and violets down the neck and upper back. The female is reported to have slightly less iridescence (7, 1). The back feathering is an overall brown with some lighter edging and traces of iridescence. The tail feathers are dark brownish-gray with black feather shafts. The primary and outermost secondary feathers are a cinnamon-red with brownish-red feather shaftsphoto . The leading and trailing edges near the feather tips transition to brown. The innermost secondary feathers also transition to brown. Similarly, the primary coverts are cinnamon-red with brown edging at the tip; all other wing coverts are brown. Ventrally, there is a small white patch on the throat that transitions to brown on the breast, then to a cream belly with a buffy wash on the thighs
Female_Text: " Body plumage is an overall brown with a green-dominated iridescence and shades of blue and violet on the nape, neck, and upper back, cinnamon-red flight feathers, and a distinctive horizontal white line (bridle) below the eye. Sexes similar, but female reportedly less iridescent." n general, adult is brown with reddish patches in the wings. The distinctive field mark is a white horizontal stripe below the eye, extending from the hinge of the beak across the auriculars to the edge of the nape (1). The crown is brown, but transitions to iridescence down the nape and neck, and into the upper back feathers. Iridescencephoto is primarily greenish on the head, nape, and upper neck, transitioning to blues and violets down the neck and upper back. The female is reported to have slightly less iridescence (7, 1). The back feathering is an overall brown with some lighter edging and traces of iridescence. The tail feathers are dark brownish-gray with black feather shafts. The primary and outermost secondary feathers are a cinnamon-red with brownish-red feather shaftsphoto . The leading and trailing edges near the feather tips transition to brown. The innermost secondary feathers also transition to brown. Similarly, the primary coverts are cinnamon-red with brown edging at the tip; all other wing coverts are brown. Ventrally, there is a small white patch on the throat that transitions to brown on the breast, then to a cream belly with a buffy wash on the thighs

Male_Text: "Forehead white with grey or buff shading, becoming grey on crown then purple on hindcrown, nape and neck; upper­parts dark olive-brown; white throat and facial stripes sometimes suffused buff; conspicuous black malar stripe; white or buffish white belly with dark reddish buff flanks and undertail-coverts; underwing chestnut; rest of plumage olive brown or purplish brown; greenish or purplish iridescence on neck, breast and upperparts; iris brown; orbital skin purplish red; bill and cere black; feet and legs reddish. Sexes alike, but female often has buff forehead and little or no grey on crown. Juvenile similar to adults but feathers fringed rusty and lack iridescence."
Female_Text: "Forehead white with grey or buff shading, becoming grey on crown then purple on hindcrown, nape and neck; upper­parts dark olive-brown; white throat and facial stripes sometimes suffused buff; conspicuous black malar stripe; white or buffish white belly with dark reddish buff flanks and undertail-coverts; underwing chestnut; rest of plumage olive brown or purplish brown; greenish or purplish iridescence on neck, breast and upperparts; iris brown; orbital skin purplish red; bill and cere black; feet and legs reddish. Sexes alike, but female often has buff forehead and little or no grey on crown. Juvenile similar to adults but feathers fringed rusty and lack iridescence."

Male_Text: "Present primarily November–October in North American populations. Upperparts, upperwings, and tail brownish olive to pale brown, the forehead paler, the crown and nape with iridescent purple sheen, and the underside of the tail blackish with white tips on all rectrices except central pair; primaries and secondaries broad and grayish brown with thin white margins to outer webs near tips when fresh, the outer primary (p10) notched and substantially attenuated at tip. Chin and throat light cream, becoming light brown on foreneck, breast, and sides, the breast sometimes slightly tinged purplish; belly paler, becoming white on undertail coverts. Underwing median and lesser underwing coverts distinctively chestnut to rust-red, the underwing greater coverts paler and the underwing primary coverts washed grayish distally." Male and Female very similar in appearance although purple iridescence on the neck averages brighter and pinkish tinge on the breast averages darker in adult males; considerable overlap in the coloration of adult males and females (8).
Female_Text: "Present primarily November–October in North American populations. Upperparts, upperwings, and tail brownish olive to pale brown, the forehead paler, the crown and nape with iridescent purple sheen, and the underside of the tail blackish with white tips on all rectrices except central pair; primaries and secondaries broad and grayish brown with thin white margins to outer webs near tips when fresh, the outer primary (p10) notched and substantially attenuated at tip. Chin and throat light cream, becoming light brown on foreneck, breast, and sides, the breast sometimes slightly tinged purplish; belly paler, becoming white on undertail coverts. Underwing median and lesser underwing coverts distinctively chestnut to rust-red, the underwing greater coverts paler and the underwing primary coverts washed grayish distally." Male and Female very similar in appearance although purple iridescence on the neck averages brighter and pinkish tinge on the breast averages darker in adult males; considerable overlap in the coloration of adult males and females (8).

Male_Text: "Adult male characterized by olive crown, often bordered at sides by white eyebrows and feathers on sides of occiput, immediately above auricular region, elongated to form hornlike or earlike tufts; iridescent purplish head and neck; red orbital region mo
Female_Text: "Adult male characterized by olive crown, often bordered at sides by white eyebrows and feathers on sides of occiput, immediately above auricular region, elongated to form hornlike or earlike tufts; iridescent purplish head and neck; red orbital region mo

Male_Text: "Forehead pinkish grey; crown and nape dark brown; throat white; breast vinaceous grey becoming iridescent greyish purple on hindneck; bellyphoto vinaceous, undertail-coverts white; upperparts olive-brown with green or purple iridescence on mantle and inner wing-coverts; primaries and rectrices darker than rest of upperparts; outer two rectrices white-tipped; underwing-coverts chestnut, some chestnut on underside of primaries; iris greyish yellow, yellow to greenish yellow; orbital skin grey but dull red at posterior angle and loral region; legs and feet red; bill black, lores red. Female darker. Races differ mainly in coloration; rufinucha paler with purpler breast, rusty buff nape and crown contrasting with pale forehead; cerviniventrisvideo similar to previous race but stronger purplish pink on breast."
Female_Text: "Forehead pinkish grey; crown and nape dark brown; throat white; breast vinaceous grey becoming iridescent greyish purple on hindneck; bellyphoto vinaceous, undertail-coverts white; upperparts olive-brown with green or purple iridescence on mantle and inner wing-coverts; primaries and rectrices darker than rest of upperparts; outer two rectrices white-tipped; underwing-coverts chestnut, some chestnut on underside of primaries; iris greyish yellow, yellow to greenish yellow; orbital skin grey but dull red at posterior angle and loral region; legs and feet red; bill black, lores red. Female darker. Races differ mainly in coloration; rufinucha paler with purpler breast, rusty buff nape and crown contrasting with pale forehead; cerviniventrisvideo similar to previous race but stronger purplish pink on breast."

Male_Text: "Quail-Doves (Geotrygon) are heavy bodied doves with a short tail and short tarsi. One of the most distinctive features of White-faced Quail-Dove is the white face: the face is whitish, and the crown and nape are blue gray. The upperparts otherwise generally are dark rufous, with a purple gloss on the back. There also is a pattern of distinct dark furrows on each side of the neck. The underparts are pale cinnamon. The sexes of White-faced Quail-Dove are similar."Adult: Sexes similar. Forecrown dull white or grayish white, shading through pale gray on the crown to deeper gray on the rear crown and nape; center of the nape darker and more brownish. Hindneck cinnamon brown; sides of neck cinnamon brown, but the feathers with paler tips; also, a series of parallel dark furrows on each side of the neck. Rest of upperparts chestnut, the back (especially the upper back) glossed with bluish violet. Primary coverts and primaries dusky grayish brown or dark dusky. Lower sides of the head pale grayish buff. Chin and throat pale buff. Breast buffy grayish, becoming paler, more cinnamon buff, on belly; undertail coverts dull cinnamon buff. Underwing coverts rufescent.
Female_Text: "Quail-Doves (Geotrygon) are heavy bodied doves with a short tail and short tarsi. One of the most distinctive features of White-faced Quail-Dove is the white face: the face is whitish, and the crown and nape are blue gray. The upperparts otherwise generally are dark rufous, with a purple gloss on the back. There also is a pattern of distinct dark furrows on each side of the neck. The underparts are pale cinnamon. The sexes of White-faced Quail-Dove are similar."Adult: Sexes similar. Forecrown dull white or grayish white, shading through pale gray on the crown to deeper gray on the rear crown and nape; center of the nape darker and more brownish. Hindneck cinnamon brown; sides of neck cinnamon brown, but the feathers with paler tips; also, a series of parallel dark furrows on each side of the neck. Rest of upperparts chestnut, the back (especially the upper back) glossed with bluish violet. Primary coverts and primaries dusky grayish brown or dark dusky. Lower sides of the head pale grayish buff. Chin and throat pale buff. Breast buffy grayish, becoming paler, more cinnamon buff, on belly; undertail coverts dull cinnamon buff. Underwing coverts rufescent.

Male_Text: "Crownphoto slate grey becoming darker towards middle and rear, but paler on foreheadphoto ; upperpartsvideo chestnut becoming purplish on upper back then olivaceous with greenish gloss on lower back; remiges dusky sometimes tinged chestnut; conspicuous black malar stripe; thin black short postocular line and thin black loral stripe; chin and upper throat buffy white deepening to rufous on foreneck, chest and sides and becoming pale cinnamon buff on belly; flanks and undertail-coverts cinnamon brown; iris brownish orange, orbital skin red; cere and bill black; legs and feet purplish red. Female often indistinguishable from male, but usually darker on breast and grey of crown duller. Juvenile has upperparts including crown brown, with darker crown and occiput; rufescent wing-coverts, dusky subterminal bar or spot on wing-coverts and scapulars; foreneck, breast and sides similar to adult but with dull black bars."
Female_Text: "Crownphoto slate grey becoming darker towards middle and rear, but paler on foreheadphoto ; upperpartsvideo chestnut becoming purplish on upper back then olivaceous with greenish gloss on lower back; remiges dusky sometimes tinged chestnut; conspicuous black malar stripe; thin black short postocular line and thin black loral stripe; chin and upper throat buffy white deepening to rufous on foreneck, chest and sides and becoming pale cinnamon buff on belly; flanks and undertail-coverts cinnamon brown; iris brownish orange, orbital skin red; cere and bill black; legs and feet purplish red. Female often indistinguishable from male, but usually darker on breast and grey of crown duller. Juvenile has upperparts including crown brown, with darker crown and occiput; rufescent wing-coverts, dusky subterminal bar or spot on wing-coverts and scapulars; foreneck, breast and sides similar to adult but with dull black bars."

Male_Text: "In males, forehead fawn, tinged with gray and fading anteriorly; crown and occiput mauve-pink to purplish drab; nape similar to crown but paler, more grayish; scapulars, proximal secondaries, and inner wing coverts dark buff-brown, light sepia, or Saccardo umber, sometimes tinged reddish; back similar, becoming grayer posteriorly, rump dull neutral to brownish gray; uppertail coverts and middle 2 rectrices brownish gray, slightly rufous; remaining rectrices slate gray, with broad pale-gray to white tips and subterminal band of brownish slate to slate black; alulae and primary coverts dull black; primaries dull black with narrow, pale edges that become broader at tip; outer marginal, lesser, median, and greater wing coverts mostly white (with gray bases), becoming completely white on outermost feathers; together these white feathers form a conspicuous white patch on wing visible when wing folded or spread; middle and outer secondaries dull black with distal portion of outer web and tip margined white; sides of neck and head, chin, throat, foreneck, and breast wood-brown, paler anteriorly and tinged with pink toward breast; sides of neck glossed with reddish-, yellowish-, or greenish-bronze sheen; conspicuous patch or streak across lower ear coverts, black or blue-black with steel-blue sheen; underparts posterior to breast neutral gray, fading to whitish in anal region; undersurface of tail black, with broad white terminal band; sides, flanks, and axillaries neutral gray, becoming slightly paler on undersurface of wings (Ridgway 1916, Oberholser 1974, Goodwin 1983b)."
Female_Text: "Female almost indistinguishable from male. Occasionally slightly duller, with less sheen, especially on crown, occiput, sides of neck, rump, and anterior underparts (Ridgway 1916, Oberholser 1974, Goodwin 1983b)."

Male_Text: "Foreheadphoto , sides of neck and head cinnamon-coloured, a little paler and more buffy on the chin, and darker crown; occiput nape and hindneck brownish grey; metallic purple gloss on lateral and lower portions of hindneck; back, scapulars, secondaries and median portion of rump reddish brown; chest and underparts lighter buff-brown; distal wing-coverts, alula, primary coverts and sides of rumpphoto grey; large rounded black spotsphoto on proximal secondaries and larger wing-coverts; outer secondaries dusky edged with grey which merges into white; dark ­violet-blue streaks above and below ear-­coverts: these streaks appear black from a distance; central tail feathers reddish brown, lateral rectrices grey with rufous outer webs; outermost pair grey with rufous outer web and white terminal band; black subterminal tail bar; bill black; feet and legs red; iris dark brown to brownish black. Female paler with back less reddish. Juvenile resembles female but lacks iridescent patches on neck and has buff fringes to all back and wings feathers. Race zenaida darker, with terminal band on outermost pair of rectrices bluish grey rather than white, and no white margins to wing spots; salvadorii is greyish or olive brown on back and only slightly tinged red, forehead and crown greyish mauve, tips of outer tail feathers greyish white."
Female_Text: "Foreheadphoto , sides of neck and head cinnamon-coloured, a little paler and more buffy on the chin, and darker crown; occiput nape and hindneck brownish grey; metallic purple gloss on lateral and lower portions of hindneck; back, scapulars, secondaries and median portion of rump reddish brown; chest and underparts lighter buff-brown; distal wing-coverts, alula, primary coverts and sides of rumpphoto grey; large rounded black spotsphoto on proximal secondaries and larger wing-coverts; outer secondaries dusky edged with grey which merges into white; dark ­violet-blue streaks above and below ear-­coverts: these streaks appear black from a distance; central tail feathers reddish brown, lateral rectrices grey with rufous outer webs; outermost pair grey with rufous outer web and white terminal band; black subterminal tail bar; bill black; feet and legs red; iris dark brown to brownish black. Female paler with back less reddish. Juvenile resembles female but lacks iridescent patches on neck and has buff fringes to all back and wings feathers. Race zenaida darker, with terminal band on outermost pair of rectrices bluish grey rather than white, and no white margins to wing spots; salvadorii is greyish or olive brown on back and only slightly tinged red, forehead and crown greyish mauve, tips of outer tail feathers greyish white."

Male_Text: "Crownphoto and nape bluish grey; rest of head, neck and breast pinkish to purplish buff, shading to buff or cream on belly into undertail-coverts; upperpartsphoto olive-brown with black markingsphoto on wings; primariesvideo and outer secondaries black with narrow white edges; two black facial streaks, one behind and the other below the eye, the upper spot is dull black and the lower iridescent blue; iridescentphoto pink or bronzy patch on each side of neck; central tail feathers olive-brown, next pair grey with black central bar, the rest grey with black central bar and terminal white patch; iris brown to reddish brown; orbital skinphoto bluish or grey; bill dark grey to black; legs and feet red. Female similar but duller; head, neck and underparts less pinkish, occiput less bluish grey, metallic reflections on side of neck less brilliant and extended. Juvenile  has wing and tail feathers similar to adults; foreneck and breast dull light buffy brownish, feathers with pale terminal margins; no metallic reflections on side of neck; wing-coverts and scapulars also, with paler margins, lesser and median coverts sometimes with small medio-terminal wedge-shaped streaks of dull white. Racesphoto 3  differ in coloration."
Female_Text: "Crownphoto and nape bluish grey; rest of head, neck and breast pinkish to purplish buff, shading to buff or cream on belly into undertail-coverts; upperpartsphoto olive-brown with black markingsphoto on wings; primariesvideo and outer secondaries black with narrow white edges; two black facial streaks, one behind and the other below the eye, the upper spot is dull black and the lower iridescent blue; iridescentphoto pink or bronzy patch on each side of neck; central tail feathers olive-brown, next pair grey with black central bar, the rest grey with black central bar and terminal white patch; iris brown to reddish brown; orbital skinphoto bluish or grey; bill dark grey to black; legs and feet red. Juvenile  has wing and tail feathers similar to adults; foreneck and breast dull light buffy brownish, feathers with pale terminal margins; no metallic reflections on side of neck; wing-coverts and scapulars also, with paler margins, lesser and median coverts sometimes with small medio-terminal wedge-shaped streaks of dull white. Racesphoto 3  differ in coloration."

Male_Text: "Males have distinctive bluish gray cap and nape and pinkish rosy hue over face, throat, and breast; neck feathers tinged with pink iridescence. Newly emerged feathers on head and neck of males have olive tipped edges leading to drabber coloration during the non-breeding season. Tips wear away during the winter to reveal brighter plumage by the breeding season (Sullivan and Mirarchi 1999). Females have olive gray cap and nape, olive brown face and throat, and tan breast; neck feathers usually tinged with olive green iridescence, although some pink iridescence occasionally occurs. Males may often show whiteness on outer 3 rectrices whereas females may usually show whiteness on outer 1-2 feathers (photo in Mirarchi 1993d), but this criterion may not be reliable with all populations and should be used in conjunction with other sex-specific characters. Occasional individuals show intermediate coloration and are difficult to sex (Menasco and Perry 1978, Schulz et al. 1995) and may be males in formative plumage or very old females (Pyle 1995a)."
Female_Text: "Males have distinctive bluish gray cap and nape and pinkish rosy hue over face, throat, and breast; neck feathers tinged with pink iridescence. Newly emerged feathers on head and neck of males have olive tipped edges leading to drabber coloration during the non-breeding season. Tips wear away during the winter to reveal brighter plumage by the breeding season (Sullivan and Mirarchi 1999). Females have olive gray cap and nape, olive brown face and throat, and tan breast; neck feathers usually tinged with olive green iridescence, although some pink iridescence occasionally occurs. Males may often show whiteness on outer 3 rectrices whereas females may usually show whiteness on outer 1-2 feathers (photo in Mirarchi 1993d), but this criterion may not be reliable with all populations and should be used in conjunction with other sex-specific characters. Occasional individuals show intermediate coloration and are difficult to sex (Menasco and Perry 1978, Schulz et al. 1995) and may be males in formative plumage or very old females (Pyle 1995a)."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Forecrown brown; rear crown and nape slate gray. Back olive brown or dull brown. Two central pairs of rectrices deep grayish brown, the second pair with a blackish band across the inner web and part of the outer web. Outer rectrices successively grayer, and the black post-median band more distinct and extensive; gray of the terminal portion of each rectrix paler than the base, becoming pale gray basally and dull white distally on the outermost pair. Wing coverts similar in color to the back, but with a few large roundish black spots; primary coverts dark grayish brown. Remiges dark grayish brown, narrowly edged paler; secondaries also with a few large roundish black spots. Sides of the head and underparts deep orange cinnamon or chestnut brown. Sides of neck glossed with metallic purple. Small subauricular spot of glossy blue black." Adult female: Duller overall than male; blue-gray on head reduced to small nape patch and iridescent neck patches are smaller.
Female_Text: "Adult male: Forecrown brown; rear crown and nape slate gray. Back olive brown or dull brown. Two central pairs of rectrices deep grayish brown, the second pair with a blackish band across the inner web and part of the outer web. Outer rectrices successively grayer, and the black post-median band more distinct and extensive; gray of the terminal portion of each rectrix paler than the base, becoming pale gray basally and dull white distally on the outermost pair. Wing coverts similar in color to the back, but with a few large roundish black spots; primary coverts dark grayish brown. Remiges dark grayish brown, narrowly edged paler; secondaries also with a few large roundish black spots. Sides of the head and underparts deep orange cinnamon or chestnut brown. Sides of neck glossed with metallic purple. Small subauricular spot of glossy blue black." Adult female: Duller overall than male; blue-gray on head reduced to small nape patch and iridescent neck patches are smaller.

Male_Text: "Sexes are alike in plumage. Females average smaller than males for most morphometrics, but substantial individual variation and overlap between sexes (see Measurements). Overall glossy black; breast and wing feathers glossy blue-green, back feathers broadly edged with bronze-green. Feathers on nape and neck are long, narrow, and edged with bronze-green, giving head a “ridged” look. Rectrices are long, square at tip, and glossed violet-purple. Irregular molt of rectrices gives tail a graduated appearance. Iris white to greenish-yellow, outer ring of iris changes to lime-green when stressed (i.e. when handled). Bill large and laterally compressed with high flange on upper mandible. Flange is flat with a variable number of small, raised ridges, but less consistent and conspicuous than bill grooves of other Crotophaga. Tarsi and skin black. No apparent plumage variation among populations." Adult (ASY) plumage all black with purple gloss on tail feathers and green and blue gloss on mantle and wing feathers. No apparent differences between sexes or between Basic and Alternate plumages. Shaggy nape feathers do not appear to function as a crest. Glossy bronze and green edgings on mantle and covert feathers often create scalloped pattern on upperparts, but not as striking as in other Crotophaga. Juvenal rectrices are tapered, but those of adults are square-tipped. At all ages, tail is long and graduated, often appearing ragged due to irregular molt.

Bill large and laterally compressed with high flange on upper mandible. Flange is flat with a variable number of small, raised ridges, but less consistent and conspicuous than bill grooves of other Crotophaga. Tarsi and skin black. No apparent plumage variation among populations." Adult (ASY) plumage all black with purple gloss on tail feathers and green and blue gloss on mantle and wing feathers. Male_Text: "Entirely blackish, glossed with greenish or violet iridescence in parts. Arched, laterally compressed bill, appearing large and reminiscent of a parrot's bill, usually showing raised hump on basal half of upper mandible. Tail long (about 17.2 cm) and with 8 graduated rectrices, outer pairs being 3-5 cm shorter than rest; rectrices easily lost, giving some individuals a disheveled appearance. Feathers of neck stiffened, and edged with brownish bronze; feathers of back, breast, and smaller wing coverts margined dull bluish, creating a scalloped pattern on anterior portion of body. Remiges and rectrices with slight violet iridescence. Wings short and broad. Area around eyes naked. Sexes alike and plumages similar throughout the year. " Entire plumage dull black except feathers of chin, crown, and sides of head, nape, and uppermost back margined with dull, slightly iridescent bronze, with margins becoming dull, slightly iridescent bluish (with bronze and greenish highlights) on feathers of middle and lower back, scapulars, lesser and median wing coverts, throat, breast, and upper belly. Contrastingly colored feather margins create scalloped pattern, especially on feathers margined with bronze. Remiges and rectrices with slight, but distinctive, purplish gloss, but may appear greenish depending on angle of view. Body- and flight feathers usually uniform in color and wear. Tail long and graduated. Rectrices truncate (squared ends rather than tapered). Tapering of rectrices in SY individuals may be greater than that of older individuals; more study is needed. Chin and throat area sometimes puffed out and enlarged (L. Blanchard pers. comm.). Sexes alike

Male_Text: "Entirely blackish; feathers of anterior portions of body with V-shaped dull bronzyolive green margins, creating a scalloped pattern. Laterally compressed bill has arched upper mandible and parallel, curved grooves. Tail long (about 17.5 cm) and graduated; rectrices often frayed. Wings short and broad. Face mostly bare of feathers with long black eyelashes. Sexes alike and plumages similar throughout the year. Immatures resemble adults but plumage mixture of dull and glossy blackish feathers and bill usually with indistinct grooves. Juveniles similar, but plumage dull brownish; bill smaller, without grooves. Vocalizations include flight tijo, delivered as series while flying, as well as modified tijo in alarm, deep aggressive conk during territorial defense, predator-deterrent Scream, and throaty Whimper when roosting (see Sounds: vocal array, below)."

Male_Text: Sexes alike."Adult: Sexes alike. Upperparts, including crest which tends toward more rufous, dull ochraceous streaked with buff and black; alula large and black; wing brown to rufous; upper tail coverts light rufous becoming dark brown; tail long, graduated and dark brown; face with white eyebrow and black whisker lines; underparts whitish with narrow black malar streak; throat and breast with black streaks; belly white (Ridgway 1916, Wetmore 1968, Payne 2005)."
Female_Text: Sexes alike."Adult: Sexes alike. Upperparts, including crest which tends toward more rufous, dull ochraceous streaked with buff and black; alula large and black; wing brown to rufous; upper tail coverts light rufous becoming dark brown; tail long, graduated and dark brown; face with white eyebrow and black whisker lines; underparts whitish with narrow black malar streak; throat and breast with black streaks; belly white (Ridgway 1916, Wetmore 1968, Payne 2005)."

Male_Text: "Lesser Ground-Cuckoo is a medium sized cuckoo, with relatively long, strong tarsi, a long graduated tail, and a slightly decurved bill. The upperparts are mostly dull brown, with rufous tips to the feathers of the rump and uppertail coverts, and a green sheen to the wing. Lesser Ground-Cuckoo has an ornate pattern on the face, with a black mask on the sides of the head, enclosing a bright yellow orbital ring, broader before the eye, and bright blue bare skin behind the eye. There also is a short white postocular stripe, which can be indistinct. The underparts of Lesser Ground-Cuckoo are cinnamon. Sexes are similar, but the juvenile is duller."
Female_Text: "Lesser Ground-Cuckoo is a medium sized cuckoo, with relatively long, strong tarsi, a long graduated tail, and a slightly decurved bill. The upperparts are mostly dull brown, with rufous tips to the feathers of the rump and uppertail coverts, and a green sheen to the wing. Lesser Ground-Cuckoo has an ornate pattern on the face, with a black mask on the sides of the head, enclosing a bright yellow orbital ring, broader before the eye, and bright blue bare skin behind the eye. There also is a short white postocular stripe, which can be indistinct. The underparts of Lesser Ground-Cuckoo are cinnamon. Sexes are similar, but the juvenile is duller."

Male_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. Crown black, slightly glossed with bronze green and spotted with pale brownish buffy, the spots more numerous on the forecorwn. Lores buffy whitish. Auricular region narrowly and indistinctly streaked with dusky and pale buff or dull buffy whitish. Nape brownish black, the feathers broadly edged with pale brownish buffy. Back and scapulars brown, feathers darker basally and sharply edged with pale buff or buffy white, producing conspicuous streaks. Rump brown, feathers with indistinct paler tips. Uppertail coverts brown glossed with purplish bronze and sharply edged with white. Central pair of rectrices brown glossed with purplish bronze and edged with white; next pair dusky olive glossed with greenish bronze and with a small white terminal spot; remaining rectrices dull black faintly glossed with greenish and tipped with white, the white tip increasing in width successively towards the outer pair. Wing coverts with broad median black streak, becoming brown at the tip, and very broadly tipped with white. Inner secondaries (tertials) brown narrowly bordered with black, broadly and sharply edged with white or white and brownish buff; remaining secondaries dull blackish glossed with bronze greenish, edged with white or buffy white. Primary coverts dull black basally, distal half white. Primaries dull black, with oblique band of white on outer webs of median portion of feathers. Underparts buff, deeper on the flanks; sides of neck and of breast broadly streaked with black. Undertail coverts dusky, sometimes tipped with tawny or rusty brownish."
Female_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. Crown black, slightly glossed with bronze green and spotted with pale brownish buffy, the spots more numerous on the forecorwn. Lores buffy whitish. Auricular region narrowly and indistinctly streaked with dusky and pale buff or dull buffy whitish. Nape brownish black, the feathers broadly edged with pale brownish buffy. Back and scapulars brown, feathers darker basally and sharply edged with pale buff or buffy white, producing conspicuous streaks. Rump brown, feathers with indistinct paler tips. Uppertail coverts brown glossed with purplish bronze and sharply edged with white. Central pair of rectrices brown glossed with purplish bronze and edged with white; next pair dusky olive glossed with greenish bronze and with a small white terminal spot; remaining rectrices dull black faintly glossed with greenish and tipped with white, the white tip increasing in width successively towards the outer pair. Wing coverts with broad median black streak, becoming brown at the tip, and very broadly tipped with white. Inner secondaries (tertials) brown narrowly bordered with black, broadly and sharply edged with white or white and brownish buff; remaining secondaries dull blackish glossed with bronze greenish, edged with white or buffy white. Primary coverts dull black basally, distal half white. Primaries dull black, with oblique band of white on outer webs of median portion of feathers. Underparts buff, deeper on the flanks; sides of neck and of breast broadly streaked with black. Undertail coverts dusky, sometimes tipped with tawny or rusty brownish."

Male_Text: "Adults have prominent blue-black erectile crest, dark blue orbital skin, and orange postorbital apteria that are usually obscured. Straw yellow ring in iris. Bill long and stout with hooked tip. Heavily streaked plumage, olive to dark grayish brown glossed with bronze on foreneck, chest, back, scapulars, and wings; underparts unstreaked grayish or buff. Long dark olive tail has white tips that often are badly tattered. Wings show large white crescent in flight. Juvenile plumage similar, but generally duller with less distinct markings and lacking metallic bronze gloss of adult plumage."Present Sep-Aug in most birds but some molt can occur year-round, obscuring temporal boundaries of this plumage. Head (including crest) and nape blue-black, broadly spotted or streaked with russet, tawny, and buff; back and scapulars blue-black with broad edgings of russet, tawny, and buff, the centers of feathers metallic dark olive or bronze; rump hair brown; uppertail coverts and middle rectrices bronzy olive, narrowly margined with white; remaining rectrices metallic blue-black on outer webs, bronze on inner webs, the outer three rectrices with broad tips of white. Remiges dark brownish black glossed with metallic olive and edged with white; greater and primary coverts broadly tipped white giving appearance of white crescents on wings in flight; tertials rufous bronze, margined with white; remainder of secondaries and upperwing coverts like back but with broader russet margins. Cheeks and chin dull white; throat, foreneck, and breast cinnamon and buff, each feather with mesial streak of black; belly unstreaked grayish white or pale buff. Lining of underwing dark brownish black.
Female_Text: "Adults have prominent blue-black erectile crest, dark blue orbital skin, and orange postorbital apteria that are usually obscured. Straw yellow ring in iris. Bill long and stout with hooked tip. Heavily streaked plumage, olive to dark grayish brown glossed with bronze on foreneck, chest, back, scapulars, and wings; underparts unstreaked grayish or buff. Long dark olive tail has white tips that often are badly tattered. Wings show large white crescent in flight. Juvenile plumage similar, but generally duller with less distinct markings and lacking metallic bronze gloss of adult plumage."Present Sep-Aug in most birds but some molt can occur year-round, obscuring temporal boundaries of this plumage. Remiges dark brownish black glossed with metallic olive and edged with white; greater and primary coverts broadly tipped white giving appearance of white crescents on wings in flight; tertials rufous bronze, margined with white; remainder of secondaries and upperwing coverts like back but with broader russet margins. Cheeks and chin dull white; throat, foreneck, and breast cinnamon and buff, each feather with mesial streak of black; belly unstreaked grayish white or pale buff. Lining of underwing dark brownish black.

Male_Text: "Like other species in the genus Neomorphus, it has a heavy, decurved bill and a shaggy, erectile crest. Its elongated tail accounts for roughly half the overall body length. The wings are short, broad, and rounded, and it has sturdy, powerful legs with zygodactyl toe orientation. The face and underparts are usually pale or buffy in coloration, with a prominent black band across the lower breast and orange-red plumage on the lower belly and vent. The color of the upperparts varies greatly between subspecies, ranging from brown with a purple sheen to bright, bronzy green to dark blue. The feathers of the throat and upper breast are marked with semicircular patterns that impart a scaled appearance, and the density and heaviness of these markings also vary in different populations. In all subspecies, the crest is glossy blue-black. The bill is pale yellowish in adult birds, and the eye is bordered by a mask-like pattern of bright blue facial skin. Iris color ranges from dark brown in northern birds to pale yellow in the south."
