annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Elvira. Monotypic.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull coppery bronze. Nape, back, scapulars, and rump bronze green. Uppertail coverts bright coppery bronze. Central pair of rectrices bronze (much less coppery than the uppertail coverts); four outer pairs of rectrices white; the three outer pairs are tipped with pale gray, and the outermost pair is tipped with black. Wing coverts bronze green. Remiges mostly dusky purplish brown, but the inner secondaries are bronze green. Underparts bright yellowish metallic green; undertail coverts pure white." Adult female: Upperparts metallic green (less bronzy than the adult male). Uppertail coverts and central pair of rectrices bright bronze (more coppery on the uppertail coverts). Four outer pairs of rectrices white, with a V shaped subterminal bar of gray or dusky, the outerpair also tipped with black or gray, and edged with blackish along the terminal half. Remiges as in the male. Underparts dull white or grayish white, becoming pure white posteriorly; the flanks are more or less spotted with metallic green.'
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull coppery bronze. Nape, back, scapulars, and rump bronze green. Uppertail coverts bright coppery bronze. Central pair of rectrices bronze (much less coppery than the uppertail coverts); four outer pairs of rectrices white; the three outer pairs are tipped with pale gray, and the outermost pair is tipped with black. Wing coverts bronze green. Remiges mostly dusky purplish brown, but the inner secondaries are bronze green. Underparts bright yellowish metallic green; undertail coverts pure white." Adult female: Upperparts metallic green (less bronzy than the adult male). Uppertail coverts and central pair of rectrices bright bronze (more coppery on the uppertail coverts). Four outer pairs of rectrices white, with a V shaped subterminal bar of gray or dusky, the outerpair also tipped with black or gray, and edged with blackish along the terminal half. Remiges as in the male. Underparts dull white or grayish white, becoming pure white posteriorly; the flanks are more or less spotted with metallic green.'

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Elvira. Monotypic.
Male_Text: "Bill nearly straight, black except for pinkish basal half of mandible, feet dark grey. Male bronzy green above, shading to dark copper-bronze on uppertail-coverts and central rectrices; outer three rectrices white, tipped black; below mostly glittering green, belly, vent and undertail-coverts white. Female dull white below flecked with green laterally and bronzy green on flanks; central rectrices bronzy, outer three white crossed by diagonal black subterminal band. Juvenile male duller green below than adult, with greyish-buff feather fringes; juvenile female greyer below than adult, green lateral spotting duller, more bronzy and sparser; both have greyish-buff fringes on face, crown, nape and rump feathers."
Female_Text: "Bill nearly straight, black except for pinkish basal half of mandible, feet dark grey. Male bronzy green above, shading to dark copper-bronze on uppertail-coverts and central rectrices; outer three rectrices white, tipped black; below mostly glittering green, belly, vent and undertail-coverts white. Female dull white below flecked with green laterally and bronzy green on flanks; central rectrices bronzy, outer three white crossed by diagonal black subterminal band. Juvenile male duller green below than adult, with greyish-buff feather fringes; juvenile female greyer below than adult, green lateral spotting duller, more bronzy and sparser; both have greyish-buff fringes on face, crown, nape and rump feathers."

Male_Text: " Male has straight black bill, mandible basally pinkish; crown iridescent violet-blue; back and underparts metallic green; undertail coverts green, with central feathers white and stiffened; tail slightly forked, maroon, broadly bordered with bronze; white femoral tufts. Female green above, whitish below, with gray spots on throat and green discs on sides; tail similar to male’s, but tipped white. Juvenile resembles adult female."
Female_Text: " Male has straight black bill, mandible basally pinkish; crown iridescent violet-blue; back and underparts metallic green; undertail coverts green, with central feathers white and stiffened; tail slightly forked, maroon, broadly bordered with bronze; white femoral tufts. Female green above, whitish below, with gray spots on throat and green discs on sides; tail similar to male’s, but tipped white. Juvenile resembles adult female."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Goethalsia. Monotypic.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Forecrown and lores chestnut (but median feathers of the forecrown tipped with green). Crown, wing coverts, back, rump, and uppertail coverts metallic green, with a bronzy cast on the lower back and rump. Central pair of rectrices bronze green basally, tipped with black; outer rectrices extensively cinnamon buff, tipped with black, the black tips narrower on the outer pair. Remiges dusky brown; inner secondaries basally cinnamon, and tipped with dusky brown. Chin cinnamon buff. Throat to belly, including sides of the breast, shining, faintly bluish green; flank feathers basally pale cinnamon buff to white, in part tipped with green. Undertail coverts pure white; also, three or more of the central undertail coverts elongated, broadened, with a thickened, curved shaft."Adult female: Upperparts similar to adult male, but forecrown green (the color as the crown). Lores chestnut. Underparts pale cinnamon buff."
Female_Text: "Adult male: Forecrown and lores chestnut (but median feathers of the forecrown tipped with green). Crown, wing coverts, back, rump, and uppertail coverts metallic green, with a bronzy cast on the lower back and rump. Central pair of rectrices bronze green basally, tipped with black; outer rectrices extensively cinnamon buff, tipped with black, the black tips narrower on the outer pair. Remiges dusky brown; inner secondaries basally cinnamon, and tipped with dusky brown. Chin cinnamon buff. Throat to belly, including sides of the breast, shining, faintly bluish green; flank feathers basally pale cinnamon buff to white, in part tipped with green. Undertail coverts pure white; also, three or more of the central undertail coverts elongated, broadened, with a thickened, curved shaft."Adult female: Upperparts similar to adult male, but forecrown green (the color as the crown). Lores chestnut. Underparts pale cinnamon buff."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Thalurania. Monotypic.
Male_Text: :Male has straight black bill; forehead iridescent violet-blue, hindcrown bluish-green, rest of upperparts green; throat ­iridescent emerald green, belly and undertail-coverts dusky green; tail slightly forked, bluish-black. Female upperparts similar to male, small white postocular spot; below greyish, side of breast with some green discs; tail slightly forked, bluish-black, central pair of rectrices with greenish shine, outer rectrices tipped white. Immature unknown."
Female_Text: :Male has straight black bill; forehead iridescent violet-blue, hindcrown bluish-green, rest of upperparts green; throat ­iridescent emerald green, belly and undertail-coverts dusky green; tail slightly forked, bluish-black. Female upperparts similar to male, small white postocular spot; below greyish, side of breast with some green discs; tail slightly forked, bluish-black, central pair of rectrices with greenish shine, outer rectrices tipped white. Immature unknown."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts bright metallic bronze green. Secondaries and four innermost primaries rufous; remaining primaries dusky. Central pair of rectrices metallic bronze green; outer rectrices mostly grayish white, duskier at tip. Underparts bright metallic yellowish green; undertail coverts white." Adult female: Upperparts bright metallic golden green. Central pair of rectrices metallic golden green. Outer rectrices white, with dusky or bronze green outer webs. Secondaries and inner primaries dull cinnamon rufous; remaining primaries dusky. Underparts grayish white, sides of the breast spotted with metallic green. Undertail coverts white or grayish white."
Female_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts bright metallic bronze green. Secondaries and four innermost primaries rufous; remaining primaries dusky. Central pair of rectrices metallic bronze green; outer rectrices mostly grayish white, duskier at tip. Underparts bright metallic yellowish green; undertail coverts white." Adult female: Upperparts bright metallic golden green. Central pair of rectrices metallic golden green. Outer rectrices white, with dusky or bronze green outer webs. Secondaries and inner primaries dull cinnamon rufous; remaining primaries dusky. Underparts grayish white, sides of the breast spotted with metallic green. Undertail coverts white or grayish white."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Body plumage primarily green, glittering green on underparts; forecrown violet blue, hind crown turquoise. Primaries dusky, secondaries rufous. Central pair of rectrices green; remaining rectrices whitish. Undertail coverts white. Adult female: Similar to male, but secondaries less rufous. Underparts pale gray. Outer rectrices white with dusky green outer webs."
Female_Text: "Adult male: Body plumage primarily green, glittering green on underparts; forecrown violet blue, hind crown turquoise. Primaries dusky, secondaries rufous. Central pair of rectrices green; remaining rectrices whitish. Undertail coverts white. Adult female: Similar to male, but secondaries less rufous. Underparts pale gray. Outer rectrices white with dusky green outer webs."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts bright metallic grass green, becoming more bronzy posteriorly, especially on the uppertail coverts. The three central pairs of rectrices are dark bronze green; the two outermost pairs of rectrices have black outer webs, but the inner webs are pure white, broadly tipped with black. Primaries dusky, the innermost primaries basally cinnamon rufous; secondaries cinnamon rufous, tipped with dusky. Underparts bright metallic grass green; undertail coverts pure white." Adult female: Upperparts similar to male, but secondaries not tipped with dusky. Central rectrices terminally black or dusky. Underparts and sides of face light brownish gray, the flanks spotted with metallic green.
Female_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts bright metallic grass green, becoming more bronzy posteriorly, especially on the uppertail coverts. The three central pairs of rectrices are dark bronze green; the two outermost pairs of rectrices have black outer webs, but the inner webs are pure white, broadly tipped with black. Primaries dusky, the innermost primaries basally cinnamon rufous; secondaries cinnamon rufous, tipped with dusky. Underparts bright metallic grass green; undertail coverts pure white." Adult female: Upperparts similar to male, but secondaries not tipped with dusky. Central rectrices terminally black or dusky. Underparts and sides of face light brownish gray, the flanks spotted with metallic green.

Male_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts, from the crown to the rump, bronze green; feathers of the crown narrowly edged with dull black. Uppertail coverts dull bronze. Central rectrices dull black, glossed with bronze; outer rectrices white. Wing coverts bronze green. Remiges dusky, with a purplish bronze reflection; secondaries basally cinnamon brown, with the tips more or less dusky. Forecrown, sides of the head, breast, and belly black; sides and undertail coverts green. Undertail coverts white." Adult female: Upperparts metallic bronze green; uppertail coverts bronzier. Wings as in male, but with reduced cinnamon on the secondaries. Underparts grayish white; undertail coverts white.
Female_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts, from the crown to the rump, bronze green; feathers of the crown narrowly edged with dull black. Uppertail coverts dull bronze. Central rectrices dull black, glossed with bronze; outer rectrices white. Wing coverts bronze green. Remiges dusky, with a purplish bronze reflection; secondaries basally cinnamon brown, with the tips more or less dusky. Forecrown, sides of the head, breast, and belly black; sides and undertail coverts green. Undertail coverts white." Adult female: Upperparts metallic bronze green; uppertail coverts bronzier. Wings as in male, but with reduced cinnamon on the secondaries. Underparts grayish white; undertail coverts white.

Male_Text: " Mostly bronzy-greenphoto , with dull buffy borders on feathers of most of underpartsphoto imparting a scaly appearancephoto ; belly greyish-buff; corners of tail dull white, set off by diagonal blackish band from rest of bronzy tail. Female has longer bill on average but otherwise smaller than male, and does not differ in colour. Young bird lacks the thickened shafts of the outer primaries and has prominent buffy fringes on the feathers of the crown, nape and uppertail-coverts. Basal half of lower mandible pinkish in most races, black in roberti; race saturatior largest and darkest, nominate smallest and palest; berlepschiphoto has belly more rusty, white on lateral rectrices more extensive; in roberti these rectrices are entirely black except for white tips; maculicaudaphoto has somewhat greener throat and more extensive black on outer rectrices; furvescens has throat and upper breast slightly darker green, belly paler."
Female_Text: " Mostly bronzy-greenphoto , with dull buffy borders on feathers of most of underpartsphoto imparting a scaly appearancephoto ; belly greyish-buff; corners of tail dull white, set off by diagonal blackish band from rest of bronzy tail. Female has longer bill on average but otherwise smaller than male, and does not differ in colour. Young bird lacks the thickened shafts of the outer primaries and has prominent buffy fringes on the feathers of the crown, nape and uppertail-coverts. Basal half of lower mandible pinkish in most races, black in roberti; race saturatior largest and darkest, nominate smallest and palest; berlepschiphoto has belly more rusty, white on lateral rectrices more extensive; in roberti these rectrices are entirely black except for white tips; maculicaudaphoto has somewhat greener throat and more extensive black on outer rectrices; furvescens has throat and upper breast slightly darker green, belly paler."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull black or blue black; crest on sides of crown and on nape deep velvety black. Back, scapulars, wing coverts, rump, and uppertail coverts bright metallic green. Rectrices black, the central pair more or less glossed with bronze green or greenish bronze; the other rectrices variably but more faintly glossed with green, at least basally. Tail deeply forked, and the next to outer pair of rectrices greatly elongaged. Primaries brownish slate or dusky; secondaries darker (nearly black), the innermost secondaries with the outer web mostly metallic green or bronze green. Malar region, sides of neck, and underparts luminous metallic yellowish green. Undertail coverts blue black or black faintly glossed with bluish." Adult female: Upperparts bright metallic bronze green or greenish bronze, duller on the crown. Central pair of rectrices bright bronze green; remaining rectrices black, more or less glossed with bronze green on the basal portion of the outer web. The two outermost pairs of rectrices broadly tipped with white. Remiges dusky; innermost secondaries with metallic bronze green outer webs. Primary coverts dusky. Lores and auriculars dusky. Malar region and underparts white, the breast and sides of the breast and the flanks heavily spotted with metallic bronze green.
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull black or blue black; crest on sides of crown and on nape deep velvety black. Back, scapulars, wing coverts, rump, and uppertail coverts bright metallic green. Rectrices black, the central pair more or less glossed with bronze green or greenish bronze; the other rectrices variably but more faintly glossed with green, at least basally. Tail deeply forked, and the next to outer pair of rectrices greatly elongaged. Primaries brownish slate or dusky; secondaries darker (nearly black), the innermost secondaries with the outer web mostly metallic green or bronze green. Malar region, sides of neck, and underparts luminous metallic yellowish green. Undertail coverts blue black or black faintly glossed with bluish." Adult female: Upperparts bright metallic bronze green or greenish bronze, duller on the crown. Central pair of rectrices bright bronze green; remaining rectrices black, more or less glossed with bronze green on the basal portion of the outer web. The two outermost pairs of rectrices broadly tipped with white. Remiges dusky; innermost secondaries with metallic bronze green outer webs. Primary coverts dusky. Lores and auriculars dusky. Malar region and underparts white, the breast and sides of the breast and the flanks heavily spotted with metallic bronze green.

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull metallic violet blue to greenish blue. Remaining upperparts metallic green or bronze green; uppertail coverts more bluish green. Rectrices dull metallic bluish green, shading into purplish black or blackish violet distally, this co
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull metallic violet blue to greenish blue. Remaining upperparts metallic green or bronze green; uppertail coverts more bluish green. Rectrices dull metallic bluish green, shading into purplish black or blackish violet distally, this co

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull metallic violet blue to greenish blue. Remaining upperparts metallic green or bronze green; uppertail coverts more bluish green. Rectrices dull metallic bluish green, shading into purplish black or blackish violet distally, this co
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull metallic violet blue to greenish blue. Remaining upperparts metallic green or bronze green; uppertail coverts more bluish green. Rectrices dull metallic bluish green, shading into purplish black or blackish violet distally, this co

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown bright metallic blue. Nape, back, scapulars, and wing coverts metallic bronze green, becoming greenish bronze or bronze green on the rump, uppertail coverts, and rectrices. Remiges dusky. Suborbital region metallic bluish emerald green; auriculars and sides of neck mostly metallic bluish green (less bluish posteriorly). Chin, throat, malars, center of breast and belly, and tibial tufts white. Sides of breast metallic bronze green, becoming duller bronze green or greenish bronze on the flanks" Adult female: Very similar to adult male, but blue of crown slightly duller or more greenish
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown bright metallic blue. Nape, back, scapulars, and wing coverts metallic bronze green, becoming greenish bronze or bronze green on the rump, uppertail coverts, and rectrices. Remiges dusky. Suborbital region metallic bluish emerald green; auriculars and sides of neck mostly metallic bluish green (less bluish posteriorly). Chin, throat, malars, center of breast and belly, and tibial tufts white. Sides of breast metallic bronze green, becoming duller bronze green or greenish bronze on the flanks" Adult female: Very similar to adult male, but blue of crown slightly duller or more greenish

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia and considered conspecific with Saucerottia saucerottei.
Male_Text: "Male has straight, medium-sized bill; upperparts golden-green, with rump and uppertail coverts coppery to purplish; underparts glittering dark golden-green; undertail-coverts greenish to steel blue; rectrices pale, steel-blue; tail slightly forked. Female similar but has the lower breast and belly duller green; has white subterminal bars on throat feathers, and feathers of the crissum edged with grayish-buff; outer rectrices purplish at tip, less forked tail (1, 2)."
Female_Text: "Male has straight, medium-sized bill; upperparts golden-green, with rump and uppertail coverts coppery to purplish; underparts glittering dark golden-green; undertail-coverts greenish to steel blue; rectrices pale, steel-blue; tail slightly forked. Female similar but has the lower breast and belly duller green; has white subterminal bars on throat feathers, and feathers of the crissum edged with grayish-buff; outer rectrices purplish at tip, less forked tail (1, 2)."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Male has straight, medium-sized, blackish bill, except for pinkish basal half of mandible; bronze-green to coppery on head, back and rump; base of primaries and secondaries chestnut; underparts glittering golden green; uppertail-coverts and tail variable, often coppery to rufous. Femalephoto similar but has throat and belly paler, more greyish, and lacks pinkish bill base. Juvenile is similar to female but has less iridescence on throat; belly greyish cinnamon. Race viola has greyish tinge on back and rump, belly fawn to cinnamon, uppertail-coverts and rectrices dark violet-blue; lichten­steini is generally lighter green, wingband paler, rectrices silvery-coloured; sumichrastivideo closest to viola or nominate in duller green plumage (1), but has somewhat purplish gloss to tail, female with silvery to purple inner rectrices, and wing longer than in lichtensteini (1); devillei shows stronger bronze to coppery on back and rump, wingband paler, tail purplish to bronzy-chestnut. Hybrids between present species and Eugenes fulgens regularly seen in SE Arizona between late 1990s and 2007, being larger and longer-billed than S. beryllina, with less rufous in wings and a golden-toned rump and tail, while some birds have an intense blue crown and gorget (2)."
Female_Text: "Male has straight, medium-sized, blackish bill, except for pinkish basal half of mandible; bronze-green to coppery on head, back and rump; base of primaries and secondaries chestnut; underparts glittering golden green; uppertail-coverts and tail variable, often coppery to rufous. Femalephoto similar but has throat and belly paler, more greyish, and lacks pinkish bill base. Juvenile is similar to female but has less iridescence on throat; belly greyish cinnamon. Race viola has greyish tinge on back and rump, belly fawn to cinnamon, uppertail-coverts and rectrices dark violet-blue; lichten­steini is generally lighter green, wingband paler, rectrices silvery-coloured; sumichrastivideo closest to viola or nominate in duller green plumage (1), but has somewhat purplish gloss to tail, female with silvery to purple inner rectrices, and wing longer than in lichtensteini (1); devillei shows stronger bronze to coppery on back and rump, wingband paler, tail purplish to bronzy-chestnut. Hybrids between present species and Eugenes fulgens regularly seen in SE Arizona between late 1990s and 2007, being larger and longer-billed than S. beryllina, with less rufous in wings and a golden-toned rump and tail, while some birds have an intense blue crown and gorget (2)."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull coppery bronze. Nape, back, scapulars, and rump bronze green. Uppertail coverts bright coppery bronze. Central pair of rectrices bronze (much less coppery than the uppertail coverts); four outer pairs of rectrices white; the three
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown dull coppery bronze. Nape, back, scapulars, and rump bronze green. Uppertail coverts bright coppery bronze. Central pair of rectrices bronze (much less coppery than the uppertail coverts); four outer pairs of rectrices white; the three

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Blackish, straight bill, with reddish base to lower mandible. Malephoto has upperparts bronze-green to coppery, especially on back and rump; throat and chest glittering golden greenphoto , belly with V-shaped white centrephoto ; undertail-coverts rufous, rectrices bronze to coppery, sometimes with purple sheen. Female similar but normally has less intense coloration on upperparts; more whitish on throat and in undertail-coverts; light green tips on outer rectrices. Juvenile has greyish-brown sides instead of the pure white belly of adults. Race niveoventer slightly larger, with tail bluish-black to purplish-black; collata has less contrasted back, brownish undertail-coverts; margaritarum can be differentiated by paler undertail-coverts and bronze to bronze-green tail."
Female_Text: "Blackish, straight bill, with reddish base to lower mandible. Malephoto has upperparts bronze-green to coppery, especially on back and rump; throat and chest glittering golden greenphoto , belly with V-shaped white centrephoto ; undertail-coverts rufous, rectrices bronze to coppery, sometimes with purple sheen. Female similar but normally has less intense coloration on upperparts; more whitish on throat and in undertail-coverts; light green tips on outer rectrices. Juvenile has greyish-brown sides instead of the pure white belly of adults. Race niveoventer slightly larger, with tail bluish-black to purplish-black; collata has less contrasted back, brownish undertail-coverts; margaritarum can be differentiated by paler undertail-coverts and bronze to bronze-green tail."

Male_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. Upperparts metallic bronze green. Rectrices deep cinnamon rufous or rufous chestnut; rectrices broadly tipped with dark metallic bronze, and the outer web of the outermost rectrix also is edged for most of its length with dark metallic bronze. Remiges dark brownish slate or dusky. Underparts cinnamon or dull cinnamon rufous, slightly paler on the chin and upper throat."
Female_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. Upperparts metallic bronze green. Rectrices deep cinnamon rufous or rufous chestnut; rectrices broadly tipped with dark metallic bronze, and the outer web of the outermost rectrix also is edged for most of its length with dark metallic bronze. Remiges dark brownish slate or dusky. Underparts cinnamon or dull cinnamon rufous, slightly paler on the chin and upper throat."

Male_Text: "Adult (Definitive Basic) male: Upperparts metallic bronze green, duller and darker on crown; uppertail-coverts intermixed with cinnamon rufous, sometimes mostly cinnamon rufous. Middle pair of rectrices mostly or with at least terminal fourth metallic bronze; basal portion chestnut. Remaining rectrices chestnut, margined terminally with metallic bronze. Remiges dusky, glossed faintly with violet. Chin, throat, and chest bright metallic yellowish emerald green; feathers pale buff basally or (on chest) subterminally. Remaining underparts, including undertail-coverts, underwing coverts, and axillars, pale cinnamon buff; femoral tufts white; bill rosy reddish, dusky dark terminally; iris dark brown; feet dull brown (Ridgway 1911, Howell and Webb 1995)."Adult (Definitive Basic) female similar to male, but shows darker upper portion of bill; also throat and back are less iridescent green. Pale rufous or chestnut tail is slightly notched; central rectrices are mostly greenish bronze; outer rectrices only are edged and tipped with bronzy green."Male. Upperparts metallic bronze green or greenish bronze, duller and darker on crown; uppertail coverts similar but variably tinged to almost entirely cinnamon-rufous; central rectrices chestnut basally and broadly tipped metallic bronze; remainder of rectrices cinnamon to chestnut, margined terminally with metallic bronze; tail fork relatively deep; longest to central rectrix 5-7 mm (Pyle 1997). Upperwing secondary coverts as in upperparts but sometimes brighter; primary coverts dusky, margined metallic green in the upper tract; primaries and secondaries dusky, glossed faintly with violet. Chin, throat, and breast uniformly bright, metallic-emerald green (Pyle 1997, Fig. 94), the feathers pale buff basally and narrowly margined this color when fresh; remaining underparts including undertail coverts, underwing coverts, and axillars pale cinnamon buff; femoral tufts white." Female. Similar to male but upperparts average duller; tail fork shallower (longest to central rectrix 3-5 mm); rectrices may average duller with less bronze edging; feathers of throat and chin green with broader pale buff margins, creating buff throat patch (Pyle 1997, Fig. 94).
Female_Text: "Adult (Definitive Basic) male: Upperparts metallic bronze green, duller and darker on crown; uppertail-coverts intermixed with cinnamon rufous, sometimes mostly cinnamon rufous. Middle pair of rectrices mostly or with at least terminal fourth metallic bronze; basal portion chestnut. Remaining rectrices chestnut, margined terminally with metallic bronze. Remiges dusky, glossed faintly with violet. Chin, throat, and chest bright metallic yellowish emerald green; feathers pale buff basally or (on chest) subterminally. Remaining underparts, including undertail-coverts, underwing coverts, and axillars, pale cinnamon buff; femoral tufts white; bill rosy reddish, dusky dark terminally; iris dark brown; feet dull brown (Ridgway 1911, Howell and Webb 1995)."Adult (Definitive Basic) female similar to male, but shows darker upper portion of bill; also throat and back are less iridescent green. Pale rufous or chestnut tail is slightly notched; central rectrices are mostly greenish bronze; outer rectrices only are edged and tipped with bronzy green."Male. Upperparts metallic bronze green or greenish bronze, duller and darker on crown; uppertail coverts similar but variably tinged to almost entirely cinnamon-rufous; central rectrices chestnut basally and broadly tipped metallic bronze; remainder of rectrices cinnamon to chestnut, margined terminally with metallic bronze; tail fork relatively deep; longest to central rectrix 5-7 mm (Pyle 1997). Upperwing secondary coverts as in upperparts but sometimes brighter; primary coverts dusky, margined metallic green in the upper tract; primaries and secondaries dusky, glossed faintly with violet. Chin, throat, and breast uniformly bright, metallic-emerald green (Pyle 1997, Fig. 94), the feathers pale buff basally and narrowly margined this color when fresh; remaining underparts including undertail coverts, underwing coverts, and axillars pale cinnamon buff; femoral tufts white." Female. Similar to male but upperparts average duller; tail fork shallower (longest to central rectrix 3-5 mm); rectrices may average duller with less bronze edging; feathers of throat and chin green with broader pale buff margins, creating buff throat patch (Pyle 1997, Fig. 94).

Male_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts (including the wing coverts) green, except for chestnut-brown lores, uppertail coverts, and rectrices. Remiges black with a slight purple sheen. Throat, upper breast and sides green; on some individuals, feathers of the throat and foreneck have narrow dull white edges, producing a scalloped effect. Lower breast gray, belly and tibia white, undertail coverts chestnut-brown."Adult female: Similar to male, but lower breast paler gray. Throat and foreneck have a scalloped appearance (more pronounced than in males), due to narrow dull white feather edges."
Female_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts (including the wing coverts) green, except for chestnut-brown lores, uppertail coverts, and rectrices. Remiges black with a slight purple sheen. Throat, upper breast and sides green; on some individuals, feathers of the throat and foreneck have narrow dull white edges, producing a scalloped effect. Lower breast gray, belly and tibia white, undertail coverts chestnut-brown."Adult female: Similar to male, but lower breast paler gray. Throat and foreneck have a scalloped appearance (more pronounced than in males), due to narrow dull white feather edges."

Male_Text: "Adult male: The maxilla is blackish and may trend to red around the nostril (hard to see in the field), whereas the mandible is red with a dark tip. Gorget and upper breast medium blue (neither turquoise nor dark blue) but can appear greenish or grayish depending on angle and intensity of ambient light. Crown, nape, and upper back are dark green, but the green from the throat sometimes extends to the nape, scapulars, and upper back. The lower back and uppertail coverts become increasingly bronze. Upperwing coverts yellowish green to bronze. Auriculars mostly greenish blue (more strongly blue posteriorly). Center of breast is grayish white, sides of breast green becoming duller bronze green on the flanks. Remiges dusky. Undertail coverts are dark centrally, edged with white. The tail is slightly forked, central retrices dark green, outer retrices bronzy distally, entire tail with a purplish subterminal band." Adult female: Similar to adult male but overall duller. Gorget is less extensive and more greenish in color. Outer retrices are tipped in gray.
Female_Text: "Adult male: The maxilla is blackish and may trend to red around the nostril (hard to see in the field), whereas the mandible is red with a dark tip. Gorget and upper breast medium blue (neither turquoise nor dark blue) but can appear greenish or grayish depending on angle and intensity of ambient light. Crown, nape, and upper back are dark green, but the green from the throat sometimes extends to the nape, scapulars, and upper back. The lower back and uppertail coverts become increasingly bronze. Upperwing coverts yellowish green to bronze. Auriculars mostly greenish blue (more strongly blue posteriorly). Center of breast is grayish white, sides of breast green becoming duller bronze green on the flanks. Remiges dusky. Undertail coverts are dark centrally, edged with white. The tail is slightly forked, central retrices dark green, outer retrices bronzy distally, entire tail with a purplish subterminal band." Adult female: Similar to adult male but overall duller. Gorget is less extensive and more greenish in color. Outer retrices are tipped in gray.

Male_Text: "Male has an essentially straight but slightly decurved, medium-sized bill. The upper mandible is blackish, the lower mandible is reddish, and distally dusky grey. The upper body parts and flanks are golden to bronze-green. The throat and breast are a glittering bluish-green. The feathers toward the chin have prominent white subterminal bars. The belly is whitish with bronze-green sides and the undertail-coverts are also white. The tail is bronzy-green and slightly forked, with almost blackish lateral and terminal portions on the outer rectrices. The female is similar to the male but mostly white below with a little green spotting on the throat and the sides, and the female’s outermost rectrices have grayish tips. The female has a distinct green malar pattern offset by white below the eye, lore, and cheek. "
Female_Text: "Male has an essentially straight but slightly decurved, medium-sized bill. The upper mandible is blackish, the lower mandible is reddish, and distally dusky grey. The upper body parts and flanks are golden to bronze-green. The throat and breast are a glittering bluish-green. The feathers toward the chin have prominent white subterminal bars. The belly is whitish with bronze-green sides and the undertail-coverts are also white. The tail is bronzy-green and slightly forked, with almost blackish lateral and terminal portions on the outer rectrices. The female is similar to the male but mostly white below with a little green spotting on the throat and the sides, and the female’s outermost rectrices have grayish tips. The female has a distinct green malar pattern offset by white below the eye, lore, and cheek. "

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Lepidopyga.
Male_Text: "Malephoto has straight short bill, maxilla black, mandible pinkish, tipped black; upperpartsvideo shining green, coppery on rump; throat and chest iridescent violet-blue, rest of underparts glittering green; tail forked, central rectrices coppery gold, rest blue-black. Femalephoto similar to male but greyish white below, with bluish-green spots on sides, outer rectrices tipped white. Juvenile like adult female, buffy fringes on head feathers. Race confinisphoto darker green on upper back, with chin and throat glittering turquoise; coelina less bronzy above, with blue throat."
Female_Text: "Malephoto has straight short bill, maxilla black, mandible pinkish, tipped black; upperpartsvideo shining green, coppery on rump; throat and chest iridescent violet-blue, rest of underparts glittering green; tail forked, central rectrices coppery gold, rest blue-black. Femalephoto similar to male but greyish white below, with bluish-green spots on sides, outer rectrices tipped white. Juvenile like adult female, buffy fringes on head feathers. Race confinisphoto darker green on upper back, with chin and throat glittering turquoise; coelina less bronzy above, with blue throat."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Hylocharis. Monotypic.
Male_Text: "present species has bill shorter on average, wings and tail longer. Bill of male mostly coral-red with black tip; maxilla of female black tinged red basally, mandible pinkish with black tip; feet blackish. In male, deep blue restricted to forehead and centre of throat, shading through blue-green to glittering green on chest, sides of neck, and malar area; sides green, most of belly and undertail-coverts white, the white typically extending forwards as a broad medial stripe that ends abruptly on lower breast; crown dark dull blue-green, rest of upperparts metallic green to bronze-green, tail dark metallic green to blue, the outer rectrices more or less tipped dusky grey and narrow. Female averages much whiter below than C. grayi, heavily flecked with bright green on sides of throat and breast; crown bluer; tail metallic green to bronze-green, shading to dusky grey distally on lateral rectrices, which are more or less tipped pale grey"
Female_Text: "present species has bill shorter on average, wings and tail longer. Bill of male mostly coral-red with black tip; maxilla of female black tinged red basally, mandible pinkish with black tip; feet blackish. In male, deep blue restricted to forehead and centre of throat, shading through blue-green to glittering green on chest, sides of neck, and malar area; sides green, most of belly and undertail-coverts white, the white typically extending forwards as a broad medial stripe that ends abruptly on lower breast; crown dark dull blue-green, rest of upperparts metallic green to bronze-green, tail dark metallic green to blue, the outer rectrices more or less tipped dusky grey and narrow. Female averages much whiter below than C. grayi, heavily flecked with bright green on sides of throat and breast; crown bluer; tail metallic green to bronze-green, shading to dusky grey distally on lateral rectrices, which are more or less tipped pale grey"

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia. Monotypic.
Male_Text: "Male has straight, mid-length, blackish bill, mandible basally reddish; crown and malar area glittering green with slight bluish tinge; upperparts and flanks dull green to bronze-green; chin centrally bronzy; lower throat and breast with violet-blue patch and greyish-edged discs; lower belly greyish brown; undertail-coverts with brownish centres; uppertail-coverts and tail bronze-green, rarely dull green, with some purplish reflections in tail-coverts and median rectrices; outer rectrices becoming blackish. Female lacks glittering crown; instead of distinct throat patch has scattered turquoise to bluish feathers with broad whitish margins; belly paler; rectrices with greyish tips. Juvenile resembles female in throat coloration but more greyish in underparts; juvenile male has dark green chin, throat with 15–30 bluish feathers, some glittering green feathers on crown and outer rectrices show small or no grey tips; and juvenile female has pale grey chin with green spots, throat shows 0–2 turquoise-blue feathers, crown dull green, and outer rectrices have grey tips."
Female_Text: "Male has straight, mid-length, blackish bill, mandible basally reddish; crown and malar area glittering green with slight bluish tinge; upperparts and flanks dull green to bronze-green; chin centrally bronzy; lower throat and breast with violet-blue patch and greyish-edged discs; lower belly greyish brown; undertail-coverts with brownish centres; uppertail-coverts and tail bronze-green, rarely dull green, with some purplish reflections in tail-coverts and median rectrices; outer rectrices becoming blackish. Female lacks glittering crown; instead of distinct throat patch has scattered turquoise to bluish feathers with broad whitish margins; belly paler; rectrices with greyish tips. Juvenile resembles female in throat coloration but more greyish in underparts; juvenile male has dark green chin, throat with 15–30 bluish feathers, some glittering green feathers on crown and outer rectrices show small or no grey tips; and juvenile female has pale grey chin with green spots, throat shows 0–2 turquoise-blue feathers, crown dull green, and outer rectrices have grey tips."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia. Monotypic.
Male_Text: "9·6–10·4 cm; male 4·74 g (mean). Previously considered conspecific with Polyerata amabilis (see Taxonomy comments), but has longer and broader bill, and shorter wings. Male has straight, mid-length, blackish bill, mandible basally reddish; nape, crown and malar area glittering green with slight bluish tinge; upperparts and flanks dull green to bronze-green; chin centrally bronzy; lower throat and breast with royal-blue patch and greyish-edged discs; lower belly greyish brown; undertail-coverts with brownish centres; uppertail-coverts and tail bronze-green, rarely dull green, with some purplish reflections in tail-coverts and median rectrices; outer rectrices becoming blackish. Female has glittering green crown; instead of distinct throat patch has scattered turquoise to bluish feathers with broad whitish margins; belly paler; rectrices with greyish tips; rump, uppertail-coverts and tail greener, less bronzy purplish. Juvenile resembles female, has crown, throat and breast dull bronzy green, with broad pale buff fringes to feathers."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Amazilia.
Male_Text: "Adult: Upperparts metallic bronze or bronze green, the back usually greener. Rectrices metallic bronze, all but the central pair with a broad subterminal band of dark purplish bronze or blackish, glossed with purplish bronze; the tips of the two outer pairs of rectrices dull brownish gray. Remiges dark brownish slage or dusky. Underparts white, spotted with metallic bronze green from the malar region to the flanks. Undertail coverts usually with a faint pale brownish gray tinge. Sexes essentially identical; female usually with tips of outer rectrices paler."
Female_Text: "Adult: Upperparts metallic bronze or bronze green, the back usually greener. Rectrices metallic bronze, all but the central pair with a broad subterminal band of dark purplish bronze or blackish, glossed with purplish bronze; the tips of the two outer pairs of rectrices dull brownish gray. Remiges dark brownish slage or dusky. Underparts white, spotted with metallic bronze green from the malar region to the flanks. Undertail coverts usually with a faint pale brownish gray tinge. Sexes essentially identical; female usually with tips of outer rectrices paler."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Hylocharis.
Male_Hue: green, gold, bronze, copper, purple, blue
Male_Text: "Adult male: Crown, nape, back, scapulars, and wing coverts metallic green, becoming golden or bronzy on the rump and bright golden or coppery on the uppertail coverts. Rectrices brilliant golden bronze, tinged with golden green in some lights. Remiges dark brownish slate or dusky. Chin and extreme upper throat dull whitish, feathers tipped with metallic violet blue; rest of throat, and the upper breast, bright metallic violet blue. Lower breast and flanks metallic bronze green. Belly buffy grayish, slightly more buffy on lower buffy. Femoral tufts white. Undertail coverts grayish brown, broadly edged and tipped with cinnamon." Adult female: Similar to the male, but underparts paler. The violet blue of the throat usually is much more restricted and is broken with dull whitish margins to the feathers.
Female_Hue: green, gold, bronze, copper, purple, blue
Female_Text: "Adult male: Crown, nape, back, scapulars, and wing coverts metallic green, becoming golden or bronzy on the rump and bright golden or coppery on the uppertail coverts. Rectrices brilliant golden bronze, tinged with golden green in some lights. Remiges dark brownish slate or dusky. Chin and extreme upper throat dull whitish, feathers tipped with metallic violet blue; rest of throat, and the upper breast, bright metallic violet blue. Lower breast and flanks metallic bronze green. Belly buffy grayish, slightly more buffy on lower buffy. Femoral tufts white. Undertail coverts grayish brown, broadly edged and tipped with cinnamon." Adult female: Similar to the male, but underparts paler. The violet blue of the throat usually is much more restricted and is broken with dull whitish margins to the feathers.

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Juliamyia.
Male_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts metallic green, crown more glittering green in some subspecies; rump more or less bronze green. Rectrices blue black. Wings dusky, with a purple sheen. Throat and lower sides of the head brilliant metallic green; some individuals have a bluish cast to the gorget. Breast and flanks metallic violet blue. Tibial tufts white. Belly and undertail coverts dull black, with a blue or dull green sheen; sides of the belly adjacent to the tibial tufts partly white."Adult female: Upperparts metallic bronze green, bronzier on the rump and uppertail coverts. Rectrices blue black to dull bluish green; two outer rectrices tipped with pale gray. Wings dusky with a purple sheen. Underparts pale gray, whiter on the breast; on some individuals the sides of the throat are spotted with metallic green, especially in subspecies panamensis. Undertail coverts dull brownish gray."
Female_Text: "Adult male: Upperparts metallic green, crown more glittering green in some subspecies; rump more or less bronze green. Rectrices blue black. Wings dusky, with a purple sheen. Throat and lower sides of the head brilliant metallic green; some individuals have a bluish cast to the gorget. Breast and flanks metallic violet blue. Tibial tufts white. Belly and undertail coverts dull black, with a blue or dull green sheen; sides of the belly adjacent to the tibial tufts partly white."Adult female: Upperparts metallic bronze green, bronzier on the rump and uppertail coverts. Rectrices blue black to dull bluish green; two outer rectrices tipped with pale gray. Wings dusky with a purple sheen. Male_Text: "Definitive Basic Plumage. In G. galeata cachinnans, Definitive Basic plumage similar to Definitive Alternate plumage, except feathers of posterior underparts “broadly edged and tipped with white” (Oberholser 1974: 304), and in G. chloropus chloropus these margins average broader in females than in males, and in worn plumage white feather-tips on underparts reduced and upperparts with reduced bronzy tinge, appearing more dark grayish (Cramp and Simmons 1980a)."Definitive Alternate Plumage.In G. galeata cachinnans, head (except bare frontal shield) and neck Blackish Neutral Gray (82); back, breast, and remaining underparts similar in color but slightly paler, appearing Dark Neutral Gray (83), except feathers on center of belly appear whitish due to white feather-tips, feathers of uppermost sides and flanks with white streak along shaft of dorsal web, producing a white stripe along uppermost sides and flanks, central undertail coverts Blackish Neutral Gray, and lateral undertail coverts white. Lower back, rump, uppertail coverts, and inner upperwing coverts, Olive-Brown (28), with this color usually darker and more uniform on posterior upperparts and becoming slightly bronzy on wings and lower back. Outer upperwing coverts Dark Neutral Gray; alula and remiges dark brownish (Brownish Olive 29) except outer webs of alula-feathers and outermost primary edged white, and tips and margins of outer webs of primaries washed with Olive-Brown. Marginal coverts of leading edge of wing (carpal portion) also white. Rectrices Plumbeous (78) with slight gloss and with narrow, indistinct, slightly paler and more brownish bars. Under wing coverts Plumbeous or paler and margined with white; axillars dark Olive Gray (42; Forbush 1925, Ridgway and Friedmann 1941, Oberholser 1974). Sexes alike, except as noted under Definitive Basic plumage above

Male_Text: " Definitive Alternate.cquired by a partial Definitive Prealternate (Prenuptial) molt. Coots wintering in Alabama show a Nov–Dec peak in molt of head-, neck-, back-, rump-, scapular-, and breast feathers; second lesser peak of head and neck molt in Feb (Mcknight and Hepp 1999). It could not be determined whether latter Feb peak represented an extension of Prebasic molt, onset of Prealternate molt, or individual replacement of worn feathers. In any case, molt not confined to time period surrounding breeding season, as claimed by Gullion (Gullion 1953b), who indicated that coots undergo only 1 complete molt /yr. By either suspending or completing molt prior to period of lowest winter temperatures and reduced food availability (Jan), wintering coots probably reduce any additional nutrient or energetic costs associated with molt, so that total protein costs can be met by simply satisfying daily energy requirements (Mcknight and Hepp 1999).Head blackish mouse gray or blackish neutral gray on upper half, sometimes with faint-green or blue gloss. Back, scapulars, and upperwing coverts light slate; rump and uppertail coverts between dark olive-gray and dark mouse gray. Tail chaetura black. Upper wing coverts and tertials light slate gray, often tinged olive. Primaries and secondaries dark sepia gray with slightly paler inner webs and outer webs tinged ash gray. Broad, white tips on secondaries, forming a white trailing edge; shafts of primaries dark hair brown. Wing-bend white on leading edge, with narrow white edges along outer webs of outer primaries and outermost alula-feather. Chin, cheeks, throat, and sides of neck fuscous black; sides and flanks deep mouse gray; middle of belly neutral gray; remainder of underparts dull brownish neutral gray, except middle undertail coverts black; and lateral undertail coverts white. Wing-lining deep mouse gray, with feathers tipped or mixed with white. From late spring through summer, tips of upperwing- and body feathers may fade to pale gray or off-white through wear.

Male_Text: "Medium-sized marsh hen; total adult length 27–36 cm, mass 208–288 g. In adult, head, neck, and most underparts glossy purple, with olive-green upperparts, white undertail coverts, red bill with yellow tip and blue-white frontal shield (at juncture of bill and forehead), and yellowish legs and feet. Toes long (middle toe and claw 7–8 cm). Sexes alike in plumage and overlap in size; female mass about 10% less than male (Hunter 1986)." Definitive Alternate PlumageDefinitive Prealternate (Prenuptial) molt partial, probably involves smaller body feathers (Cramp and Simmons 1980a).Head, front, and sides of neck, and all underparts (except undertail coverts), mainly deep, glossy, bluish purple, becoming more blackish along base of bill and frontal shield, and dull blackish on lower belly, vent, and thighs. Under tail-coverts white. Hindneck, sides of back, and sides of breast pale blue, often washed green. Remainder of back, scapulars, rump through tail, inner greater and median upperwing coverts, and tertials, olive brown to olive green, but variable; back iridescent and sometimes more bluish, scapulars and rump sometimes brownish, upperwing coverts sometimes purer green, and tail toward iridescent olive-blue. Lesser upperwing coverts, outer median and greater wing coverts, outer webs of remiges and primary coverts, pale blue, with olive green wash on inner primaries (P1–P6 or P7), and near central median and greater wing coverts. Inner webs of remiges and primary coverts dark grayish brown. Axillaries and larger underwing coverts dark brown or gray brown, washed bronze or bluish, especially on outer webs, and larger underwing coverts sometimes narrowly tipped white. Smaller underwing coverts pale blue or blue green. Under surface of remiges and rectrices dull gray (Taylor 1998).

Notes: Species name listed as Porphyrio martinica in Birds of the World

Male_Text: "The wings are broad and rounded with a wingspan of about 1 m. The plumage is uniform dark olive-brown, although paler on the face, chin, and throat, with slight bronze iridescence on the wings and especially the tail. Most feathers have triangular white markings, largest on the wings and back, giving birds a spotted appearance." The Definitive Basic plumage is mostly dark olive-brown, darkest on hindneck, interscapulars, and lower back, with bronzy or purplish iridescence on wings and especially the tail. The ends of the primaries are darker than the wing coverts and the tail feathers are even darker brown. The lores, malar region, chin, and upper throat are dull white and unmarked or faintly streaked with brown. Most feathers, except the primaries and rectrices, have a wide white streak along the shaft that comes to point at end of feather. The overlapping of the larger feathers creates bold, bright-white triangles on the back, scapulars, and especially the wing coverts. Toward the neck, the triangles become much narrower and appear as streaks, giving a whitish cast to the neck and head. The white triangles on the wing coverts can be helpful in the field in tentatively identifying the sex of adults. Probably because adult males generally are larger than females, their wing-covert triangles seem wider, longer, and more prominent than do those of females. Long triangles on 1 or 2 of the outermost (largest) greater coverts are usually visible on males but are hidden on females (Bryan 1996b).
Female_Text: "The wings are broad and rounded with a wingspan of about 1 m. The plumage is uniform dark olive-brown, although paler on the face, chin, and throat, with slight bronze iridescence on the wings and especially the tail. Most feathers have triangular white markings, largest on the wings and back, giving birds a spotted appearance." The Definitive Basic plumage is mostly dark olive-brown, darkest on hindneck, interscapulars, and lower back, with bronzy or purplish iridescence on wings and especially the tail. The ends of the primaries are darker than the wing coverts and the tail feathers are even darker brown. The lores, malar region, chin, and upper throat are dull white and unmarked or faintly streaked with brown. Most feathers, except the primaries and rectrices, have a wide white streak along the shaft that comes to point at end of feather. The overlapping of the larger feathers creates bold, bright-white triangles on the back, scapulars, and especially the wing coverts. Toward the neck, the triangles become much narrower and appear as streaks, giving a whitish cast to the neck and head. The white triangles on the wing coverts can be helpful in the field in tentatively identifying the sex of adults. Probably because adult males generally are larger than females, their wing-covert triangles seem wider, longer, and more prominent than do those of females. Long triangles on 1 or 2 of the outermost (largest) greater coverts are usually visible on males but are hidden on females (Bryan 1996b).

Male_Text: "Present primarily Oct-Sep in North American populations. Head, neck, and upper chest uniformly black with faint bluish green gloss; white streak immediately below lower eyelid; back, scapulars, rump, and anterior median uppertail coverts plain grayish brown or brownish gray (similar to colors 119A and 119B); median anterior uppertail coverts sometimes edged white; lateral and posterior uppertail coverts white, the latter rarely with a few dusky spots or blotches. Lower chest, belly, undertail coverts, axillars, and underwing coverts white, the underwing coverts sometimes tipped with brownish gray, and the carpometacarpal region (wrist) spotted dusky. Inner primaries (p1-p4, less frequently p5, p5-p6, or p5-p7) with basal white areas, usually 25 mm or more in length, on their shafts and outer webs. Tips of upperwing median coverts, all exposed portions of greater coverts, and secondaries immediately distal to tertials immaculate white. More distal secondaries deep brownish gray with white on inner webs and basal part and distal edges of outer webs. Primaries and primary coverts dull black. Tail deep brownish gray becoming darker (sometimes nearly black) distally and white basally, the demarcation between white and dark of rectrices distinct (illustrated by Pyle 2008). Upperpart feathers, wing coverts, tertials, and rectrices all uniform in wear (all Basic), not showing molt limits as in Formative Plumage."
Female_Text: "Present primarily Oct-Sep in North American populations. Head, neck, and upper chest uniformly black with faint bluish green gloss; white streak immediately below lower eyelid; back, scapulars, rump, and anterior median uppertail coverts plain grayish brown or brownish gray (similar to colors 119A and 119B); median anterior uppertail coverts sometimes edged white; lateral and posterior uppertail coverts white, the latter rarely with a few dusky spots or blotches. Lower chest, belly, undertail coverts, axillars, and underwing coverts white, the underwing coverts sometimes tipped with brownish gray, and the carpometacarpal region (wrist) spotted dusky. Inner primaries (p1-p4, less frequently p5, p5-p6, or p5-p7) with basal white areas, usually 25 mm or more in length, on their shafts and outer webs. Tips of upperwing median coverts, all exposed portions of greater coverts, and secondaries immediately distal to tertials immaculate white. More distal secondaries deep brownish gray with white on inner webs and basal part and distal edges of outer webs. Primaries and primary coverts dull black. Tail deep brownish gray becoming darker (sometimes nearly black) distally and white basally, the demarcation between white and dark of rectrices distinct (illustrated by Pyle 2008). Upperpart feathers, wing coverts, tertials, and rectrices all uniform in wear (all Basic), not showing molt limits as in Formative Plumage."

Male_Text: "Southern Lapwings are sexually monochromatic. Adult Southern Lapwings have gray brown upperparts with a white belly and undertail coverts. The upper parts of the wings present a bronze green iridescent sheen. A black breast band extends up to the bird’s forecrown. A white patch of feathers of variable size may surround the forecrown part of the badge. However, some individuals do not present any white feathers surrounding the black facial badge, instead having only the characteristic gray feathers. A very distinctive characteristic of Southern Lapwings is the black filamentous crest, which can be raised to an upright position during ritualized behaviors. Primaries and most secondaries black. On the upper surface of the wing, the greater and median coverts are white, forming a diagonal white band across the wing in flight. Also, the underwing coverts are white, contrasting with the black under surfaces of the primaries and secondaries. Rump white. Basal half of tail white, distal half black, with a narrow white tip."
Female_Text: "Southern Lapwings are sexually monochromatic. Adult Southern Lapwings have gray brown upperparts with a white belly and undertail coverts. The upper parts of the wings present a bronze green iridescent sheen. A black breast band extends up to the bird’s forecrown. A white patch of feathers of variable size may surround the forecrown part of the badge. However, some individuals do not present any white feathers surrounding the black facial badge, instead having only the characteristic gray feathers. A very distinctive characteristic of Southern Lapwings is the black filamentous crest, which can be raised to an upright position during ritualized behaviors. Primaries and most secondaries black. On the upper surface of the wing, the greater and median coverts are white, forming a diagonal white band across the wing in flight. Also, the underwing coverts are white, contrasting with the black under surfaces of the primaries and secondaries. Rump white. Basal half of tail white, distal half black, with a narrow white tip."

Male_Text: "Head, neck, and breast black, with green or purplish iridescent sheen. Mantle, scapulars, tertials, and wing coverts, except for primary coverts, reddish to maroonish chestnut; primary coverts and rump dark maroon; tail purplish black. Underparts maroon-chestnut (Jenni 1996). According to Oberholser (Oberholser 1974) back, scapulars, tertials, and “lesser median” wing coverts bay glossed or mixed with maroon; rump and uppertail-coverts dark maroon; and greater wing coverts dark purplish brown or blackish maroon. Primaries and secondaries yellow, with greenish tinge described as lime green or chartreuse, with dark-brown or black tips. Outermost primaries edged with brown on outer web."
Female_Text: "Head, neck, and breast black, with green or purplish iridescent sheen. Mantle, scapulars, tertials, and wing coverts, except for primary coverts, reddish to maroonish chestnut; primary coverts and rump dark maroon; tail purplish black. Underparts maroon-chestnut (Jenni 1996). According to Oberholser (Oberholser 1974) back, scapulars, tertials, and “lesser median” wing coverts bay glossed or mixed with maroon; rump and uppertail-coverts dark maroon; and greater wing coverts dark purplish brown or blackish maroon. Primaries and secondaries yellow, with greenish tinge described as lime green or chartreuse, with dark-brown or black tips. Outermost primaries edged with brown on outer web."

Male_Text: "Head and neck, upper back, breast, and outer surface of closed wing brownish black with Dark Greenish (162) bronze iridescence, more pronounced in males; large white spot in anterior lores, white stripe over eye, white speckling on top and sides of head, neck, and upper breast; speckling finer and denser in males (CMH, REG); margins of scapulars white. Black of breast spreads onto white upper belly and black chevrons extend along white flanks under anterior third of closed wing; more prominent in males than females (CMH, REG). Lower back and rump immaculate white, shorter uppertail-coverts solid brownish or sooty black, longer uppertail-coverts and bases of tail feathers immaculate white; distal half of tail feathers blackish brown, tipped with white that becomes progressively wider, from just visible on central pair to 5–8 mm on outer rectrices. Remiges brownish black, the shafts white except at tips. Remiges with white tips that increase in extent inwardly from P6 (barely visible) through S10 (broad). White on base of outer web of remiges beginning on P5, decreasing in extent through innermost secondaries and increasing through S9, and with white on base of inner web beginning with P2 and increasing through S9. S10 like S9 but with larger subterminal brownish-black mark. Tertials, S11, and S12 brownish black with outer web of S11 edged white. Remaining wing feathers brownish black except inner primary coverts broadly tipped white, and greater coverts with white edges, broad white ends, and mostly (innermost and outermost feathers) to completely white inner web. Some to most median coverts edged white, some outer lesser coverts tipped white, and small white patch on innermost portion of forewing. White ends of primary- and greater coverts, together with white bases of remiges, form conspicuous white band across extended wing (K. Russell in litt.). Undersurface of wing and axillaries pure white, continuous with white of sides, rump, and vent; undersurface of remiges drab towards tips; undersurface of body below breast wholly white."
Female_Text: "Head and neck, upper back, breast, and outer surface of closed wing brownish black with Dark Greenish (162) bronze iridescence, more pronounced in males; large white spot in anterior lores, white stripe over eye, white speckling on top and sides of head, neck, and upper breast; speckling finer and denser in males (CMH, REG); margins of scapulars white. Black of breast spreads onto white upper belly and black chevrons extend along white flanks under anterior third of closed wing; more prominent in males than females (CMH, REG). Lower back and rump immaculate white, shorter uppertail-coverts solid brownish or sooty black, longer uppertail-coverts and bases of tail feathers immaculate white; distal half of tail feathers blackish brown, tipped with white that becomes progressively wider, from just visible on central pair to 5–8 mm on outer rectrices. Remiges brownish black, the shafts white except at tips. Remiges with white tips that increase in extent inwardly from P6 (barely visible) through S10 (broad). White on base of outer web of remiges beginning on P5, decreasing in extent through innermost secondaries and increasing through S9, and with white on base of inner web beginning with P2 and increasing through S9. S10 like S9 but with larger subterminal brownish-black mark. Tertials, S11, and S12 brownish black with outer web of S11 edged white. Remaining wing feathers brownish black except inner primary coverts broadly tipped white, and greater coverts with white edges, broad white ends, and mostly (innermost and outermost feathers) to completely white inner web. Some to most median coverts edged white, some outer lesser coverts tipped white, and small white patch on innermost portion of forewing. White ends of primary- and greater coverts, together with white bases of remiges, form conspicuous white band across extended wing (K. Russell in litt.). Undersurface of wing and axillaries pure white, continuous with white of sides, rump, and vent; undersurface of remiges drab towards tips; undersurface of body below breast wholly white."

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Aphriza. Monotypic.
Formerly placed in the genus Philomachus. Monotypic.
Recognized as monotypic by del Hoyo et al. (1992) and Clements (2000) and BNA. Howard and Moore recognized 2 subspecies: <i></> C.a. alba and C.a. rubida.</>

Male_Text: "Definitive Prebasic molt complete; begins early Jul and completed by late Oct (Figure 5); duration in individuals unknown, but probably about 60 d (REG). Generally commences when birds move to coast, though some C. p. ptilocnemis from St. Matthew I. begin early primary molt before leaving island for mainland (UAM specimens, REG). In all subspecies, molt of primaries sequential from P1 to P10. Following from captures and specimens C. p. couesi and C. p. tschuktschorum from Alaska; data combined as timing not significantly different between these populations (REG) but likely differences in timing between populations at extremes of range (e.g., C. p. tschuktschorum from Chukotka and Yukon Delta; needs study). Onset early Jul (1 late Jun record) and completion by late Oct; all birds in active wing molt by late Aug. Mean score (0–50) by 2-wk periods: 1–15 Jul, 4.2 ± 4.64 SD (range 0–28, n = 63); 16–31 Jul, 7.1 ±7.37 (range 0–28, n = 13); 1–15 Aug,20.2 ± 9.81 (range 0–40, n = 100);16–31 Aug, 33.9 ± 9.07 (range 7–46, n = 109); 1–15 Sep, 40.3 ± 7.64 (range23–49, n = 52); 16–30 Sep, 47.2 ±3.89 (range 20–50, n = 80); 1–15 Oct,48.5 ± 2.97 (range 35–50, n = 104). Molt of secondaries and rectrices begins when P4–P6 new and completed when P9 and P10 new (REG); similar pattern reported for Purple Sandpiper (Morrison 1976b). In C. p.ptilocnemis, wing, rump, uppertail coverts, and posterior underparts as in Definitive Alternate; rest of upper-parts Light Neutral Gray (85) to Pale Neutral Gray (86; all other subspecies Medium Neutral Gray [84] to Dark Neutral Gray [83]); scapulars and back feathers darker centrally, with a very faint purplish or bronzy gloss in certain light; head and neck light or pale gray, darker and nearly uniform on crown, paler and more or less streaked with white elsewhere; throat white, immaculate or sparsely streaked; breast white, irregularly marked with Pale Neutral Gray."
