annotation: Recognized as monotypic by del Hoyo et al. (1992), Clements (2000) and BNA. Howard and Moore (2003) recognizes 3 subspecies: <i></>C.m. belcheri, C.m....
Male_Text: Definitive Basic. "Head and neck generally dark slate-gray with black centers on crown feathers, slightly paler chin, blackish spot in front of eye, and narrow, diffuse white eyering. Some individuals have small white spots above lores or behind eyes, occasionally forming short and broken supercilium. Upperparts dark slate-gray to soft blackish brown (Pearson 1936); back and scapular feathers black with gray fringes and centers (of some feathers) faintly glossed purple. Tertials and wing coverts grayish black with narrow gray fringes, except inner wing coverts fringed white. Lower back and rump feathers grayish black with narrow gray fringes; uppertail coverts black with gray fringes and sometimes traces of broken white. Breast slate gray to brownish ash (feathers narrowly fringed white when fresh and appearing scaled). Remaining underparts white with distinct dark-gray streaks on sides and flanks (feathers with wedge-shaped central mark that broadens distally), sometimes forming continuous lines, narrow gray streaks or mottling on belly and vent, and dark-gray pointed marks on undertail coverts. Tail and wings generally as in Definitive Alternate plumage. Inner tail feathers grayish black, outer tail feathers light ashy. Greater and lesser wing coverts with tips rather square when new (Cramp and Simmons 1983)." Definitive Alternate. Crown blackish brown, streaked with rufous-cinnamon. Forehead and supercilium off-white with gray mottling, lores dusky, ear coverts reddish dusky. Streaks on lores and below eye to ear coverts dull dark gray with lighter mottling (off-white, pale gray, or pale brown). Diffuse off-white eyering. Feathers at base of bill dull dark gray with paler mottling. Sides of neck dark gray, streaked with buff. Back and scapulars blackish brown. Feathers fringed broadly with rufous-cinnamon (and whitish), sometimes forming 2 rufous-cinnamon spots at feather tip. Longer feathers have subterminal rufous-cinnamon side spots; fresh feathers narrowly tipped with white. Lower back, rump, and uppertail coverts slaty black to dusky, with faint pale-gray tips (some lateral feathers with partial white fringes). Some lateral uppertail coverts are dull black to pale gray and have broad white edges, often with white central mark. Rufous-cinnamon color of upperparts bleaches, wears rapidly, and fades to cinnamon-buff and pale buff in Jun–Jul. By Aug, only black feather centers remain. Chin and throat cream-buff with dark brown-gray spotting. Throat, neck, breast, and upper belly off-white with distinct dark streaks and spots becoming bolder on lower breast. Streaks colored brown to black; rarely, streaks fuse to form a solid dark patch on lower breast. Foreneck and sides of breast feathers black with broad white fringes, sometimes tinged cinnamon-pink at sides of breast. Lower belly and vent off-white, sometimes with elongated dusky-gray marks. Under tail-coverts slaty black. R1 black and sometimes glossed purple, fringed narrowly with cinnamon or off-white. Remaining rectrices dark gray with narrow white fringes, feathers becoming paler (medium gray) toward R6. Primaries dark gray, becoming blackish toward outer primaries (on outer webs and tips). Inner primaries dark gray with white borders on basal edges and tips. Shafts of primaries pale horn brown, becoming white at tips, except shaft of P10 entirely white. Secondaries dark gray, fringed white at tips. One (S8) and sometimes more (S7, S9) inner secondaries almost completely white; neighboring feathers (S7, S9) are white on bases and inner webs, becoming grayer distally (toward S5–S1). Median secondary coverts dark gray with poorly defined pale-gray fringe; outer feather tips rather square, innermost feather tips rounder with whiter fringe. Lesser secondary coverts blackish with narrow gray fringe; new coverts (occasionally present) black with pale cinnamon tips. Greater secondary coverts dark gray, narrowly tipped with white, with white tips becoming broad on innermost feathers. Combination of white on inner secondaries and greater wing coverts creates wing-stripe (clearly visible in flight), with broader white wedge on inner wing, and narrower bar distally. Underside of primaries darkish gray. Median and lesser under primary coverts, greater under primary coverts, and lesser under secondary coverts primarily gray; median under secondary coverts, inner greater under secondary coverts, and some shorter axillaries primarily white.
Female_Text: Definitive Basic. "Head and neck generally dark slate-gray with black centers on crown feathers, slightly paler chin, blackish spot in front of eye, and narrow, diffuse white eyering. Some individuals have small white spots above lores or behind eyes, occasionally forming short and broken supercilium. Upperparts dark slate-gray to soft blackish brown (Pearson 1936); back and scapular feathers black with gray fringes and centers (of some feathers) faintly glossed purple. Tertials and wing coverts grayish black with narrow gray fringes, except inner wing coverts fringed white. Lower back and rump feathers grayish black with narrow gray fringes; uppertail coverts black with gray fringes and sometimes traces of broken white. Breast slate gray to brownish ash (feathers narrowly fringed white when fresh and appearing scaled). Remaining underparts white with distinct dark-gray streaks on sides and flanks (feathers with wedge-shaped central mark that broadens distally), sometimes forming continuous lines, narrow gray streaks or mottling on belly and vent, and dark-gray pointed marks on undertail coverts. Tail and wings generally as in Definitive Alternate plumage. Inner tail feathers grayish black, outer tail feathers light ashy. Greater and lesser wing coverts with tips rather square when new (Cramp and Simmons 1983)." Definitive Alternate. Crown blackish brown, streaked with rufous-cinnamon. Forehead and supercilium off-white with gray mottling, lores dusky, ear coverts reddish dusky. Streaks on lores and below eye to ear coverts dull dark gray with lighter mottling (off-white, pale gray, or pale brown). Diffuse off-white eyering. Feathers at base of bill dull dark gray with paler mottling. Sides of neck dark gray, streaked with buff. Back and scapulars blackish brown. Feathers fringed broadly with rufous-cinnamon (and whitish), sometimes forming 2 rufous-cinnamon spots at feather tip. Longer feathers have subterminal rufous-cinnamon side spots; fresh feathers narrowly tipped with white. Lower back, rump, and uppertail coverts slaty black to dusky, with faint pale-gray tips (some lateral feathers with partial white fringes). Some lateral uppertail coverts are dull black to pale gray and have broad white edges, often with white central mark. Rufous-cinnamon color of upperparts bleaches, wears rapidly, and fades to cinnamon-buff and pale buff in Jun–Jul. By Aug, only black feather centers remain. Chin and throat cream-buff with dark brown-gray spotting. Throat, neck, breast, and upper belly off-white with distinct dark streaks and spots becoming bolder on lower breast. Streaks colored brown to black; rarely, streaks fuse to form a solid dark patch on lower breast. Foreneck and sides of breast feathers black with broad white fringes, sometimes tinged cinnamon-pink at sides of breast. Lower belly and vent off-white, sometimes with elongated dusky-gray marks. Under tail-coverts slaty black. R1 black and sometimes glossed purple, fringed narrowly with cinnamon or off-white. Remaining rectrices dark gray with narrow white fringes, feathers becoming paler (medium gray) toward R6. Primaries dark gray, becoming blackish toward outer primaries (on outer webs and tips). Inner primaries dark gray with white borders on basal edges and tips. Shafts of primaries pale horn brown, becoming white at tips, except shaft of P10 entirely white. Secondaries dark gray, fringed white at tips. One (S8) and sometimes more (S7, S9) inner secondaries almost completely white; neighboring feathers (S7, S9) are white on bases and inner webs, becoming grayer distally (toward S5–S1). Median secondary coverts dark gray with poorly defined pale-gray fringe; outer feather tips rather square, innermost feather tips rounder with whiter fringe. Lesser secondary coverts blackish with narrow gray fringe; new coverts (occasionally present) black with pale cinnamon tips. Greater secondary coverts dark gray, narrowly tipped with white, with white tips becoming broad on innermost feathers. Combination of white on inner secondaries and greater wing coverts creates wing-stripe (clearly visible in flight), with broader white wedge on inner wing, and narrower bar distally. Underside of primaries darkish gray. Median and lesser under primary coverts, greater under primary coverts, and lesser under secondary coverts primarily gray; median under secondary coverts, inner greater under secondary coverts, and some shorter axillaries primarily white.

annotation: Formerly placed in the genus Tryngites. Monotypic.
Monotypic. Referred to as Heterscelus brevipes by Clements (2000) and Howard and Moore (2003).
Monotypic. Referred to as Heterosceles incanus by Clements (2000) and Howard and Moore (2003).

Male_Text: "Plumage entirely brownish black, except as follows. In fresh plumage, sides of neck, remaining upperparts, and breast with greenish gloss. Remiges white on proximal portion of inner web (white tapers onto distal portion) and with black shafts, which become horn colored proximally. Some inner secondaries occasionally tipped white. Greater and median upper primary coverts becoming partly white on innermost feathers (white may be on inner, outer, or both webs of these feathers). Greater, and all but innermost median upperwing coverts white. These, together with innermost primary coverts, forming a large white patch on the wing. Under wing surface entirely white except marginal-coverts along leading edge, and tips of remiges (trailing edge of wing) black, and occasionally some outermost under primary coverts with brown spot at tip of each outer web. Amount of white on wing varies geographically. For additional details, see Cramp 1985a ."
Female_Text: "Plumage entirely brownish black, except as follows. In fresh plumage, sides of neck, remaining upperparts, and breast with greenish gloss. Remiges white on proximal portion of inner web (white tapers onto distal portion) and with black shafts, which become horn colored proximally. Some inner secondaries occasionally tipped white. Greater and median upper primary coverts becoming partly white on innermost feathers (white may be on inner, outer, or both webs of these feathers). Greater, and all but innermost median upperwing coverts white. These, together with innermost primary coverts, forming a large white patch on the wing. Under wing surface entirely white except marginal-coverts along leading edge, and tips of remiges (trailing edge of wing) black, and occasionally some outermost under primary coverts with brown spot at tip of each outer web. Amount of white on wing varies geographically. For additional details, see Cramp 1985a ."

Male_Text: "Adult winter. Ground coloration white on head and underparts, darker on upperparts. Forehead, lores, crown, ear coverts and eye line feathers black with broad white tips. In some individuals, white tips narrow, giving darker appearance to head area overall. Nape and foreneck white, occasionally suffused dusky gray. Mantle and back feathers black with iridescent sheen, with white fringes giving scalloped appearance to upperparts. Rump usually pure white. Uppertail coverts black with white fringes. Remiges and rectrices black with glossy sheen. Wings as adult summer."
Female_Text: "Adult winter. Ground coloration white on head and underparts, darker on upperparts. Forehead, lores, crown, ear coverts and eye line feathers black with broad white tips. In some individuals, white tips narrow, giving darker appearance to head area overall. Nape and foreneck white, occasionally suffused dusky gray. Mantle and back feathers black with iridescent sheen, with white fringes giving scalloped appearance to upperparts. Rump usually pure white. Uppertail coverts black with white fringes. Remiges and rectrices black with glossy sheen. Wings as adult summer."

annotation: Formerly treated as conspecific with Synthliboramphus hypoleucus, which together were known as Xantus's Murrelet.
Monotypic. Formerly considered conspecific with Synthliboramphus scrippsi, which together were known as Xantus's Murrelet.
Formerly placed in the genus Procelsterna (P. cerulea).

Male_Text: "Forehead and streak above lores to above front of eye white. Streak from lores to eye, and crown and nape down to eye and ear coverts deep black, slightly glossed blue when fresh. Central hindneck black, sides of neck white. Upperparts and upperwing coverts black; less deep and glossy than crown, except for lesser coverts, which contrast markedly with white leading edge of wing. Underparts, including undertail coverts, white, slightly tinged gray on flanks and belly when fresh. Tail black like upperparts, but outer web and much of base of inner web of R6 white. Remiges black with indistinct dull gray wedge to bases of inner web of outer primaries, slightly paler gray on inner web of outer primaries; outer web of primaries with dull-gray bloom when fresh. Under wing coverts and axillaries white; tips of greater underwing coverts often tinged gray. In worn plumage, white feather-bases of central hindneck and mantle exposed, forming white collar; upperparts more brown-black, especially on scapulars, tertials, and median and greater upperwing coverts; white outer web of tertial 6 partly abraded."
Female_Text: "Forehead and streak above lores to above front of eye white. Streak from lores to eye, and crown and nape down to eye and ear coverts deep black, slightly glossed blue when fresh. Central hindneck black, sides of neck white. Upperparts and upperwing coverts black; less deep and glossy than crown, except for lesser coverts, which contrast markedly with white leading edge of wing. Underparts, including undertail coverts, white, slightly tinged gray on flanks and belly when fresh. Tail black like upperparts, but outer web and much of base of inner web of R6 white. Remiges black with indistinct dull gray wedge to bases of inner web of outer primaries, slightly paler gray on inner web of outer primaries; outer web of primaries with dull-gray bloom when fresh. Under wing coverts and axillaries white; tips of greater underwing coverts often tinged gray. In worn plumage, white feather-bases of central hindneck and mantle exposed, forming white collar; upperparts more brown-black, especially on scapulars, tertials, and median and greater upperwing coverts; white outer web of tertial 6 partly abraded."

Male_Text: "Present primarily March–October. Forehead, crown, nape, lores, and auriculars plumbeous gray; sides of neck with 4–6 distinct and bold black and white stripes; back and scapulars black with 4 columns of rectangular white spots or transverse rows formed by white subterminal feather bands, black tips, and black shaft streaks (Figures 165–166 in Pyle [7]); rectrices blackish. Wing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage including distinct white spots to lesser and median upperwing coverts. Chin, throat, and foreneck black; lower throat and foreneck glossed with greenish (partially purplish in some lights or possibly representing introgression with Pacific Loon) (21); throat crossed by narrow transverse band of short vertical white streaks; remainder of underparts white except for black-and-white stripes to sides of breast, glossy black lower sides and flanks, partial dark vent strap, and longest undertail coverts blackish, usually with narrow white tips."
Female_Text: "Present primarily March–October. Forehead, crown, nape, lores, and auriculars plumbeous gray; sides of neck with 4–6 distinct and bold black and white stripes; back and scapulars black with 4 columns of rectangular white spots or transverse rows formed by white subterminal feather bands, black tips, and black shaft streaks (Figures 165–166 in Pyle [7]); rectrices blackish. Wing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage including distinct white spots to lesser and median upperwing coverts. Chin, throat, and foreneck black; lower throat and foreneck glossed with greenish (partially purplish in some lights or possibly representing introgression with Pacific Loon) (21); throat crossed by narrow transverse band of short vertical white streaks; remainder of underparts white except for black-and-white stripes to sides of breast, glossy black lower sides and flanks, partial dark vent strap, and longest undertail coverts blackish, usually with narrow white tips."

annotation: Monotypic. Considered subspecies of G. arctica by AOU (1957), Peters (1979), and del Hoyo, et al. (1992).
Male_Text: "Present primarily March–October. Forehead, crown, lores, and auriculars plumbeous gray, paling on upper nape and down back of neck to pale silvery gray; sides of neck with 5–7 indistinct black and white stripes; back and scapulars black with 4 columns of rectangular white spots or transverse rows formed by white subterminal feather bands, black tips, and black shaft streaks (Figures 165–166 in Pyle [9]); rectrices blackish brown. Wing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage, including distinct white spots to lesser and median upperwing coverts. Chin, throat, and foreneck black; lower throat and foreneck glossed with purplish, some birds showing green gloss in certain light conditions; throat crossed by narrow transverse band of short vertical white streaks; remainder of underparts white except for indistinct black stripes to sides of breast, glossy black lower sides and flanks, partial-to-complete dark vent strap, and longest undertail coverts blackish, usually with narrow white tips."
Female_Text: "Present primarily March–October. Forehead, crown, lores, and auriculars plumbeous gray, paling on upper nape and down back of neck to pale silvery gray; sides of neck with 5–7 indistinct black and white stripes; back and scapulars black with 4 columns of rectangular white spots or transverse rows formed by white subterminal feather bands, black tips, and black shaft streaks (Figures 165–166 in Pyle [9]); rectrices blackish brown. Wing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage, including distinct white spots to lesser and median upperwing coverts. Chin, throat, and foreneck black; lower throat and foreneck glossed with purplish, some birds showing green gloss in certain light conditions; throat crossed by narrow transverse band of short vertical white streaks; remainder of underparts white except for indistinct black stripes to sides of breast, glossy black lower sides and flanks, partial-to-complete dark vent strap, and longest undertail coverts blackish, usually with narrow white tips."

Male_Text: "Present primarily March–September and often in transitional state through October or early November. Head and neck blackish with variable greenish gloss (may appear purplish on hindneck and elsewhere in certain light); foreneck with a transverse line of small, white spots (6–12) laterally, and very short vertical stripes medially below head and an oblong patch of vertical, parallel, white stripes (these sometimes forked and may change with head and neck movements), on each side of neck, each patch widening toward rear, tapering front and back, and not quite joining in front or back on either side of neck. Remaining upperparts black with bluish or greenish sheen, most feathers with a pair of white, squarish subterminal patches (Figures 169–170 in 39), small and rounded on anterior mantle, back, and rump, increasing in size rearward on mantle and becoming largest, and rectangular in shape, on scapulars forming transverse rows. Rectrices black; upperwing and underwing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage. Lower throat with sharp line of demarcation between black neck and white breast; underparts below throat primarily white, the sides of the upper breast with black stripes that connect the black neck to the white spotted sides that become progressively shorter towards center of breast, the flanks black with 1–2 white spots on each feather; undertail coverts brownish black and tipped white; vent with a dark brown band."
Female_Text: "Present primarily March–September and often in transitional state through October or early November. Head and neck blackish with variable greenish gloss (may appear purplish on hindneck and elsewhere in certain light); foreneck with a transverse line of small, white spots (6–12) laterally, and very short vertical stripes medially below head and an oblong patch of vertical, parallel, white stripes (these sometimes forked and may change with head and neck movements), on each side of neck, each patch widening toward rear, tapering front and back, and not quite joining in front or back on either side of neck. Remaining upperparts black with bluish or greenish sheen, most feathers with a pair of white, squarish subterminal patches (Figures 169–170 in 39), small and rounded on anterior mantle, back, and rump, increasing in size rearward on mantle and becoming largest, and rectangular in shape, on scapulars forming transverse rows. Rectrices black; upperwing and underwing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage. Lower throat with sharp line of demarcation between black neck and white breast; underparts below throat primarily white, the sides of the upper breast with black stripes that connect the black neck to the white spotted sides that become progressively shorter towards center of breast, the flanks black with 1–2 white spots on each feather; undertail coverts brownish black and tipped white; vent with a dark brown band."

Male_Text: "Basic. Present primarily October–February. Crown and hindneck pale gray; nape primarily whitish, forming pale hind collar, often with dark medial streak; back feathers squared and dark brown with whitish to pale gray corners (Figure 169 in Pyle [40]), cerated banded appearance, except longest scapulars which have light subterminal marks or bands; one or more alternate back feathers sometimes retained, black with large white squares (Figure 170 in Pyle [40]); lower back and rump gray; uppertail coverts and tail blackish with thin white tips. Lores, face, and auriculars whitish, extending up to or above eye, the posterior auriculars often darker, forming crescent-shaped marks extending from sides of crown; feathers on sides of neck white with dark brown tips, producing mottled appearance, the brown sometimes extending around the sides of neck in middle portion of neck (43). Upperwing coverts blackish with distinct white circular spots (Figure 169 in Pyle [40]); remiges and alula blackish to brownish black, the remiges glossed purple on outer webs and tips when fresh, paler on inner webs and at base; primaries with whitish shafts (paler than in Common Loon); tertials glossy blackish with single or sometimes paired white spots near tip. Chin, throat, foreneck, and remaining underparts white, the feathers on sides of upper breast with brown centers creating streaked effect; upper flank feathers with diffuse darker centers; vent with brownish band; undertail coverts brown basally with broad white tips; underwing coverts primarily white, the undewing primary coverts, greater coverts and axillars with brown to grayish median streaks. Definitive Basic Plumage best separated from similar predefinitive plumages primarily by the upperwing coverts being glossy blackish with white spots.ALTERNATE.Present primarily March–September, often through October, and occasionally through November. Head and neck blackish with variable purplish gloss (may appear greenish on hindneck and elsewhere in certain light), the throat with a coarse transverse bar of 4–8 short vertical white streaks and sides of neck with usually less than 12 but rarely up to 14, longer, vertical white streaks on either side of middle of neck, forming half collar which usually does not meet in front or back of neck (each white neck patch composed of fewer, coarser white streaks than corresponding patches in Common Loon). Remaining upperparts black, most feathers with a pair of white, squarish subterminal patches (Figures 169–170 in Pyle [40]), largest on scapulars, smaller on upper mantle and rump, the rump often sparsely spotted, and the lower back and uppertail coverts usually black without spots (white marks on scapulars larger than in Common Loon, usually > 10 mm wide vs. < 10 mm wide in Common Loon; 40). Rectrices black; wing feathers as in Definitive Basic Plumage. Underparts below throat primarily white, the sides of the upper breast with black stripes that connect the black neck to the white spotted sides which become progressively shorter towards center of breast, the flanks black with 1–2 white spots on each feather, the undertail coverts brownish black tipped white, and the vent with a dark brown band. Some individuals in Third Alternate Plumage likely do not acquire full definitive alternate head or back appearance (40; study based on marked, known-age birds needed).

Male_Text: "Acquired at least by fourth calendar year (JAR, MCC). Entire head and upper neck naked. Alulae, greater primary coverts, first 2 secondary coverts, rectrices, secondaries, and primaries dark black, with greenish or purplish sheen. Remaining feathering bright white, but under tail coverts longer, more plumelike and extend beyond the rectrices. A band of salmon-pink underwing coverts clearly visible when the stork fully extends the wings; less obvious faint pink feathers may occur on the breast, belly, back and undertail coverts (Kahl 1972)."

"Sexes differ in size and plumage coloration. Male smaller than female (Table 1) and entirely black, except for brownish inner secondaries on upperwing, and patch of bare skin (gular sac) on lower neck. Gular sac becomes bright red and is inflated like a large balloon during courtship displays and early incubation period, but becomes pale orange and shrinks to become barely visible at other times of the year. At close range, male also glossed purple on head and green on neck, scapulars, and upperwing. Male legs and feet black or gray to brownish black." Female entirely blackish brown except for prominent white patch across breast and uppermost belly (extending variably to sides of neck and with a narrow wedge of dark color extending from throat onto center of upper breast), white tips across axillaries forming 3–4 lines on underwing, and a pale tan to dirty white ‘alar' bar on upperwing which extends diagonally inward from the crook on leading edge of wing. Head and upperparts with less extensive gloss than male (mostly restricted to back of head and neck), and gular sac absent. Female legs and feet mauvish to pink." Male. Entirely black, with metallic purple sheen especially on back and scapulars, green gloss to crown, nape and wings; lanceolate feathers of crown, nape, back and scapulars. Inner secondaries brownish forming a pale bar or wedge on trailing edge of inner wing (Howell 1994). Wings long, narrow, pointed; tail long and narrow, held either in forked position or closed with overlapping outer rectrices giving appearance of slightly swollen tip to tail. Female. Blackish brown on head and upperparts, with slight purple and green gloss; lesser wing coverts, along with inner median and greater wing coverts, grayish brown, pale tan to dirty white forming distinct pale ‘alar' bar, extending diagonally inwards towards body from bend on leading edge of wing. Inner secondaries as in male. Sides of neck, whole breast, and sides of upper belly, white, extending as pale scalloping into axillary region. Hind neck paler, forming light collar. Narrow wedge of dark color extends from throat into center of upper breast. Black area on belly protrudes forward into white breast patch, forming a somewhat narrow and tapered forward protrusion and creating a distinctive bilobed (U) shape to white breast. Wing and tail shape as in adult male.
Female_Text: "Sexes differ in size and plumage coloration. Male smaller than female (Table 1) and entirely black, except for brownish inner secondaries on upperwing, and patch of bare skin (gular sac) on lower neck. Gular sac becomes bright red and is inflated like a large balloon during courtship displays and early incubation period, but becomes pale orange and shrinks to become barely visible at other times of the year. At close range, male also glossed purple on head and green on neck, scapulars, and upperwing. Male legs and feet black or gray to brownish black." Female entirely blackish brown except for prominent white patch across breast and uppermost belly (extending variably to sides of neck and with a narrow wedge of dark color extending from throat onto center of upper breast), white tips across axillaries forming 3–4 lines on underwing, and a pale tan to dirty white ‘alar' bar on upperwing which extends diagonally inward from the crook on leading edge of wing. Head and upperparts with less extensive gloss than male (mostly restricted to back of head and neck), and gular sac absent. Female legs and feet mauvish to pink." Male. Entirely black, with metallic purple sheen especially on back and scapulars, green gloss to crown, nape and wings; lanceolate feathers of crown, nape, back and scapulars. Inner secondaries brownish forming a pale bar or wedge on trailing edge of inner wing (Howell 1994). Wings long, narrow, pointed; tail long and narrow, held either in forked position or closed with overlapping outer rectrices giving appearance of slightly swollen tip to tail. Female. Blackish brown on head and upperparts, with slight purple and green gloss; lesser wing coverts, along with inner median and greater wing coverts, grayish brown, pale tan to dirty white forming distinct pale ‘alar' bar, extending diagonally inwards towards body from bend on leading edge of wing. Inner secondaries as in male. Sides of neck, whole breast, and sides of upper belly, white, extending as pale scalloping into axillary region. Hind neck paler, forming light collar. Narrow wedge of dark color extends from throat into center of upper breast. Black area on belly protrudes forward into white breast patch, forming a somewhat narrow and tapered forward protrusion and creating a distinctive bilobed (U) shape to white breast. Wing and tail shape as in adult male.

Male_Text: "Both sexes have diagonal buff bar across upperwing coverts (absent in some; Nelson 1975a). Malevideo has dark purple-green or green sheen on dorsal feathers of head, neck, and scapulars; feathers of nape, mantle, and scapulars lanceolate in shape. Color and extent of sheen variable, perhaps by region, but needs study: Murphy (Murphy 1936) states sheen on Great Frigatebird green, blue, and bronzy purple; Harrison (Harrison 1983b), glossed green; Howell (Howell 1994), mostly green. On Johnston Atoll and Northwestern Hawaiian Is., predominately green, but with obvious purple (VGM, EAS). Male inflates large, red gular sac during courtship; sac deflates, shrinks, and fades to pale orange soon after pairing. Femalevideo has black head and nape sharply demarcated from gray chin and throat, which merge into white breastvideo ; black head also contrasts with paler brown hindneck and upper mantle; minimal sheen of purple-green present on back scapulars only; lanceolate nape and mantle feathers shorter than in male; pale brownish fringes on most of lesser upperwing secondary coverts form a noticeable wing panel." Male. All plumage black; glossy black-green with glossy purple shades on back of head, neck and mantle, generally only on outer web of feathers; concealed feather bases dark brown. Head, neck, mantle, scapulars lanceolate (longer than female's): at nape, about 30 mm long, middle of mantle about 40 mm long, lower margins of mantle about 75 mm long. Bare, distensible gular sac over throat and foreneck (mostly not visible when not breeding); when inflated, appears red. Pale bars on wings formed by pale tips on upperwing coverts; become duller and browner with wear. Breast and belly glossy pale black; concealed feather bases dark brown on breast, light gray-brown on belly. Axillaries have pale gray-brown to gray tips forming generally visible scallops; pale tips on axillaries can be fairly broad and whitish in some birds, may have some white on inner side of thigh. On underwing, greater primary coverts and greater secondary coverts black-brown, often paler brown on some lesser coverts forming a weak bar on distal half of tract, remiges and greater coverts with some grey bloom contrasting with blacker forewing. Flank-feathers black-brown to brown; lanceolate in shape, outer ones 45 mm long." Female. Head, neck, scapulars similar to male; lanceolate feathers at nape about 25 mm long (much shorter than male's). Sides of neck and upper mantle glossy black-green with some purple, not as extensive or obvious as in male. Bare gular pouch covers chin, is light salmon color when breeding, but rarely visible. Throat to lower foreneck light gray. Back, scapulars, rump, belly, and tail black to black-brown; concealed feather bases dark brown. Upper wing similar to male, obvious pale bar on upperwing coverts (feathers have brown center and light brown tips, light brown changing to grayish when worn). White of breast has broad inverted U-shape at bottom where black belly extends into it. May have pale gray-brown to gray tips on axillaries forming visible scallops.
Female_Text: "Both sexes have diagonal buff bar across upperwing coverts (absent in some; Nelson 1975a). Malevideo has dark purple-green or green sheen on dorsal feathers of head, neck, and scapulars; feathers of nape, mantle, and scapulars lanceolate in shape. Color and extent of sheen variable, perhaps by region, but needs study: Murphy (Murphy 1936) states sheen on Great Frigatebird green, blue, and bronzy purple; Harrison (Harrison 1983b), glossed green; Howell (Howell 1994), mostly green. On Johnston Atoll and Northwestern Hawaiian Is., predominately green, but with obvious purple (VGM, EAS). Male inflates large, red gular sac during courtship; sac deflates, shrinks, and fades to pale orange soon after pairing. Femalevideo has black head and nape sharply demarcated from gray chin and throat, which merge into white breastvideo ; black head also contrasts with paler brown hindneck and upper mantle; minimal sheen of purple-green present on back scapulars only; lanceolate nape and mantle feathers shorter than in male; pale brownish fringes on most of lesser upperwing secondary coverts form a noticeable wing panel." Male. All plumage black; glossy black-green with glossy purple shades on back of head, neck and mantle, generally only on outer web of feathers; concealed feather bases dark brown. Head, neck, mantle, scapulars lanceolate (longer than female's): at nape, about 30 mm long, middle of mantle about 40 mm long, lower margins of mantle about 75 mm long. Bare, distensible gular sac over throat and foreneck (mostly not visible when not breeding); when inflated, appears red. Pale bars on wings formed by pale tips on upperwing coverts; become duller and browner with wear. Breast and belly glossy pale black; concealed feather bases dark brown on breast, light gray-brown on belly. Axillaries have pale gray-brown to gray tips forming generally visible scallops; pale tips on axillaries can be fairly broad and whitish in some birds, may have some white on inner side of thigh. On underwing, greater primary coverts and greater secondary coverts black-brown, often paler brown on some lesser coverts forming a weak bar on distal half of tract, remiges and greater coverts with some grey bloom contrasting with blacker forewing. Flank-feathers black-brown to brown; lanceolate in shape, outer ones 45 mm long." Female. Head, neck, scapulars similar to male; lanceolate feathers at nape about 25 mm long (much shorter than male's). Sides of neck and upper mantle glossy black-green with some purple, not as extensive or obvious as in male. Bare gular pouch covers chin, is light salmon color when breeding, but rarely visible. Throat to lower foreneck light gray. Back, scapulars, rump, belly, and tail black to black-brown; concealed feather bases dark brown. Upper wing similar to male, obvious pale bar on upperwing coverts (feathers have brown center and light brown tips, light brown changing to grayish when worn). White of breast has broad inverted U-shape at bottom where black belly extends into it. May have pale gray-brown to gray tips on axillaries forming visible scallops.

Male_Text: "Male. Entire plumage black (glossed green on head, neck, and part of body), with the following exceptions: Tail deep brownish subterminally, paling to white at tip (white tip may disappear with wear). Upper back feathers have small central pale-silver gray spot. Lesser wing coverts centrally spotted, and median and greater wing coverts have pale silvery gray outer web and innermost portion of inner web (more extensive on median coverts), forming broad silver-gray patch on wing; innermost greater coverts and innermost secondaries, however, are black with silver-gray streak along shaft (mainly on inner portion of outer web). Scapulars lanceolate and elongated, and rearmost scapulars broader and greatly enlarged, completely overlying tertials. All scapulars have median silver-gray streak along shaft, except largest (rearmost) feather has broad silver-gray streak mainly on inner web, and large scapulars underlying this feather are black with silver-gray spot at tip. Outer webs of central pair of rectrices (R1) and longest scapular feather (not inner secondaries, contra Palmer 1962a) have transverse corrugations, although corrugations are more pronounced in Definitive Alternate plumage (Owre 1967a). Other long scapulars overlying inner greater coverts also have less noticeable and more widely spaced indentations." Female. Head, neck, and upper portion of breast and back tawny buff (becoming darker and more brownish on crown and whitish on lower portion of face and chin), with rich chestnut band across breast, separating buff on throat from blackish belly (chestnut band less pronounced in North American birds than in Central and South American birds). Feathers of upper back have brown edges and white centers; remainder of feathering similar to that of Definitive Basic male, except dark portions more dusky brownish than black. DEFINITIVE ALT. Male. Similar to Definitive Basic male, except black surfaces become more glossy and olivaceous (DSC); feathers of hindneck somewhat elongated, forming a mane; series of filamentous plumes (white with violet or brownish cast, fading to white) present on sides of crown, nape, and upper neck; silvery-white areas in feathering somewhat larger and scapulars more elongated. No information on whether plumes on head and neck persist until Prebasic molt or are shed early. Female. Similar to Definitive Basic female, except some whitish, loose-webbed feathers are present on side of head and upper neck.
Female_Text: "Male. Entire plumage black (glossed green on head, neck, and part of body), with the following exceptions: Tail deep brownish subterminally, paling to white at tip (white tip may disappear with wear). Upper back feathers have small central pale-silver gray spot. Lesser wing coverts centrally spotted, and median and greater wing coverts have pale silvery gray outer web and innermost portion of inner web (more extensive on median coverts), forming broad silver-gray patch on wing; innermost greater coverts and innermost secondaries, however, are black with silver-gray streak along shaft (mainly on inner portion of outer web). Scapulars lanceolate and elongated, and rearmost scapulars broader and greatly enlarged, completely overlying tertials. All scapulars have median silver-gray streak along shaft, except largest (rearmost) feather has broad silver-gray streak mainly on inner web, and large scapulars underlying this feather are black with silver-gray spot at tip. Outer webs of central pair of rectrices (R1) and longest scapular feather (not inner secondaries, contra Palmer 1962a) have transverse corrugations, although corrugations are more pronounced in Definitive Alternate plumage (Owre 1967a). Other long scapulars overlying inner greater coverts also have less noticeable and more widely spaced indentations." Female. Head, neck, and upper portion of breast and back tawny buff (becoming darker and more brownish on crown and whitish on lower portion of face and chin), with rich chestnut band across breast, separating buff on throat from blackish belly (chestnut band less pronounced in North American birds than in Central and South American birds). Feathers of upper back have brown edges and white centers; remainder of feathering similar to that of Definitive Basic male, except dark portions more dusky brownish than black. DEFINITIVE ALT. Male. Similar to Definitive Basic male, except black surfaces become more glossy and olivaceous (DSC); feathers of hindneck somewhat elongated, forming a mane; series of filamentous plumes (white with violet or brownish cast, fading to white) present on sides of crown, nape, and upper neck; silvery-white areas in feathering somewhat larger and scapulars more elongated. No information on whether plumes on head and neck persist until Prebasic molt or are shed early. Female. Similar to Definitive Basic female, except some whitish, loose-webbed feathers are present on side of head and upper neck.

Male_Text: "DEF BAS."Definitive Prebasic molt complete; occurs late summer–fall. Definitive Basic plumage dull blackish overall; upperparts slightly browner; scapulars and upperwing coverts have blackish margins. Secondaries and inner webs of primaries brownish; secondaries have darker margins. Wing-lining brownish, with green or purple gloss. Concealed down and bases of contour feathers light grayish brown. Grayish brown feathers around base of gular pouch taper out behind and below eyes." DEF ALT. Definitive Prealternate Molt partial (includes head and neck, but full extent unknown); occurs Dec–Jan. Definitive Alternate plumage similar to Definitive Basic, but brighter, with purple green gloss on head and neck; light feathered area around base of gular pouch brownish yellow. Whitish or creamy filoplumes, about 60 mm long on sides of neck. Other nearly white plumes on scapular area, 20–30 per side, 30–70 mm long (mean 50 mm). Plumes obvious Dec–Mar; worn away by Jul (14). Sexes similar.
Female_Text: "DEF BAS."Definitive Prebasic molt complete; occurs late summer–fall. Definitive Basic plumage dull blackish overall; upperparts slightly browner; scapulars and upperwing coverts have blackish margins. Secondaries and inner webs of primaries brownish; secondaries have darker margins. Wing-lining brownish, with green or purple gloss. Concealed down and bases of contour feathers light grayish brown. Grayish brown feathers around base of gular pouch taper out behind and below eyes." DEF ALT. Definitive Prealternate Molt partial (includes head and neck, but full extent unknown); occurs Dec–Jan. Definitive Alternate plumage similar to Definitive Basic, but brighter, with purple green gloss on head and neck; light feathered area around base of gular pouch brownish yellow. Whitish or creamy filoplumes, about 60 mm long on sides of neck. Other nearly white plumes on scapular area, 20–30 per side, 30–70 mm long (mean 50 mm). Plumes obvious Dec–Mar; worn away by Jul (14). Sexes similar.

Male_Text: DEF BAS."Feathering black or Sepia, variably glossed iridescent emerald, purple, or bronze. Concealed bases of contour feathers Sepia or dark Natal Brown. A single crest near forehead often present, never prominent. Crown and feathered border of gular pouch black, glossed iridescent emerald. Head and body black, glossed iridescent purple. Wings and tail black, rarely glossed iridescent purple or bronze; color varies with angle of light. Wing-lining dark Natal Brown, rarely glossed iridescent emerald or purple. Forehead bare, dark Scarlet; often with scattered small dark Natal Brown feathers. Neck usually with some (often many) small white filoplumes." DEF ALT. Definitive Prealternate molt partial (6). Unknown whether acquired in second or third year of life. Plumage likely acquired in winter or early spring and likely retained until late summer or fall. Differs from Definitive Basic as follows: Higher gloss throughout. Two crests, one over forehead, other at junction of crown and nape, black crests glossed with iridescent emerald. Club-shaped filoplumes 25–40 mm long distributed along front, back, and sides of neck; most shed by time of egg-laying. Large white patch on lower flanks, which begins to disappear (feathers shed) by end of breeding."
Female_Text: DEF BAS."Feathering black or Sepia, variably glossed iridescent emerald, purple, or bronze. Concealed bases of contour feathers Sepia or dark Natal Brown. A single crest near forehead often present, never prominent. Crown and feathered border of gular pouch black, glossed iridescent emerald. Head and body black, glossed iridescent purple. Wings and tail black, rarely glossed iridescent purple or bronze; color varies with angle of light. Wing-lining dark Natal Brown, rarely glossed iridescent emerald or purple. Forehead bare, dark Scarlet; often with scattered small dark Natal Brown feathers. Neck usually with some (often many) small white filoplumes." DEF ALT. Definitive Prealternate molt partial (6). Unknown whether acquired in second or third year of life. Plumage likely acquired in winter or early spring and likely retained until late summer or fall. Differs from Definitive Basic as follows: Higher gloss throughout. Two crests, one over forehead, other at junction of crown and nape, black crests glossed with iridescent emerald. Club-shaped filoplumes 25–40 mm long distributed along front, back, and sides of neck; most shed by time of egg-laying. Large white patch on lower flanks, which begins to disappear (feathers shed) by end of breeding."

Male_Text: DEF BAS. "Present primarily August-January. All contour feathering black with metallic gloss; concealed down and bases of all contour feathers pale grayish brown. Head with emerald gloss; neck glossed ultramarine violet; back and breast feathering glossed emerald to turquoise, more bronze on scapulars and becoming duller ventrally on underparts; rectrices with slight bronze gloss. Upperwing coverts, secondaries, and tertials glossed greenish to bronze; primaries brownish black. Underwing coverts dark brown with slight greenish or purplish gloss. Some individuals in Third Basic Plumage may show slight brownish on breast or be indistinguishable from Second Basic Plumage (10)." Definitive Basic Plumage often characterized by 2-3 sets of basic feathers among primaries and secondaries, in Staffelmauser patterns; replacement sets in primaries defined by a worn feather immediately distal to a fresh proximal feather, and those of secondaries showing mixed generations in various sequences (18, 22, 10). Older basic feathers not as contrastingly narrow and brown as retained juvenile feathers after incomplete Second Prebasic Molt. Number of sets in primaries equates to minimum ages of 2–4 years (22,10); individuals wintering in Asia and northwestern North America may average more sets in older birds than those wintering in California." DEF ALT. "Present primarily January–August. Similar to Definitive Basic Plumage except gloss of head, neck, and often breast stronger based on newer feathering; frontal and distal crown feathers elongated, forming two moderate-sized crests, over center front of crown and where crown meets nape. Sides of neck with numerous slender white filoplumes, mostly 20–30 mm long (longest 35 mm) scattered among contour feathers; some also on interscapular region; very brittle and easily broken or lost. Lower flanks with conspicuous white patches of filoplumes on each side.
Female_Text: DEF BAS. "Present primarily August-January. All contour feathering black with metallic gloss; concealed down and bases of all contour feathers pale grayish brown. Head with emerald gloss; neck glossed ultramarine violet; back and breast feathering glossed emerald to turquoise, more bronze on scapulars and becoming duller ventrally on underparts; rectrices with slight bronze gloss. Upperwing coverts, secondaries, and tertials glossed greenish to bronze; primaries brownish black. Underwing coverts dark brown with slight greenish or purplish gloss. Some individuals in Third Basic Plumage may show slight brownish on breast or be indistinguishable from Second Basic Plumage (10)." Definitive Basic Plumage often characterized by 2-3 sets of basic feathers among primaries and secondaries, in Staffelmauser patterns; replacement sets in primaries defined by a worn feather immediately distal to a fresh proximal feather, and those of secondaries showing mixed generations in various sequences (18, 22, 10). Older basic feathers not as contrastingly narrow and brown as retained juvenile feathers after incomplete Second Prebasic Molt. Number of sets in primaries equates to minimum ages of 2–4 years (22,10); individuals wintering in Asia and northwestern North America may average more sets in older birds than those wintering in California." DEF ALT. "Present primarily January–August. Similar to Definitive Basic Plumage except gloss of head, neck, and often breast stronger based on newer feathering; frontal and distal crown feathers elongated, forming two moderate-sized crests, over center front of crown and where crown meets nape. Sides of neck with numerous slender white filoplumes, mostly 20–30 mm long (longest 35 mm) scattered among contour feathers; some also on interscapular region; very brittle and easily broken or lost. Lower flanks with conspicuous white patches of filoplumes on each side.

Male_Text: DEF BAS. "Head, lower neck, center of upper back, lower back, rump, uppertail coverts and underparts black with iridescent bluish gloss. Sides of upper back, scapulars, wing coverts bronze with iridescent greenish gloss, feathers rounded and bordered with black. Tail graduated, with 14 black rectrices; shafts gray. Remiges brownish-black, secondaries with iridescent greenish-bronze gloss. Underwing dull, browner. All feathers browner when worn." DEF ALT. Adjacent to bare facial skin is a border of short, white feathering on cheeks, throat, and chin. Brown tips described by Palmer (Palmer 1962a) as wearing off, thus appear whiter than Basic. Remainder of head and neck black with blue iridescent sheen; elongated, pointed black feathers on center of nape and hindneck form a short medial crest. White feathers (nuptial plumes) overlay the black on crown, upper neck and lower throat, but not in the crest, nor in a dark band adjacent to the white cheek. These white feathers are long, very narrow, and loose-textured with a range of forms including filoplumes. In some birds (probably older), head and upper neck appear mostly white. Conspicuous patch of white feathers on each thigh; these are much longer and broader than head plumes but of similar loose texture. Remaining plumage retained from Definitive Basic plumage.
Female_Text: DEF BAS. "Head, lower neck, center of upper back, lower back, rump, uppertail coverts and underparts black with iridescent bluish gloss. Sides of upper back, scapulars, wing coverts bronze with iridescent greenish gloss, feathers rounded and bordered with black. Tail graduated, with 14 black rectrices; shafts gray. Remiges brownish-black, secondaries with iridescent greenish-bronze gloss. Underwing dull, browner. All feathers browner when worn." DEF ALT. Adjacent to bare facial skin is a border of short, white feathering on cheeks, throat, and chin. Brown tips described by Palmer (Palmer 1962a) as wearing off, thus appear whiter than Basic. Remainder of head and neck black with blue iridescent sheen; elongated, pointed black feathers on center of nape and hindneck form a short medial crest. White feathers (nuptial plumes) overlay the black on crown, upper neck and lower throat, but not in the crest, nor in a dark band adjacent to the white cheek. These white feathers are long, very narrow, and loose-textured with a range of forms including filoplumes. In some birds (probably older), head and upper neck appear mostly white. Conspicuous patch of white feathers on each thigh; these are much longer and broader than head plumes but of similar loose texture. Remaining plumage retained from Definitive Basic plumage.

Male_Text: DEF BAS. " Present primarily Aug–Jul. Head, neck, lower back, rump, and uppertail coverts black with dull greenish gloss; feathers of upper back, scapulars, and upperwing coverts brownish gray with bronze gloss present to varying degrees, widely margined with glossy black, forming scaled appearance to upperparts when fresh. Feathers broader and rounder than in previous plumages (Pyle 2008). Tail graduated (wedge-shaped), black to blackish brown; alula black; remiges and rectrices black to brownish black (browner when worn), with dull gloss on dorsal surface. Short, thick, light-brownish down present but invisible below feather coat. No aftershafts. Some individuals in Third Basic Plumage may show slight brownish wash on breast and retained juvenile feathers (among p10 and s9–s11) among two generations of basic feathers (Pyle 2008), but most indistinguishable from later basic plumages." Definitive Basic Plumage often characterized by 2-4 sets of basic feathers among primaries and secondaries, in Staffelmauser patterns; replacement sets in primaries defined by a worn feather immediately distal to a fresh proximal feather, and those of secondaries showing mixed generations in various sequences (Pyle 2006, 2008). Older basic feathers not as contrastingly narrow and brown as retained juvenile feathers after incomplete Second Prebasic Molt. Number of sets in primaries equates to minimum ages of 2–5 years (Pyle 2008); individuals of northern breeding populations may average more sets than those of southern populations." DEF ALT. " Present primarily Mar–Aug. Similar to Definitive Basic Plumage except some feathers of head, neck, and often breast replaced with glossier feathers. Ornamental. ear-like nuptial crests, source of the specific name auritus, located above and behind eye in spring. The crests are modified contour feathers, narrow, with separated barbs; color variable—black in east, mostly white in west; length to 78 mm in western birds, to 38 mm in east; plumes straighter in east, curlier in west. Up to 88 plumes recorded but usually 40–60 per side in male, fewer in female. Plumes occasionally also present on upper neck, and some individuals have long white filoplumes on head, neck, and thighs; variable and often visible only in the hand (much less conspicuous than in some other cormorant species). Retained basic feathering loses sheen and becomes progressively browner.

Male_Text: A small cormorant (~1.2–1.4 kg) with an emerald green eye, grayish bill, and a pale yellow gular (throat) pouch with a pronounced white 'V' of feathers outlining the pouch. Breeding adult (Definitive Alternate Plumage) develops small patch of white filoplumes (thin feathers) along sides of head (most postauricular), sides of neck and ventral region neck, giving streaked appearance. Otherwise adult body plumage (Definitive Basic Plumage) entirely black except for slight dark-greenish gloss to upperwings and back. Juvenile shows a yellower bill and brown body feathering, which gradually gets replaced with black (in Formative Plumage and Second Basic Plumage) over the first 2 years of life. Sexes are alike in all plumages. DEF BAS. "Present primarily August-January. All contour feathering black with metallic gloss; concealed down and bases of all contour feathers pale grayish brown. Head with emerald gloss; neck glossed ultramarine violet; back and breast feathering glossed

Notes: removed from list based on the updated description

Male_Text: "Dichromatic by sex. Males glossy blackish green on crown, nape, mantle, scapulars, back, rump, and tail. Some scapulars have creamy white fringes around the margin. Chestnut streak over eye. Lores dull yellow. Chin, throat, and underparts white to buffy. Central gular stripe pale buff. Patch of dark, pale-edged feathers attached to sides of chest and concealed beneath wing. Primary coverts black, tertials and greater upperwing coverts chestnut, and median and lesser wing coverts pale grey-buff (Cramp and Simmons 1977); thus forming oval wing patches (visible in flight and on folded wing) surrounded by chestnut." Female like male, but crown less prominent and heavily edged in chestnut, gular stripe darker, chest with dark brown streaks, and inner secondaries and greater upperwing coverts paler."
Female_Text: "Dichromatic by sex. Males glossy blackish green on crown, nape, mantle, scapulars, back, rump, and tail. Some scapulars have creamy white fringes around the margin. Patch of dark, pale-edged feathers attached to sides of chest and concealed beneath wing. Primary coverts black, tertials and greater upperwing coverts chestnut, and median and lesser wing coverts pale grey-buff (Cramp and Simmons 1977); thus forming oval wing patches (visible in flight and on folded wing) surrounded by chestnut." Female like male, but crown less prominent and heavily edged in chestnut, gular stripe darker, chest with dark brown streaks, and inner secondaries and greater upperwing coverts paler."

Male_Text: "Dark Morph. Head and neck reddish (variably buffy brown, dark tawny rufous, brownish red, or chestnut); back, wings, and tail dark neutral gray, dark slaty blue, medium gray, or medium bluish gray, some feathers occasionally fringed or tinged rufous; belly slightly paler. When fully grown (January–June), lanceolate occipital plumes extend from hind crown to base of nape and neck and covering breast, creating a "maned" appearance, the plumes up to 7–9 cm on hind crown to 10–12 cm on lower neck, and reddish with purplish gloss and paler tips; lanceolate and filamentous scapular plumes extend up to 25–35 cm caudally to cover back and wings, often extending beyond tail, dark neutral gray with blackish gray central stripe. By end of breeding season (July–August), head and neck color can fade to dark cinnamon and back color can become brownish."
Female_Text: "Dark Morph. Head and neck reddish (variably buffy brown, dark tawny rufous, brownish red, or chestnut); back, wings, and tail dark neutral gray, dark slaty blue, medium gray, or medium bluish gray, some feathers occasionally fringed or tinged rufous; belly slightly paler. When fully grown (January–June), lanceolate occipital plumes extend from hind crown to base of nape and neck and covering breast, creating a "maned" appearance, the plumes up to 7–9 cm on hind crown to 10–12 cm on lower neck, and reddish with purplish gloss and paler tips; lanceolate and filamentous scapular plumes extend up to 25–35 cm caudally to cover back and wings, often extending beyond tail, dark neutral gray with blackish gray central stripe. By end of breeding season (July–August), head and neck color can fade to dark cinnamon and back color can become brownish."

annotation: Not recognized by del Hoyo et al. (1992) or Clements (2000) or Howard and Moore (2003), but included in treatments Peters (1979).

Male_Text: "Adult plumages similar, but females tend to be smaller, duller, and lighter. Sexual dimorphism appears geographically variable according to older studies (Oberholser 1912b). Adults with glossy greenish-black cap and back, wings black with greenish or bluish cast, underparts gray. Wing feathers edged in buff. Neck of adult is rufous-the character that distinguishes North American populations from those of Butorides striatus . Legs orange, bill dark. Shaggy greenish-black crest erectile. Young birds striped brownish on neck and below; back brownish with buff spots; shape and size distinguish them from young of any other species. Color pattern of both adults and young cryptic, clearly adaptive for undisturbed, solitary life in dense vegetation (Hancock and Kushlan 1984)."

Male_Text: " Extensive variation in plumagephoto , sometimes even within same race. Within range, adults of virescens group generally identified by thick, maroon-coloured neck, black cap, comparatively large bill and green-tinged, grey-black upperparts; the chestnut neck offers the best feature for separating virescens from striata in their zone of overlap. In Asia and Africa, several other herons might be confused with members of striata group: compared to Ixobyrchus sturmii and I. flavicollis, larger and paler, without pale throat stripes; from Nycticorax caledonicus by smaller size, dark (not white) underparts and green (not yellow) legs; from immature Nycticorax and Ardeola rufiventris by being smaller, with proportionately longer neck and slighter bill, as well as dark cap and lacks spotting of night-herons. Small size; sexes generally alike, except perhaps in race stagnatilis, and in virescens group females are typically smaller, as well as duller and paler especially during breeding season. "

Male_Text: "Adults distinctive with black cap, upper back, and scapulars; gray wingsphoto , rump, and tail; white headphoto - and neck-sides; and white to pale gray underparts. Bill stout and black, eyes red. Legs yellow-green for most of the year, turning pink at height of breeding season. Lores black during courtship, while black of head and back acquire blue-green gloss during this period and white head plumes are well developed. Non-breeding adultvideo has cap and back duller, lacks nuchal plumes; greenish-blue lores, and pale yellow legs and feet." Crest glossy greenish black with 1–8 (average 2–3) long white occipital plumes, sometimes blackish or gray at base (see below). Lower forehead white, superciliary stripe clear white, sometimes washed gray posterior to the eye, and remainder of head white. Nape white to light grayish; back and scapulars uniformly glossy greenish black; wing coverts, rump, and tail coverts uniformly medium to dark bluish gray. Chin, throat, underside of neck, belly, underwing coverts, and undertail coverts white or pale grayish. Primaries and secondaries grayish dorsally (whitish ventrally), with 2-4 sets according to Staffelmauser molt patterns (see Definitive Prebasic Molt); older feathers tinged brownish due to bleaching. Tail medium to dark bluish gray."

Male_Text: DEF BAS"(Oct-Apr). All feathers white, except for tips of three or four longest primaries, iridescent dark green. Occasional females can have tip of p7 partially or entirely white (Pyle 2008) thus having only three outer primaries (p8-p10) with dark tips. Most to all males appear to have dark tip to p7 and four dark-tipped primaries overall. Extent of black to p7 may correlate with age in females; study needed." DEF ALT. (Apr-Sep): Aspect similar to that of definitive basic plumage (above) but some to most head and neck feathers apparently replaced, contrastingly glossy when fresh. Head, neck, and back can become soiled buff to brownish in some individuals by summer.

annotation: Formerly three subspecies recognized (Peters 1931), but now recognized as monotypic.
Male_Text: DEF BAS. "Head and neck with dark sooty-brown feathers margined white, and appearing distinctly streaked; crown more blackish, with narrow streaking, while throat and foreneck paler with wide streaking. Upper back and scapulars black with purple and green gloss. Breast to vent dark brown with faint purple gloss on feather bases, but feathers may be tipped red-brown. Thighs usually red-brown. Tail, wing, and remainder of body as in Definitive Alternate plumage." DEF ALT. Head, neck, back, scapulars, breast to vent and thighs deep chestnut except paler on underparts, tinged black with purple gloss on crown, foreneck, and chin, faintly glossed purple on upperparts with tips of lower scapulars purple-blue. Back, rump, tail-coverts, tail, and flanks, black glossed purple and (toward edges of feathers) metallic green. Lesser upperwing coverts deep chestnut. Remainder of upperwing coverts, remiges, tertials, underwing, and axillaries glossed dark metallic green and tinged purple on centers of median and greater upperwing coverts, inner secondaries, and tertials. Plumage increases in brightness during courtship (Hancock et al. 1992).

Male_Text: DEF BAS. "Plumage generally similar to Definitive Alternate but without white face; head and neck fuscous black streaked with dull white, remaining upperparts duller, more dusky brown, less glossy than Definitive Alternate (Oberholser 1974)." DEF ALT. Head, neck, mantle, scapulars, and chest to vent and thighs dark chestnut, tinged black with purple gloss on crown, foreneck, and chin. Underparts paler. Narrow band of white feathers borders base of bill, bare loral skin connecting eye and bill, and rear of eye. White feathers form a continuous white band separating dark head plumage from eye, loral skin and bill (Palmer 1962a). Neck and mantle metallic magenta-purple with metallic green reflections (Belknap 1957), lesser wing coverts and outer scapulars maroon, primaries metallic dark green, secondaries metallic bronzy green, becoming purplish near body, tail like mantle, posterior part of chin and all of throat liver brown; remainder of underparts brown with greenish or purplish sheen on some feathers; undertail coverts metallic maroon mixed with dark green; lining of wing metallic olive green; axillars similar but partly purple (Oberholser 1974). Narrow band of white feathers borders base of bill, bare loral skin connecting eye and bill, and rear of eye. Male_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. The back, rump, wing coverts, inner secondaries, and undersurface are dark, strongly glossed with bronzy green. The primaries, outer secondaries, and rectrices steel blue. The long, narrow feathers of the hindneck and sides of the neck are sparkling emerald green. The throat and the fore part of head are dull gray.
Female_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. The back, rump, wing coverts, inner secondaries, and undersurface are dark, strongly glossed with bronzy green. The primaries, outer secondaries, and rectrices steel blue. The long, narrow feathers of the hindneck and sides of the neck are sparkling emerald green. The throat and the fore part of head are dull gray.

Male_Text: "All feathers are dark brown; mantle feathers, tertials, and secondaries have lighter edges; darker feathers, especially on neck and upper back have iridescent blue, purple, or green. Remiges, rectrices, and greater underwing coverts appear silvery below because of whitish ventrum of rachis and rami. Powder down absent (16). Legs pink, generally stained white from excreta. Iris buff or brown to rich dark brown, sometimes with silver or buff speckling; much variation. Head and distal fourth of neck bare, with blackish bristles, generally red or purplish red, brightest on cere; intensity variable within individuals—e.g., color may “drain” from head when bird is captured. Skin of nape and crown loose, with transverse corrugations, allowing neck to extend and feathered “collar” to retract during feeding, collar-preening, and heat stress. White papillae often concentrated in front of eye and across forehead. Head color and pattern varies markedly within and between races, and not always evident in dead birds. Sexes similar, females averaging slightly larger than males but evidently distinguishable only from Discriminant Function equations (17, 18).
Female_Text: "All feathers are dark brown; mantle feathers, tertials, and secondaries have lighter edges; darker feathers, especially on neck and upper back have iridescent blue, purple, or green. Remiges, rectrices, and greater underwing coverts appear silvery below because of whitish ventrum of rachis and rami. Powder down absent (16). Legs pink, generally stained white from excreta. Iris buff or brown to rich dark brown, sometimes with silver or buff speckling; much variation. Head and distal fourth of neck bare, with blackish bristles, generally red or purplish red, brightest on cere; intensity variable within individuals—e.g., color may “drain” from head when bird is captured. Skin of nape and crown loose, with transverse corrugations, allowing neck to extend and feathered “collar” to retract during feeding, collar-preening, and heat stress. White papillae often concentrated in front of eye and across forehead. Head color and pattern varies markedly within and between races, and not always evident in dead birds. Male_Text: "No plumages other than those described as Juvenile and Definitive Basic reported. Suggests that Definitive Basic plumage follows Juvenile plumage and is acquired by a complete molt early in second year of life (about 14–16 mo). Primary molt proceeds outward from P1 (n = 10, Lee and Clark 1993). Molt progresses through at least a few primaries before secondary molt begins (Meyer and Collopy 1990). Tail molt begins with outermost (longest) rectrices when wing molt is well advanced (Meyer and Collopy 1990)." Based on observations in mid-Jul and museum specimens, Lee and Clark (Lee and Clark 1993) concluded that total replacement of flight feathers was rapid, occurring in most kites from late Jun through Jul; all adults were in molt in mid-Jul and thus distinguishable from young of year. Observations at 27 nests (Meyer and Collopy 1990) and at large premigration communal roosts (Meyer 1993) indicated that individuals molted more slowly and that population was less synchronous than Lee and Clark (Lee and Clark 1993) suggested. Extra, nonbreeding birds began wing molt mid- to late Apr. Breeding females did not begin until late May–early Jun, when young were near fledging. Breeding males began 3–6 wk later, in late Jun to mid-Jul. In roosts, nearly 25% of adults had completed molt by 4 Aug, about 40% by 15 Aug, and 90% by 1 Sep; these birds could be distinguished from young of the year by latter's short tail." Head, neck, underside, axillaries, and underwing coverts white. No longer streaked on head, neck, and chest due to tan shafts of contours, but a smaller number of shafts are now black (Lee and Clark 1993). Back, upperwing coverts, and all rectrices and remiges are black, no longer dull brown. White tips of flight feathers and upperwing coverts are gone (probably from wear even prior to molt). Scapulars and marginal and lesser upper-secondary coverts now have purplish rather than greenish iridescent sheen; remaining black areas on upperside appear to be dusted bluish gray in living birds (less so on distal portions of primaries and outer secondaries), possibly due to accumulated powder from powder feathers (Robertson 1988b). The mainly white posthumerals and white proximal portions of secondaries create mottled patterns on backs of perched birds. In adults, outermost rectrices (32–37 cm) are more than twice as long as innermost pair (Robertson 1988b).

Tail molt begins with outermost (longest) rectrices when wing molt is well advanced (Meyer and Collopy 1990)." Based on observations in mid-Jul and museum specimens, Lee and Clark (Lee and Clark 1993) concluded that total replacement of flight feathers was rapid, occurring in most kites from late Jun through Jul; all adults were in molt in mid-Jul and thus distinguishable from young of year. Observations at 27 nests (Meyer and Collopy 1990) and at large premigration communal roosts (Meyer 1993) indicated that individuals molted more slowly and that population was less synchronous than Lee and Clark (Lee and Clark 1993) suggested. Extra, nonbreeding birds began wing molt mid- to late Apr. Breeding females did not begin until late May–early Jun, when young were near fledging. Breeding males began 3–6 wk later, in late Jun to mid-Jul. In roosts, nearly 25% of adults had completed molt by 4 Aug, about 40% by 15 Aug, and 90% by 1 Sep; these birds could be distinguished from young of the year by latter's short tail." Head, neck, underside, axillaries, and underwing coverts white. No longer streaked on head, neck, and chest due to tan shafts of contours, but a smaller number of shafts are now black (Lee and Clark 1993). Back, upperwing coverts, and all rectrices and remiges are black, no longer dull brown. White tips of flight feathers and upperwing coverts are gone (probably from wear even prior to molt). Scapulars and marginal and lesser upper-secondary coverts now have purplish rather than greenish iridescent sheen; remaining black areas on upperside appear to be dusted bluish gray in living birds (less so on distal portions of primaries and outer secondaries), possibly due to accumulated powder from powder feathers (Robertson 1988b). The mainly white posthumerals and white proximal portions of secondaries create mottled patterns on backs of perched birds. In adults, outermost rectrices (32–37 cm) are more than twice as long as innermost pair (Robertson 1988b).
