The upperwing feathers are olive gray and often have an indistinct bluish sheen (Selander 1959). Dark, sooty brown extends down the throat and breast. The belly and vent are pale buffish brown or pale white; however, melanistic individuals are purely sooty brown (Selander 1959). Short bristle feathers form a small frontal crest. Birds have an indistinct brown malar stripe as a result of different feather structure (dos Anjos 2009). The tail is highly graduated and retrices are uniformly brown in plain-tailed morph, while in white-tipped morphs central retrices have white on edges. Sexes are indistinguishable by plumage, however females are signficantly smaller (dos Anjos 2009). Juveniles are paler than adults and generally have gray irides."
Female_Text: "A large, magpie-sized jay with a dark brown uppertail, rump, back, and scapulars. Plumage gradually changes into dark brown or black at the head and neck. The upperwing feathers are olive gray and often have an indistinct bluish sheen (Selander 1959). Dark, sooty brown extends down the throat and breast. The belly and vent are pale buffish brown or pale white; however, melanistic individuals are purely sooty brown (Selander 1959). Short bristle feathers form a small frontal crest. Birds have an indistinct brown malar stripe as a result of different feather structure (dos Anjos 2009). The tail is highly graduated and retrices are uniformly brown in plain-tailed morph, while in white-tipped morphs central retrices have white on edges. Sexes are indistinguishable by plumage, however females are signficantly smaller (dos Anjos 2009). Juveniles are paler than adults and generally have gray irides."

Male_Text: "Present primarily Sep–Aug in North American populations. Crown, including crest, dull blackish gray (N 4.04), crest with bluish iridescence when viewed from certain angles; forehead and crown with narrow white or pale blue streaks (1.9 PB 3.14/3.2); auriculars and nape dull blackish gray; mantle blackish gray (N 4.04); rump light sky blue (1.9 PB 8.2/3.2). Tail appears deep blue; outer webs of rectrices indigo blue (5.0 PB 3.14/3.0 and 7.6 PB 1.9/5.1); inner margins fuscous (5.0 YR 3.04/1.5) except central rectrices (r1) blue; all outer webs (and both webs of central pair of rectrices) barred blackish. Upperwing lesser coverts blackish gray (N 4.04); median, greater, and primary coverts broadly edged light blue (4.0 PB 5.9/10.4 and 3.2 PB 7.2/6.5), often with faint dusky bars on greater coverts. Primaries and secondaries fuscous (5.0 YR 3.04/1.5); outer margins of primaries light blue (4.0 PB 5.9/10.4 and 3.2 PB 7.2/6.5); outer margins of secondaries and tertials darker blue (smalt blue 7.0 PB 3.5/9.5 and ultramarine blue 7.3 PB 4.0/11.7); tertials conspicuously barred with black, bars becoming less distinct distally through secondaries. Throat and upper breast blackish gray (N 4.04), the throat with white to grayish-white streaks creating conspicuous throat patch; lower breast blackish gray (N 4.04) becoming dull indigo blue (5.0 PB 3.14/3.0) on belly and lighter sky blue (3.2 PB 7.2/6.5 and 1.9 PB 8.2/3.2) on undertail coverts." Definitive Basic Plumage separated from Formative Plumage by having wing and tail feathers uniform in quality and freshness: tertials and inner secondaries uniform in wear; primary and greater coverts uniformly bluer, not contrasting in feather quality with retained distal greater coverts; basic outer primaries and rectrices broader, more truncate, darker blue, and relatively fresher (Pyle 1997d).
Female_Rump: "Present primarily Sep–Aug in North American populations. Crown, including crest, dull blackish gray (N 4.04), crest with bluish iridescence when viewed from certain angles; forehead and crown with narrow white or pale blue streaks (1.9 PB 3.14/3.2); auriculars and nape dull blackish gray; mantle blackish gray (N 4.04); rump light sky blue (1.9 PB 8.2/3.2). Tail appears deep blue; outer webs of rectrices indigo blue (5.0 PB 3.14/3.0 and 7.6 PB 1.9/5.1); inner margins fuscous (5.0 YR 3.04/1.5) except central rectrices (r1) blue; all outer webs (and both webs of central pair of rectrices) barred blackish. Upperwing lesser coverts blackish gray (N 4.04); median, greater, and primary coverts broadly edged light blue (4.0 PB 5.9/10.4 and 3.2 PB 7.2/6.5), often with faint dusky bars on greater coverts. Primaries and secondaries fuscous (5.0 YR 3.04/1.5); outer margins of primaries light blue (4.0 PB 5.9/10.4 and 3.2 PB 7.2/6.5); outer margins of secondaries and tertials darker blue (smalt blue 7.0 PB 3.5/9.5 and ultramarine blue 7.3 PB 4.0/11.7); tertials conspicuously barred with black, bars becoming less distinct distally through secondaries. Throat and upper breast blackish gray (N 4.04), the throat with white to grayish-white streaks creating conspicuous throat patch; lower breast blackish gray (N 4.04) becoming dull indigo blue (5.0 PB 3.14/3.0) on belly and lighter sky blue (3.2 PB 7.2/6.5 and 1.9 PB 8.2/3.2) on undertail coverts." Definitive Basic Plumage separated from Formative Plumage by having wing and tail feathers uniform in quality and freshness: tertials and inner secondaries uniform in wear; primary and greater coverts uniformly bluer, not contrasting in feather quality with retained distal greater coverts; basic outer primaries and rectrices broader, more truncate, darker blue, and relatively fresher (Pyle 1997d).

Male_Text: "Male. Crown, hind neck, and sides of neck dull purplish blue (nearest Ultramarine Blue, but somewhat iridescent, approaching True Blue [168A] in certain lights); crown fading to pale blue anteriorly and laterally on forehead and superciliary region, latter becoming white to bluish white; auricular, subauricular, and suborbital regions blackish tinged with blue, and thus darker than neighboring neck areas; lores grayish black, with variable amount of faint gray spotting, or dusky; nasal tufts variable, ranging from whitish to grayish; back dull grayish brown (Light Drab [119C] to Drab-Gray [119D]), feathers usually edged paler, back thus appearing faintly streaked; scapulars and rump similar to back, but with admixture of dull blue, thus slightly darker; uppertail-coverts dull blue, matching hind crown and nape. Chin, throat, and midchest grayish white, seemingly streaked with gray and black, an effect caused by absence of barbs from terminal portions of rachises, which become black on chin, together with variable graying of lateral margins of vanes; sides of chest dull purplish blue, as above, extending toward midchest as pectoral collar, but becoming limited medially to lateral margins of feathers where more or less replaced by brownish gray; lower breast pale brownish gray (Smoke Gray [45]), slightly darker laterally, streaked lightly and obscurely with darker shade (Light Drab); belly similar or slightly lighter, but lacking obscure streaks and becoming white posteriorly; undertail-coverts dull blue; ankle feathers Light Drab, with variable quantity of dull blue comparable to shade of undertail-coverts. Remiges, feathers of alula, and coverts dull blue (nearest Ultramarine Blue, but somewhat iridescent, approaching True Blue in certain lights, and dull brownish blue in other lights); primaries dull dark gray distally; inner webs of all remiges except innermost secondaries dull dark gray; P7 longest; underwing coverts dull gray, tipped with dull blue marginally; rectrices similar to remiges or slightly darker." Female. Similar to male, averaging slightly paler.
Female_Text: "Male. Crown, hind neck, and sides of neck dull purplish blue (nearest Ultramarine Blue, but somewhat iridescent, approaching True Blue [168A] in certain lights); crown fading to pale blue anteriorly and laterally on forehead and superciliary region, latter becoming white to bluish white; auricular, subauricular, and suborbital regions blackish tinged with blue, and thus darker than neighboring neck areas; lores grayish black, with variable amount of faint gray spotting, or dusky; nasal tufts variable, ranging from whitish to grayish; back dull grayish brown (Light Drab [119C] to Drab-Gray [119D]), feathers usually edged paler, back thus appearing faintly streaked; scapulars and rump similar to back, but with admixture of dull blue, thus slightly darker; uppertail-coverts dull blue, matching hind crown and nape. Chin, throat, and midchest grayish white, seemingly streaked with gray and black, an effect caused by absence of barbs from terminal portions of rachises, which become black on chin, together with variable graying of lateral margins of vanes; sides of chest dull purplish blue, as above, extending toward midchest as pectoral collar, but becoming limited medially to lateral margins of feathers where more or less replaced by brownish gray; lower breast pale brownish gray (Smoke Gray [45]), slightly darker laterally, streaked lightly and obscurely with darker shade (Light Drab); belly similar or slightly lighter, but lacking obscure streaks and becoming white posteriorly; undertail-coverts dull blue; ankle feathers Light Drab, with variable quantity of dull blue comparable to shade of undertail-coverts. Remiges, feathers of alula, and coverts dull blue (nearest Ultramarine Blue, but somewhat iridescent, approaching True Blue in certain lights, and dull brownish blue in other lights); primaries dull dark gray distally; inner webs of all remiges except innermost secondaries dull dark gray; P7 longest; underwing coverts dull gray, tipped with dull blue marginally; rectrices similar to remiges or slightly darker." Female. Similar to male, averaging slightly paler.

annotation: Formerly considered conspecific with Aphelocoma woodhouseii.
Formerly considered conspecific with Aphelocoma californica.

Male_Text: "Nasal tufts, anterior portions of forehead and chin, eye-ring, and cheeks white. Remainder of head, back, and scapulars “Mouse Gray” or slightly brownish, head slightly paler. Rump darker gray than back, uppertail-coverts dark gray to blackish. Central rectrices (R1) dull black with slight metallic green sheen. Second innermost pair of rectrices (r2), with most of inner web and basal portion of outer web, blackish and remainder of feather white. Remaining rectrices white. Wings black; feathers have metallic green sheen; secondaries white on distal third of feather. Crissum white; remainder of underparts same color as back but slightly paler. Wing-lining blackish; some feathers have whitish edges (Oberholser 1974)."Definitive Basic body plumage is smooth and compact; some individual variation in extent of white around eyes and bill and on face. Contrast between glossy black wings and white patch on secondaries and glossy black inner tail feathers and white outer tail feathers is striking in flight."
Female_Text: "Nasal tufts, anterior portions of forehead and chin, eye-ring, and cheeks white. Remainder of head, back, and scapulars “Mouse Gray” or slightly brownish, head slightly paler. Rump darker gray than back, uppertail-coverts dark gray to blackish. Central rectrices (R1) dull black with slight metallic green sheen. Second innermost pair of rectrices (r2), with most of inner web and basal portion of outer web, blackish and remainder of feather white. Remaining rectrices white. Wings black; feathers have metallic green sheen; secondaries white on distal third of feather. Crissum white; remainder of underparts same color as back but slightly paler. Wing-lining blackish; some feathers have whitish edges (Oberholser 1974)."Definitive Basic body plumage is smooth and compact; some individual variation in extent of white around eyes and bill and on face. Contrast between glossy black wings and white patch on secondaries and glossy black inner tail feathers and white outer tail feathers is striking in flight."

Male_Text: "Head, neck, breast, back, uppertail-coverts, tail, vent, undertail-coverts, lower midbelly, and tibia black, glossed with iridescent blue. Outer scapulars white, forming contrasting patch above wing. Rump light gray. Black throat-feathers hairlike, with white bases (Goodwin 1976b), so when magpie has full lingual pouch or when singing with bill elevated in Stretch Display (see Behavior: agonistic behavior, above), these white bases are flashed. Belly and flanks white and sharply demarcated from black breast. At gatherings, or when Treetop-Sitting (see Behavior: spacing, above), males fluff scapulars, rump, and flanks so that wings are entirely hidden. They appear pure white in the middle, with black ends; quite different from nearby females." Secondaries, wing coverts, alula, and outer webs of primaries are iridescent blue above, dull black below. Each of the 10 primaries has subterminal white area 4–14 cm long on inner web that comes to within 0.5–2 cm of black tip (nearer tip on outer feathers). The small, outermost primary (P10) is narrow and sickle shaped, and white area almost reaches tip in most individuals. Together these white markings form white patch on outer wing. Adults only very rarely (2.4%) have white markings on more than the 10 primary feathers; 62% of juveniles also had white in secondaries (Reed 1990c, CHT). Tail black, long, and graduated; central (longest) 2 feathers and outer webs of remaining 5 feathers are glossed metallic iridescent blue-green. Iridescent area includes subterminal 2- to 3-cm band with bronze green, then purple, zone grading into greenish blue tip about 4 cm long. Inner webs of outer rectrices are dull black, as are undersurfaces of all rectrices. Ends of rectrices squarish, unlike rounded shape of Juvenile rectrices. Adult males have longer central rectrices than either juvenile males or females; thus their tails appear longer and more graded (Reed 1990c, CHT).
Female_Text: "Head, neck, breast, back, uppertail-coverts, tail, vent, undertail-coverts, lower midbelly, and tibia black, glossed with iridescent blue. Outer scapulars white, forming contrasting patch above wing. Rump light gray. Black throat-feathers hairlike, with white bases (Goodwin 1976b), so when magpie has full lingual pouch or when singing with bill elevated in Stretch Display (see Behavior: agonistic behavior, above), these white bases are flashed. Belly and flanks white and sharply demarcated from black breast. At gatherings, or when Treetop-Sitting (see Behavior: spacing, above), males fluff scapulars, rump, and flanks so that wings are entirely hidden. They appear pure white in the middle, with black ends; quite different from nearby females." Secondaries, wing coverts, alula, and outer webs of primaries are iridescent blue above, dull black below. Each of the 10 primaries has subterminal white area 4–14 cm long on inner web that comes to within 0.5–2 cm of black tip (nearer tip on outer feathers). The small, outermost primary (P10) is narrow and sickle shaped, and white area almost reaches tip in most individuals. Together these white markings form white patch on outer wing. Adults only very rarely (2.4%) have white markings on more than the 10 primary feathers; 62% of juveniles also had white in secondaries (Reed 1990c, CHT). Tail black, long, and graduated; central (longest) 2 feathers and outer webs of remaining 5 feathers are glossed metallic iridescent blue-green. Iridescent area includes subterminal 2- to 3-cm band with bronze green, then purple, zone grading into greenish blue tip about 4 cm long. Inner webs of outer rectrices are dull black, as are undersurfaces of all rectrices. Ends of rectrices squarish, unlike rounded shape of Juvenile rectrices. Adult males have longer central rectrices than either juvenile males or females; thus their tails appear longer and more graded (Reed 1990c, CHT).

Male_Text: "Present primarily September–August. Head, nape, back, upperwing lesser coverts, tail, uppertail-coverts, upper breast, femoral feathers, lower belly, and undertail-coverts black, often with glossy greenish sheen to the head and elsewhere, and a narrow grayish to whitish band separating the lower back from the rump; rectrices deep iridescent bluish. Upperwing median and greater coverts, primary coverts, tertials, and secondaries uniformly deep iridescent bluish; primaries blackish with white patches to their inner webs, increasing in size distally, and the outer web of the inner primaries (pp1‒5) has a bluish sheen. Lower breast, upper belly, and scapulars (which contrast with black wings and back) white."
Female_Text: "Present primarily September–August. Head, nape, back, upperwing lesser coverts, tail, uppertail-coverts, upper breast, femoral feathers, lower belly, and undertail-coverts black, often with glossy greenish sheen to the head and elsewhere, and a narrow grayish to whitish band separating the lower back from the rump; rectrices deep iridescent bluish. Upperwing median and greater coverts, primary coverts, tertials, and secondaries uniformly deep iridescent bluish; primaries blackish with white patches to their inner webs, increasing in size distally, and the outer web of the inner primaries (pp1‒5) has a bluish sheen. Lower breast, upper belly, and scapulars (which contrast with black wings and back) white."

Male_Text: "Present primarily September–July. Plumage of upperparts black with metallic violet gloss on back, shoulders, rump, uppertail coverts, upperwing coverts, and secondaries; primaries, primary coverts, and outermost rectrices glossed greenish blue; middle rectrices duller or more blue-violet than rump. Underparts slightly glossed with bluish violet on breast and flanks. Bases of neck-, back-, chin-, throat-, breast-, belly-, and rump feathers: gray (21). Feathers of upper back, scapulars, central and lower back show a scale-like appearance resulting from a non-interlocking of distal ends (1–2 mm) of barbs (16). Definitive Basic Plumage separated from Formative Plumage by having back feathers and all wing feathers uniformly glossy black; basic outer primaries and rectrices blacker, broader, and more truncate than retained juvenile feather of Formative Plumage."
Female_Text: "Present primarily September–July. Plumage of upperparts black with metallic violet gloss on back, shoulders, rump, uppertail coverts, upperwing coverts, and secondaries; primaries, primary coverts, and outermost rectrices glossed greenish blue; middle rectrices duller or more blue-violet than rump. Underparts slightly glossed with bluish violet on breast and flanks. Bases of neck-, back-, chin-, throat-, breast-, belly-, and rump feathers: gray (21). Feathers of upper back, scapulars, central and lower back show a scale-like appearance resulting from a non-interlocking of distal ends (1–2 mm) of barbs (16). Definitive Basic Plumage separated from Formative Plumage by having back feathers and all wing feathers uniformly glossy black; basic outer primaries and rectrices blacker, broader, and more truncate than retained juvenile feather of Formative Plumage."

Male_Text: "Small, rather tame crow with short, stout, sharp-pointed bill and well-developed nasal bristles covering nostrils. Nominate race has coarse black plumage with considerable purple-blue iridescence; iris brown; bill and legs black. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile somewhat duller than adult. Race minutus slightly smaller and duller than nominate, and male tends to have larger tarsi and smaller bill."
Female_Text: "Small, rather tame crow with short, stout, sharp-pointed bill and well-developed nasal bristles covering nostrils. Nominate race has coarse black plumage with considerable purple-blue iridescence; iris brown; bill and legs black. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile somewhat duller than adult. Race minutus slightly smaller and duller than nominate, and male tends to have larger tarsi and smaller bill."

Male_Text: "A moderate-sized crow with upturned nasal bristles that do not cover nostrils; relatively long bill. Plumage is deep blackphoto with slight blue-purple gloss, body feathers with grey bases; irisphoto brown, patch of bare skin behind eye and at base of bill; bill and legs black. Distinguished from C. pal­marumphoto by longer and less stout bill, and by longer wingsphoto and slower, heavier wingbeats in flight. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile is slightly duller than adult."
Female_Text: "A moderate-sized crow with upturned nasal bristles that do not cover nostrils; relatively long bill. Plumage is deep blackphoto with slight blue-purple gloss, body feathers with grey bases; irisphoto brown, patch of bare skin behind eye and at base of bill; bill and legs black. Distinguished from C. pal­marumphoto by longer and less stout bill, and by longer wingsphoto and slower, heavier wingbeats in flight. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile is slightly duller than adult."

Male_Text: "The largest Caribbean crow; long (35–49 mm) and tapered bill, nasal bristles upturned and sweeping over culmen ridge, intense plush-like black feathers at base of culmen between bill and eye. Plumage is black with purple or blue gloss, body feathers with white bases (concealed white bases give rise to name); iris red-brown (yellow iris also reported, possibly age-specific), bare skin about bill base and below eye; bill and legs black. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile is slightly duller than adult.
Female_Text: "The largest Caribbean crow; long (35–49 mm) and tapered bill, nasal bristles upturned and sweeping over culmen ridge, intense plush-like black feathers at base of culmen between bill and eye. Plumage is black with purple or blue gloss, body feathers with white bases (concealed white bases give rise to name); iris red-brown (yellow iris also reported, possibly age-specific), bare skin about bill base and below eye; bill and legs black. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile is slightly duller than adult.

Male_Text: "Smallest and dullest Caribbean crow; body plumage loose and soft, nostrils of some individuals fully exposed. Has head, face and throat black, base of neck feathers grey, rest of plumage mostly dark, dull grey or sooty black, back greyish-black with hint of brown; some violet iridescence in wings, tail and neck; iris grey-brown or reddish-brown (possibly indicating age or sex), bare suborbital patch evident on most individuals; bill slate-grey; legs black. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile undescribed."
Female_Text: "Smallest and dullest Caribbean crow; body plumage loose and soft, nostrils of some individuals fully exposed. Has head, face and throat black, base of neck feathers grey, rest of plumage mostly dark, dull grey or sooty black, back greyish-black with hint of brown; some violet iridescence in wings, tail and neck; iris grey-brown or reddish-brown (possibly indicating age or sex), bare suborbital patch evident on most individuals; bill slate-grey; legs black. Sexes similar, male slightly larger than female. Juvenile undescribed."

Male_Text: "Adult: Black, glossed purplish on the upperparts and bluish on the underparts. Crown, nape, wing coverts and secondaries glossy dark violet. Sides of neck, the back, scapulars, rump, uppertail coverts, and primary coverts glossy dark violet blue. Primaries and rectrices dark steel blue, the central rectrices tinged with violet, and the outermost primaries more greenish blue. Sides of head and the underparts dark steel blue or greenish steel blue, becoming more greenish posteriorly."
Female_Text: "Adult: Black, glossed purplish on the upperparts and bluish on the underparts. Crown, nape, wing coverts and secondaries glossy dark violet. Sides of neck, the back, scapulars, rump, uppertail coverts, and primary coverts glossy dark violet blue. Primaries and rectrices dark steel blue, the central rectrices tinged with violet, and the outermost primaries more greenish blue. Sides of head and the underparts dark steel blue or greenish steel blue, becoming more greenish posteriorly."

Male_Text: "Adult: Black, glossed purplish on the upperparts and bluish on the underparts. Crown, nape, wing coverts and secondaries glossy dark violet. Sides of neck, the back, scapulars, rump, uppertail coverts, and primary coverts glossy dark violet blue. Primaries and rectrices dark steel blue, the central rectrices tinged with violet, and the outermost primaries more greenish blue. Sides of head and the underparts dark steel blue or greenish steel blue, becoming more greenish posteriorly.
Female_Text: "Adult: Black, glossed purplish on the upperparts and bluish on the underparts. Crown, nape, wing coverts and secondaries glossy dark violet. Sides of neck, the back, scapulars, rump, uppertail coverts, and primary coverts glossy dark violet blue. Primaries and rectrices dark steel blue, the central rectrices tinged with violet, and the outermost primaries more greenish blue. Sides of head and the underparts dark steel blue or greenish steel blue, becoming more greenish posteriorly.

Male_Text: "All feathers blackish neutral gray to jet black, with greenish-violet iridescence. Proximal portions of contour feathers glaucous, but hidden by overlapping feathers. Iridescence marked on belly (unlike American Crow), but is lacking on underside of remiges and rectrices. Iridescence reduced to tips of underwing coverts, but present (KJM)."
Female_Text: "All feathers blackish neutral gray to jet black, with greenish-violet iridescence. Proximal portions of contour feathers glaucous, but hidden by overlapping feathers. Iridescence marked on belly (unlike American Crow), but is lacking on underside of remiges and rectrices. Iridescence reduced to tips of underwing coverts, but present (KJM)."

Male_Text: "Present primarily Oct-Sep. Visible plumage entirely glossy black (Fig. 1, Fig. 16, and Fig. 18) with purplish, blue, or violet sheen on upperparts; sides of neck often with brownish tinge; outer webs of primaries, and feathers of underparts (including underwing surface) with faint metallic bluish to greenish gloss. Bases of neck-feathers snow-white (Fig. 5), may extend down to upper-breast region. Throat feathers lanceolate and elongated giving a shaggy-neck profile or “goitered” look. As plumage of hindneck, underparts, and rump become worn, glossy feather margins contrast with dull-black feather centers to produce a dark scaling effect. Definitive Basic Plumage separated from Formative Plumage by having wing and tail feathers uniformly glossy black, without molt limits; basic outer primaries and rectrices broader, more truncate, black, and relatively fresher, not wearing as much to brown in spring and summer."
Female_Text: "Present primarily Oct-Sep. Visible plumage entirely glossy black (Fig. 1, Fig. 16, and Fig. 18) with purplish, blue, or violet sheen on upperparts; sides of neck often with brownish tinge; outer webs of primaries, and feathers of underparts (including underwing surface) with faint metallic bluish to greenish gloss. Bases of neck-feathers snow-white (Fig. 5), may extend down to upper-breast region. Throat feathers lanceolate and elongated giving a shaggy-neck profile or “goitered” look. As plumage of hindneck, underparts, and rump become worn, glossy feather margins contrast with dull-black feather centers to produce a dark scaling effect. Definitive Basic Plumage separated from Formative Plumage by having wing and tail feathers uniformly glossy black, without molt limits; basic outer primaries and rectrices broader, more truncate, black, and relatively fresher, not wearing as much to brown in spring and summer."

Male_Text: "Plumage entirely black with purple, bluish, and greenish gloss. Tail characteristically wedge-shaped in flight. Throat feathers lanceolate and elongated creating shaggy appearance. remiges and rectrices do not become distinctly brownish with wear as in immatures (Kerttu 1973, Heinrich 1994b). Sexes similar. Description of Eurasian adults similar. Entire plumage deep black, glossed with purple to purplish blue. Greater and primary underwing coverts, and under surface of remiges and rectrices glossy brown-black. Bases of head and body feathers gray, becoming palest on neck and mantle. As plumage becomes worn, gloss becomes more bluish or bronzy, and dull black feather centers of underparts visible with glossy feather margins showing as distinct dark scaling. Sexes similar but female average slightly less purple with more dull black feather centers showing (Cramp and Perrins 1994a)."
Female_Text: "Plumage entirely black with purple, bluish, and greenish gloss. Tail characteristically wedge-shaped in flight. Throat feathers lanceolate and elongated creating shaggy appearance. remiges and rectrices do not become distinctly brownish with wear as in immatures (Kerttu 1973, Heinrich 1994b). Sexes similar. Description of Eurasian adults similar. Entire plumage deep black, glossed with purple to purplish blue. Greater and primary underwing coverts, and under surface of remiges and rectrices glossy brown-black. Bases of head and body feathers gray, becoming palest on neck and mantle. As plumage becomes worn, gloss becomes more bluish or bronzy, and dull black feather centers of underparts visible with glossy feather margins showing as distinct dark scaling. Sexes similar but female average slightly less purple with more dull black feather centers showing (Cramp and Perrins 1994a)."

Male_Text: "(Nov-Feb or Nov-Oct). Definitive Basic aspect of females with greenish-blue, iridescent upperparts, usually slightly duller than that of males (Cohen 1984c) and white underparts. Some females retain small amount of brown feathering on forehead for several years (Stutchbury and Robertson 1987d). In males, upperparts bright iridescent greenish blue, underparts white, similar to males in Formative Plumage (above)."
Female_Text: "(Nov-Feb or Nov-Oct). Definitive Basic aspect of females with greenish-blue, iridescent upperparts, usually slightly duller than that of males (Cohen 1984c) and white underparts. Some females retain small amount of brown feathering on forehead for several years (Stutchbury and Robertson 1987d). In males, upperparts bright iridescent greenish blue, underparts white, similar to males in Formative Plumage (above)."

Male_Text: "Adult: Medium sized swallow with long, strongly graduated tail. Crown, nape back and scapulars dull metallic green. Lesser wing coverts, rump and uppertail coverts bluish green.  Median and greater wing coverts and tertials dusky greenish blue, with broad, lighter greenish blue or bluish green margins.  Remiges and rectrices dark greenish blue. Lores dusky.  Auriculars, malars, underwing coverts, and entire underparts pure white.  Female similar to male, but more or less duller in color; auriculars mottled with grayish brown; and tail shorter, with a slightly shallower fork."
Female_Text: "Adult: Medium sized swallow with long, strongly graduated tail. Crown, nape back and scapulars dull metallic green. Lesser wing coverts, rump and uppertail coverts bluish green.  Median and greater wing coverts and tertials dusky greenish blue, with broad, lighter greenish blue or bluish green margins.  Remiges and rectrices dark greenish blue. Lores dusky.  Auriculars, malars, underwing coverts, and entire underparts pure white.  Female similar to male, but more or less duller in color; auriculars mottled with grayish brown; and tail shorter, with a slightly shallower fork."

Male_Text: "(Nov-Feb or Nov-Oct). Definitive Basic aspect of males bright glossy green with a slight bronzy shade on back and scapulars, becoming bronzy green on crown; occiput and nape purple, with a concealed narrow collar of ash round the hind neck, caused simply by the gray bases of the feathers; rump rather more bluish green, mixed with purple on the uppertail coverts, and with white patches laterally; wing coverts black, the lesser and median series tipped with bluish green; greater coverts, alula, and primary coverts black, externally glossed with deep indigo; tail feathers also black with a bluish gloss; lores dusky; feathers over and behind the eye, auriculars, cheeks, sides of face, and entire under surface of body silky white; underwing coverts and axillaries smokey-brown with whitish edgings, the coverts near the edge of the wing and the lower greater coverts darker; quills dusky brown below, rather more ashy on their inner edge."
Female_Text: "(Nov-Feb or Nov-Oct). Definitive Basic aspect of males bright glossy green with a slight bronzy shade on back and scapulars, becoming bronzy green on crown; occiput and nape purple, with a concealed narrow collar of ash round the hind neck, caused simply by the gray bases of the feathers; rump rather more bluish green, mixed with purple on the uppertail coverts, and with white patches laterally; wing coverts black, the lesser and median series tipped with bluish green; greater coverts, alula, and primary coverts black, externally glossed with deep indigo; tail feathers also black with a bluish gloss; lores dusky; feathers over and behind the eye, auriculars, cheeks, sides of face, and entire under surface of body silky white; underwing coverts and axillaries smokey-brown with whitish edgings, the coverts near the edge of the wing and the lower greater coverts darker; quills dusky brown below, rather more ashy on their inner edge."

Male_Text: "Male is strongly iridescent bronzy green to coppery bronze above, upperparts often appearing golden; wingsphoto and tail dusky bronze-green, tail slightly forked; underpartsphoto white, underwing-coverts dusky with bronze-green margins. Female is similar but duller, with some grey-brown mottling on breast. Juvenile is duller and browner, with extensive grey-brown mottling on breast. Race sclateriphoto is less golden, has longer wings, smaller bill, deeper tail fork."
Female_Text: "Male is strongly iridescent bronzy green to coppery bronze above, upperparts often appearing golden; wingsphoto and tail dusky bronze-green, tail slightly forked; underpartsphoto white, underwing-coverts dusky with bronze-green margins. Female is similar but duller, with some grey-brown mottling on breast. Juvenile is duller and browner, with extensive grey-brown mottling on breast. Race sclateriphoto is less golden, has longer wings, smaller bill, deeper tail fork."

Male_Text: "Adult: Crown, sides of the head, nape, back, scapulars, and wing coverts steel-blue with a greenish gloss; the upperparts are greener in fresh plumage. There is a distinct white, short line above the lores. Rump white or grayish white; these feathers usually have a narrow, dusky shaft line. Uppertail coverts dusky, glossed with bluish green, and often with white or pale grayish margins. Remiges and rectrices dull black, with a faint greenish gloss; the outer webs and tips of the tertials with broad white margins. Malars and underparts white; upper breast usually faintly shaded with grayish. Underwing coverts white or grayish white. Tail slightly forked."
Female_Text: "Adult: Crown, sides of the head, nape, back, scapulars, and wing coverts steel-blue with a greenish gloss; the upperparts are greener in fresh plumage. There is a distinct white, short line above the lores. Rump white or grayish white; these feathers usually have a narrow, dusky shaft line. Uppertail coverts dusky, glossed with bluish green, and often with white or pale grayish margins. Remiges and rectrices dull black, with a faint greenish gloss; the outer webs and tips of the tertials with broad white margins. Malars and underparts white; upper breast usually faintly shaded with grayish. Underwing coverts white or grayish white. Tail slightly forked."

Male_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. Crown, nape, and sides of the head and neck glossy black, with a faint bluish luster. Back and scapulars sepia brown, becoming darker on the rump and deepening to black or dark sooty brown on the uppertail coverts. Rectrices dull black or sooty black. Lesser wing coverts glossy black or brownish black; rest of wing brownish black, fading to dark grayish brown or sooty on secondary and innermost greater wing coverts. Malar region, chin, and throat white, spotted or flecked with sooty brown. Center of breast and belly white. Flanks and under surface of wing plain grayish brown. Vent and undertail coverts sooty black or very dark sooty brown."
Female_Text: "Adult: Sexes similar. Crown, nape, and sides of the head and neck glossy black, with a faint bluish luster. Back and scapulars sepia brown, becoming darker on the rump and deepening to black or dark sooty brown on the uppertail coverts. Rectrices dull black or sooty black. Lesser wing coverts glossy black or brownish black; rest of wing brownish black, fading to dark grayish brown or sooty on secondary and innermost greater wing coverts. Malar region, chin, and throat white, spotted or flecked with sooty brown. Center of breast and belly white. Flanks and under surface of wing plain grayish brown. Vent and undertail coverts sooty black or very dark sooty brown."

Male_Text: "Nominate subspecies is brownish black with a slight green sheen on the upperparts from the forehead to the back, plus the scapulars; paler grey-brown rump and underparts; wings and tail brownish-black; tail slightly forked. The greater upperwing-coverts and tertials have slightly lighter tips. The ear-coverts and sides of the neck are dark brown, the cheeks are grey-brown, and the lores are black. Dusky grey-brown undertail coverts are conspicuous in flight. Diagnostic tuft of white feathers on lower leg may be visible when perched, but is generally difficult to see in the field." The sexes are alike
Female_Text: "Nominate subspecies is brownish black with a slight green sheen on the upperparts from the forehead to the back, plus the scapulars; paler grey-brown rump and underparts; wings and tail brownish-black; tail slightly forked. The greater upperwing-coverts and tertials have slightly lighter tips. The ear-coverts and sides of the neck are dark brown, the cheeks are grey-brown, and the lores are black. Dusky grey-brown undertail coverts are conspicuous in flight. Diagnostic tuft of white feathers on lower leg may be visible when perched, but is generally difficult to see in the field." The sexes are alike

Male_Text: "The Blue-and-White Swallow adult plumage is characterized by glossy steel-blue on the forehead, crown, mantle, back, rump, and uppertail coverts. The mantle feathers are spotted under the surface with white or pale gray. The feathers over the ears and lores are a less bright blue. The wing coverts are black with steel-blue margins that are not as distinct in the greater coverts (Turner and Rose 1989). The underside of the swallow is white with a gray wash on the sides and flanks. The white underneath can be warm buff in fresh plumage. The far sides of the breast are black. A few dusky spots on the chest of some birds can also be pronounced and form a narrow collar (Turner and Rose 1989). The undertail coverts are black with steel-blue margins, and the underwing coverts and axilaries also are gray with whitish tips (Turner and Rose 1989). The tail feathers are grayish black, and the tail is slightly forked. The only difference in adult plumage between males and females is that the female tends to have duller white and stronger buffy coloration (Stiles and Skutch 1989)."
Female_Text: "The Blue-and-White Swallow adult plumage is characterized by glossy steel-blue on the forehead, crown, mantle, back, rump, and uppertail coverts. The mantle feathers are spotted under the surface with white or pale gray. The feathers over the ears and lores are a less bright blue. The wing coverts are black with steel-blue margins that are not as distinct in the greater coverts (Turner and Rose 1989). The underside of the swallow is white with a gray wash on the sides and flanks. The white underneath can be warm buff in fresh plumage. The far sides of the breast are black. A few dusky spots on the chest of some birds can also be pronounced and form a narrow collar (Turner and Rose 1989). The undertail coverts are black with steel-blue margins, and the underwing coverts and axilaries also are gray with whitish tips (Turner and Rose 1989). The tail feathers are grayish black, and the tail is slightly forked. The only difference in adult plumage between males and females is that the female tends to have duller white and stronger buffy coloration (Stiles and Skutch 1989)."

Male_Text: "Present primarily October–September. Female. Upperparts similar to those of Definitive Basic male but duller and less uniform, with more of gray bases of feathers visible; forehead and fore part of crown hair brown, mixed with metallic blue, sometimes becoming grayish white on forehead; hindneck with narrow, light hair-brown collar; lores dull black; back, rump and upperwing lesser coverts dull metallic blue; remainder of upperwing including distal marginal coverts grayish tinged dull metallic blue; throat and sides of head and neck hair brown or mouse gray, with only auriculars showing entirely metallic blue; breast and sides of underparts similar but darker, with dull white or grayish white edgings of feathers; middle of posterior underparts white; undertail coverts with sooty centers forming triangular patches (9); underwing coverts hair brown. Definitive Basic females generally have more metallic blue on dorsum than Formative females and can also be distinguished by undertail-covert pattern and, possibly, lack of contrast to distal marginal coverts (see Formative Plumage). Females in all plumages lack metallic blue ventral feathering, which distinguishes them from female-like Formative males. Tail distinctly notched. Male. Plumage uniformly metallic dusky violet or induline blue; bases of feathers dark hair brown, deep mouse gray, or blackish mouse gray; each side of rump usually with small concealed tuft of white feathers and another larger tuft of white on each side of body; wings and tail fuscous black, inner webs fuscous with slight metallic greenish gloss; upperwing lesser and median coverts similar to upperparts, other upperwing coverts similar to rest of wing; underwing coverts chaetura black with metallic blue sheen. Tail distinctly notched."
Female_Text: "Present primarily October–September. Female. Upperparts similar to those of Definitive Basic male but duller and less uniform, with more of gray bases of feathers visible; forehead and fore part of crown hair brown, mixed with metallic blue, sometimes becoming grayish white on forehead; hindneck with narrow, light hair-brown collar; lores dull black; back, rump and upperwing lesser coverts dull metallic blue; remainder of upperwing including distal marginal coverts grayish tinged dull metallic blue; throat and sides of head and neck hair brown or mouse gray, with only auriculars showing entirely metallic blue; breast and sides of underparts similar but darker, with dull white or grayish white edgings of feathers; middle of posterior underparts white; undertail coverts with sooty centers forming triangular patches (9); underwing coverts hair brown. Definitive Basic females generally have more metallic blue on dorsum than Formative females and can also be distinguished by undertail-covert pattern and, possibly, lack of contrast to distal marginal coverts (see Formative Plumage). Females in all plumages lack metallic blue ventral feathering, which distinguishes them from female-like Formative males. Tail distinctly notched. Male. Plumage uniformly metallic dusky violet or induline blue; bases of feathers dark hair brown, deep mouse gray, or blackish mouse gray; each side of rump usually with small concealed tuft of white feathers and another larger tuft of white on each side of body; wings and tail fuscous black, inner webs fuscous with slight metallic greenish gloss; upperwing lesser and median coverts similar to upperparts, other upperwing coverts similar to rest of wing; underwing coverts chaetura black with metallic blue sheen. Tail distinctly notched."

Male_Text: "Malephoto is dark glossy steel-blue, wings and tail blacker, tail deeply forked. Differs from extremely similar P. subis in slightly longer and more deeply forked tail (probably indistinguishable in the field). Femalephoto has duller upperparts and dusky brown underparts, feathers extensively pale-mar­gined, appearing scaly, undertail-coverts white with dusky shafts. Juvenile resembles adult female."
Female_Text: "Malephoto is dark glossy steel-blue, wings and tail blacker, tail deeply forked. Differs from extremely similar P. subis in slightly longer and more deeply forked tail (probably indistinguishable in the field). Femalephoto has duller upperparts and dusky brown underparts, feathers extensively pale-mar­gined, appearing scaly, undertail-coverts white with dusky shafts. Juvenile resembles adult female."

Male_Text: "Adult male: Violaceous steel blue upperparts, including scapulars and wing coverts. Forecrown dull brown. Gray brown or sooty gray lores, sides of the head, chin, throat, breast, sides and flanks. The throat and chin are paler; the breast feathers have grayish white tips; and the axillaries and underwing coverts are deep sooty gray. Some individuals have a violaceous patch of varying size on the sides of their breast. The rest of the underparts are white except the longer undertail coverts, which have dusky shafts. Wings and tail are black with faint blue gloss; the tail is moderately forked." Adult female: Similar to male except duller. Less steel blue gloss, especially on the head, paler chin and throat
Female_Text: "Adult male: Violaceous steel blue upperparts, including scapulars and wing coverts. Forecrown dull brown. Gray brown or sooty gray lores, sides of the head, chin, throat, breast, sides and flanks. The throat and chin are paler; the breast feathers have grayish white tips; and the axillaries and underwing coverts are deep sooty gray. Some individuals have a violaceous patch of varying size on the sides of their breast. The rest of the underparts are white except the longer undertail coverts, which have dusky shafts. Wings and tail are black with faint blue gloss; the tail is moderately forked." Adult female: Similar to male except duller. Less steel blue gloss, especially on the head, paler chin and throat

Male_Text: "Present primarily October–September. Female. Upperparts similar to those of Definitive Basic male but duller and less uniform, with more of gray bases of feathers visible; forehead and fore part of crown hair brown, mixed with metallic blue, sometimes be
Female_Text: "Present primarily October–September. Female. Upperparts similar to those of Definitive Basic male but duller and less uniform, with more of gray bases of feathers visible; forehead and fore part of crown hair brown, mixed with metallic blue, sometimes be

Male_Text: "Adult Male. Rich, steel-blue overall, with purple gloss. The wings and tail, however, are much glossier with a shade of greenish or sooty-black. Feathers around the vent and the anterior portion of the crissum are dark bluish at the base, pure white in the middle, and then blackish, and ultimately transition into the dominant steel-blue color; the white is concealed, and both the amount and purity diminish with distance from that region of the body, until it fades into the usual gray median portion of the feather. It is also common for the adult male to have a concealed white patch on the breast, under the wings (1, 3)."Adult Female. Duller, more sooty-brown with steel-blue feather margins above, except on the forehead and anterior portion of the crown. These glossy margins are wider on the back and scapulars, where the underlying grayish-brown color is mostly concealed. Wings and tail are a darker sooty-brown or blackish, with a faint greenish-blue gloss. The sides of the head and neck, throat, breast, and underwing coverts are uniform brown to sooty-gray, and similar in color to the forehead, but paler. Lower breast, abdomen, around the vent and undertail coverts are white; unstreaked belly (3).
Female_Text: "Adult Male. Rich, steel-blue overall, with purple gloss. The wings and tail, however, are much glossier with a shade of greenish or sooty-black. Feathers around the vent and the anterior portion of the crissum are dark bluish at the base, pure white in the middle, and then blackish, and ultimately transition into the dominant steel-blue color; the white is concealed, and both the amount and purity diminish with distance from that region of the body, until it fades into the usual gray median portion of the feather. It is also common for the adult male to have a concealed white patch on the breast, under the wings (1, 3)."Adult Female. Duller, more sooty-brown with steel-blue feather margins above, except on the forehead and anterior portion of the crown. These glossy margins are wider on the back and scapulars, where the underlying grayish-brown color is mostly concealed. Wings and tail are a darker sooty-brown or blackish, with a faint greenish-blue gloss. The sides of the head and neck, throat, breast, and underwing coverts are uniform brown to sooty-gray, and similar in color to the forehead, but paler. Lower breast, abdomen, around the vent and undertail coverts are white; unstreaked belly (3).

Male_Text: "Female. Resembles adult male, but duller above. The forecrown is sooty brown. The wings and tail have a greenish-blue gloss. The sides of the head and neck are grayish brown or sooty, the auriculars glossed with steel blue. The malar region, chin, throat, breast, sides, flanks, axillaries, and underwing coverts are sooty gray or grayish brown; the feathers of the chest (and sometimes the throat) also have indistinct pale gray tips. The lower breast, belly, and undertail coverts are pure white." Male. Most of the body (upperparts, throat, and upper breast) is glossy steel blue or violaceous steel blue. The lower breast, belly, and undertail coverts are pure white, except for some dark spots or a dark band across the undertail coverts. Underwing coverts and axillars are gray brown. Wings and tail are black with a bluish gloss.
Female_Text: "Female. Resembles adult male, but duller above. The forecrown is sooty brown. The wings and tail have a greenish-blue gloss. The sides of the head and neck are grayish brown or sooty, the auriculars glossed with steel blue. The malar region, chin, throat, breast, sides, flanks, axillaries, and underwing coverts are sooty gray or grayish brown; the feathers of the chest (and sometimes the throat) also have indistinct pale gray tips. The lower breast, belly, and undertail coverts are pure white." Male. Most of the body (upperparts, throat, and upper breast) is glossy steel blue or violaceous steel blue. The lower breast, belly, and undertail coverts are pure white, except for some dark spots or a dark band across the undertail coverts. Underwing coverts and axillars are gray brown. Wings and tail are black with a bluish gloss.

Male_Text: "Male: Forehead chestnut; remainder of upperparts metallic indigo blue to slightly purplish blue; wings chaetura black to chaetura drab or fuscous on inner webs, exposed surface with metallic green sheen, except lesser coverts, which are similar to back (no reddish-brown edgings); tail deeply forked, outermost rectrices (r6) projecting 35–53 mm beyond central pair (r1) on closed tail (Figure 209 in Pyle [26]); rectrices chaetura black, glossed with metallic green, all feathers except middle pair with conspicuous large white or buffy white spot on inner web, largest and oblong on outer pair. Lores and cheeks fuscous or fuscous black; sides of neck like crown; chin and throat chestnut to cinnamon rufous, separated from remainder of underparts by incomplete breast-band of dull metallic blue or greenish feathers; remainder of underparts, including wing-lining, varies from chestnut to pale pinkish buff." Female: Similar to male, but upperparts slightly more greenish; underparts average paler; tail less deeply forked, the outermost rectrices (r6) projecting 26–38 mm beyond central pair (r1) on closed tail (Figure 209 in Pyle [26])."
Female_Text: "Male: Forehead chestnut; remainder of upperparts metallic indigo blue to slightly purplish blue; wings chaetura black to chaetura drab or fuscous on inner webs, exposed surface with metallic green sheen, except lesser coverts, which are similar to back (no reddish-brown edgings); tail deeply forked, outermost rectrices (r6) projecting 35–53 mm beyond central pair (r1) on closed tail (Figure 209 in Pyle [26]); rectrices chaetura black, glossed with metallic green, all feathers except middle pair with conspicuous large white or buffy white spot on inner web, largest and oblong on outer pair. Lores and cheeks fuscous or fuscous black; sides of neck like crown; chin and throat chestnut to cinnamon rufous, separated from remainder of underparts by incomplete breast-band of dull metallic blue or greenish feathers; remainder of underparts, including wing-lining, varies from chestnut to pale pinkish buff." Female: Similar to male, but upperparts slightly more greenish; underparts average paler; tail less deeply forked, the outermost rectrices (r6) projecting 26–38 mm beyond central pair (r1) on closed tail (Figure 209 in Pyle [26])."

Male_Text: "Present primarily December–November. Lores and upperparts primarily metallic bluish black or greenish slate; forehead with a triangular patch of cream, pale wood-brown, or buff; auriculars bright to dark chestnut, extending as narrow nape collar of buff or cinnamon, sometimes mixed chestnut; back feathers and scapulars fringed brownish gray when fresh, the central back feathers also edged bright white forming two to a few narrow vertical streaks; rump tawny to pinkish buff; uppertail coverts dull hair-brown, margined broadly at tips with grayish white when fresh; tail grayish brown to brown with slight metallic greenish sheen when fresh. Upperwing lesser coverts metallic bluish black or greenish slate proximally, becoming grayish brown distally; remaining upperwing feathers grayish brown to brown with slight metallic greenish sheen and narrow white fringing when fresh, the tertials and inner secondaries tipped dull whitish, broadly when fresh. In winter narrow brownish gray, buff, and brownish white fringing to fresher upperpart feathers creates muted appearance; by spring this edging wears off resulting in brighter appearance for breeding. Chin, throat, and sides of neck chestnut, the center and base of throat metallic greenish or bluish black; chest and breast whitish washed with buff or ochraceous and mottled dull light drab; remainder of underparts primarily white, the upper flanks washed drab and the central portions of the longer undertail coverts hair-brown; underwing coverts dull drab, occasionally washed with cinnamon or chestnut. Males average larger bluish patch on lower throat; otherwise males and females similar in plumage (CRB, MBB)."
Female_Text: "Present primarily December–November. Lores and upperparts primarily metallic bluish black or greenish slate; forehead with a triangular patch of cream, pale wood-brown, or buff; auriculars bright to dark chestnut, extending as narrow nape collar of buff or cinnamon, sometimes mixed chestnut; back feathers and scapulars fringed brownish gray when fresh, the central back feathers also edged bright white forming two to a few narrow vertical streaks; rump tawny to pinkish buff; uppertail coverts dull hair-brown, margined broadly at tips with grayish white when fresh; tail grayish brown to brown with slight metallic greenish sheen when fresh. Upperwing lesser coverts metallic bluish black or greenish slate proximally, becoming grayish brown distally; remaining upperwing feathers grayish brown to brown with slight metallic greenish sheen and narrow white fringing when fresh, the tertials and inner secondaries tipped dull whitish, broadly when fresh. In winter narrow brownish gray, buff, and brownish white fringing to fresher upperpart feathers creates muted appearance; by spring this edging wears off resulting in brighter appearance for breeding. Chin, throat, and sides of neck chestnut, the center and base of throat metallic greenish or bluish black; chest and breast whitish washed with buff or ochraceous and mottled dull light drab; remainder of underparts primarily white, the upper flanks washed drab and the central portions of the longer undertail coverts hair-brown; underwing coverts dull drab, occasionally washed with cinnamon or chestnut. Males average larger bluish patch on lower throat; otherwise males and females similar in plumage (CRB, MBB)."

Male_Text: "Present Oct-Sep. Forehead russet, chestnut or tawny; lores and orbital ring dull black, sometimes slightly mixed with tawny; nape and back metallic greenish slate black, the former duller and the latter with a few grayish white streaks formed by edges of feathers; narrow collar on nape between ochraceous orange and tawny; rump tawny to cinnamon rufous; uppertail coverts fuscous; wings and tail brownish-gray, slightly glossed with dull metallic green, but inner webs of quills light fuscous; outer rectrices margined on inner webs terminally with white; tertials tipped narrowly with pale brownish white; lesser wing coverts with slightly more metallic sheen; sides of head below eyes and sides of neck between ochraceous orange and tawny; throat buffy cinnamon; lower breast and abdomen dull brownish white or buffy white; sides and flanks light hair brown washed with cinnamon; undertail coverts white, the longer ones hair brown centrally and all tinged with cinnamon buff or pale orange cinnamon; lining of underwing dull light hair brown or drab washed with buff."
Female_Text: "Present Oct-Sep. Forehead russet, chestnut or tawny; lores and orbital ring dull black, sometimes slightly mixed with tawny; nape and back metallic greenish slate black, the former duller and the latter with a few grayish white streaks formed by edges of feathers; narrow collar on nape between ochraceous orange and tawny; rump tawny to cinnamon rufous; uppertail coverts fuscous; wings and tail brownish-gray, slightly glossed with dull metallic green, but inner webs of quills light fuscous; outer rectrices margined on inner webs terminally with white; tertials tipped narrowly with pale brownish white; lesser wing coverts with slightly more metallic sheen; sides of head below eyes and sides of neck between ochraceous orange and tawny; throat buffy cinnamon; lower breast and abdomen dull brownish white or buffy white; sides and flanks light hair brown washed with cinnamon; undertail coverts white, the longer ones hair brown centrally and all tinged with cinnamon buff or pale orange cinnamon; lining of underwing dull light hair brown or drab washed with buff."

Male_Text: "(Ridgway 1904). Pileum (including postocular and upper half of loral regions) and hindneck uniform black, with a faint bluish gloss; malar region, chin, throat, and upper chest uniform deep black, sharply defined posteriorly; sides of head and neck between the two black areas white; back, scapular, lesser wing coverts, rump, and upper tail coverts plain deep olive gray or mouse gray, the rump more strongly tinged with olive; wings and tail dull slate color with gray edgings, edgings paler on primaries and (except in worn plumage) on tertials; sides, flanks and under tail coverts olive gray (paler and more tinged with olive than back); median portion of lower chest, breast, and abdomen white."
Female_Text: "(Ridgway 1904). Pileum (including postocular and upper half of loral regions) and hindneck uniform black, with a faint bluish gloss; malar region, chin, throat, and upper chest uniform deep black, sharply defined posteriorly; sides of head and neck between the two black areas white; back, scapular, lesser wing coverts, rump, and upper tail coverts plain deep olive gray or mouse gray, the rump more strongly tinged with olive; wings and tail dull slate color with gray edgings, edgings paler on primaries and (except in worn plumage) on tertials; sides, flanks and under tail coverts olive gray (paler and more tinged with olive than back); median portion of lower chest, breast, and abdomen white."

Male_Text: "Male. In fresh plumage (Aug–Jan), crown and nape black, faintly glossed blue. Remaining upperparts, including lesser and median wing coverts and central rectrices (R1), medium bluish gray, with some nape-feathers often showing white centers; remaining rectrices black, R3–R6 tipped blue-gray, R4–R6 with diagonal white subterminal bar, largest on R6. Greater wing coverts and tertials dark brown-gray, broadly margined on outer web with same color as back. Primaries, secondaries, primary coverts, and alula dark gray-brown; all but outer primaries narrowly margined on outer web with same color as back; P3–P6 fringed pale gray inward of emargination. Forehead and supercilium, extending to sides of upper mantle, whitish. Extreme base of bill and eye-stripe, extending to sides of upper mantle, black; black may be very broad at rear, connecting with rear crown, although narrower on some birds, with white mottling on lower border and sides of neck. Narrow white eye-ring. Chin, cheeks, ear coverts, and sides of neck pale buff to whitish, darkening to cinnamon-orange on breast and rufous-cinnamon on sides of breast, flanks, belly, vent, and undertail-coverts (underparts, however, very variable, from buffy white to ochre-cinnamon). Underwing coverts and axillaries whitish, washed cinnamon; median underprimary coverts dark gray; base of primaries whitish. In worn plumage (Jan–Aug), cap duller, loses gloss (feather tips abraded); upperparts duller and less blue, with more white mottling on nape; flight feathers bleached paler and browner; and underparts paler and less richly colored, dirty pale orange-buff to dull whitish." Female. Similar to male, but crown and eye-stripe may be mid-gray-blue, as upperparts are, although usually slightly darker, blackish gray; sooty-black feather-bases show to variable extent, especially on forecrown, which may wear to dull black (and in worn plumage, whole cap averages darker). Feathers of eye-stripe blackish, fringed gray; black may show on some birds when plumage is fresh, especially behind eye, and on most when worn, though eye-stripe never is as wide or as black as on male. White supercilium is less contrasting, and underparts on average are paler and not so richly colored, cinnamon-buff.

"(Sep-following Aug). Back, rump, uppertail coverts, and central pair of rectrices bluish-gray, with faint suggestion of barring on latter and shafts black; sides of head (except short dark streaks back of eye) and underparts white or grayish-white, the flanks and undertail coverts rusty or cinnamon; primaries dark brownish-slate, the longest with a white spot near middle on outer web and narrow white fringe at tips; secondaries brownish-slate, margined with bluish-gray and tipped with white; tertials dark gray, margined with bluish-gray and tipped with white; wing coverts dark centrally, margined with bluish-gray, the greater ones tipped with white, forming wing-bar; underwing coverts black with large white patch formed by white bases of primaries; rectrices, except middle pair, black with large white patches near ends, outer webs of outermost rectrices are white (Roberts 1932, Cadman et al. 1987)." Sexes differ in plumage, primarily that of head. Female shows crown more or less obscured by bluish-gray and hindneck is black as in males. Dimorphism of crown plumage varies geographically (see Systematics: geographic variation), being less pronounced in southeastern populations, where crowns of definitive-plumaged females can be more-or-less black, matching formative-plumaged males but typically duller (less glossy) than those of definitive-plumaged males (Sheppard and Klimkiewicz 1976, Wood 1992c, Pyle 1997c). Females also show duller body plumage overall (Cadman et al. 1987, Pyle 1997c), especially upperparts (duller gray) and wing edging (dull and with brownish tinge). Males of all populations show crown and nape black glossy greenish black, and brighter body plumage overall, including upperparts (brighter bluish gray) and wing edging bluish gray without brownish tinge (Cadman et al. 1987, Pyle 1997c).

Traits.inferred: Beak Culmen; Beak Nares; Beak Width; Beak Depth; Tarsus Length; Wing Length; Kipp's Distance; Secondary1; Hand-Wing Index; Tail Length

annotation: Formerly called Plain Wren, but now treated separately from Cantorchilus zeledoni and C. elutus.
Formerly considered conspecific with Cantorchilus modestus and C. elutus.
Traits.inferred: Beak Culmen; Beak Nares; Beak Width; Beak Depth; Tarsus Length; Wing Length; Kipp's Distance; Secondary1; Hand-Wing Index; Tail Length

annotation: Formerly considered conspecific with Cantorchilus modestus and C. zeledoni.

Male_Text: "Male. Head with glossy, bluish-black cap (with-out gray or dull-black feathers) extending down to upper edge of lores and auriculars. White eye-ring, lores grayish white. Nape, back, scapulars, and rump deep neutral gray to deep slate gray or brownish. Wing-coverts colored as back. Alula-feathers, primary coverts, and remiges dull blackish brown. Alula and proximal portion of primaries edged pale gray on outer web. Secondaries edged same color as back on outer web. Tertials and innermost secondaries margined dull whitish on outer web. Tail long and graduated (approximately 52 mm); outermost rectrix (R6) with outer web and terminal portion of inner web white; R5 with edge of outer web and tip of inner web white; and R4 with white tip. Underparts grayish white." Female. Similar to male but lacks dark cap (top of head same color as back) and greater wing coverts, back, and rump more brownish. Pyle and Unitt (Pyle and Unitt 1998) speculate that older females may show black in crown, but otherwise gray.

annotation: Formerly considered conspecific with P. albiloris.
Formerly included in the genus Cettia.

Male_Text: "Male. Head, back, and upper breast are glossy blue black (darker than Smithe color 90). Wings and tail dull black, not glossy. Lower breast and belly light Amber. Rump, uppertail-coverts, and outer rectrices white."Female. Plumage generally duller than that of male. Head, back, upper breast, wings, and tail are all dull grayish black, not glossy. Lower breast and belly are light Amber, both lighter and duller than adult male plumage. Rump, uppertail-coverts, and outer rectrices are white as in male."

annotation: Formerly included in the genus Luscinia.

Traits.inferred: Beak Nares; Kipp's Distance; Secondary1; Hand-Wing Index

Male_Text: "This and Dumetella are the smallest mimids; has wings short and rounded, tail somewhat long. Plumage is uniform glossy blue-blackvideo ; iris dark reddish; billphoto and legsphoto black. Sexes alike, female slightly less heavy than male. Juvenile is brownish-grey, mottled below, iris grey."
Female_Text: "This and Dumetella are the smallest mimids; has wings short and rounded, tail somewhat long. Plumage is uniform glossy blue-blackvideo ; iris dark reddish; billphoto and legsphoto black. Sexes alike, female slightly less heavy than male. Juvenile is brownish-grey, mottled below, iris grey."

annotation: Formerly known as Le Conte's Thrasher.

Male_Text: "All starlings after the first Prebasic molt have very similar plumage. Body feathers are glossy blackish, iridescence gives an almost oily sheen to many areas. Iridescence on crown is mixed green and purple, auricular area green, nape and throat purple, back mostly green, and breast and belly mostly green. Body feathers on the dorsal side have more or less triangular terminal spots ranging from cream #54 to cinnamon 39 spots on the ventral side are whitish, and increase in size posteriorly. Under tail coverts broadly edged with whitish. Wing and tail feathers blackish to olive brown #28, with margins of cinnamon #39." Females are somewhat duller than adult males. Other plumage differences include iridescence on the distal vane of the secondaries: present on most of the secondaries in adult males but only on the inner secondaries in adult females and juveniles (Suthers 1978). Under wing coverts also differ, being very dark or black in adult males and brown or gray in females, but this varies among individuals."
Female_Text: "All starlings after the first Prebasic molt have very similar plumage. Body feathers are glossy blackish, iridescence gives an almost oily sheen to many areas. Iridescence on crown is mixed green and purple, auricular area green, nape and throat purple, back mostly green, and breast and belly mostly green. Body feathers on the dorsal side have more or less triangular terminal spots ranging from cream #54 to cinnamon 39 spots on the ventral side are whitish, and increase in size posteriorly. Under tail coverts broadly edged with whitish. Wing and tail feathers blackish to olive brown #28, with margins of cinnamon #39." Females are somewhat duller than adult males. Other plumage differences include iridescence on the distal vane of the secondaries: present on most of the secondaries in adult males but only on the inner secondaries in adult females and juveniles (Suthers 1978). Under wing coverts also differ, being very dark or black in adult males and brown or gray in females, but this varies among individuals."

Male_Text: "Male. Plumage entirely black, except primaries 2 through 9 with white inner webs that are black distally (black distal portion of inner web ~ 25 mm. in length). White portion of primaries forming prominent white patch on wing visible only in flight or when wing extended. Head with prominent crest. Contour feathers glossy, appearing slightly bluish green. Margins of median and lesser wing coverts, and narrow margins on outer webs of greater and primary wing coverts, remiges and rectrices similarly glossy. Tail long and squarish in shape. Rectrices truncate and less tapered in shape than in previous plumages." Female. Contour feathers medium gray with slight brownish tinge, becoming slightly paler and whiter on chin, forehead, and nape. Head with prominent crest as in male. Darker ear coverts, undertail-coverts, and narrow border around eye; darker, almost blackish on lores, central portion of crest feathers, and uppertail-coverts. Uppertail-coverts margined with medium gray. Undertail-coverts margined with whitish. Feathers of lower belly margined paler. Feathers of wing and tail dark brownish gray, appearing blackish. Primaries 2 through 9 with paler gray inner webs that are darker distally. Pale gray portion of primaries forming patch on wing visible in flight or when wing extended as in male. Lesser wing coverts broadly margined paler, becoming whiter distally. Median wing coverts margined with white. Greater wing coverts margined and tipped with white. Remiges narrowly edged paler with extent of edge becoming more restricted to base of feather towards outer primaries, and brightness of edge increasing towards tertials, edged with white. Rectrices paler, very narrowly edged on outer web, becoming whitish on outermost feathers. Shape of rectrices as in male."

"Nominate racephoto has headphoto and upper breastvideo brownish black, browner on hindneck and neck-side, with variable amounts of greenish gloss on cap and face, often also some purplish gloss on cheeks and breast, rest of upperparts dull brown with strong green gloss on some outer scapulars, blackish and whitish barring on rump and uppertail-coverts; white from lower breast downwards except for a blackish patch with strong green gloss on sides of lower breast and deep brown and/or blackish barring on flanks and undertail-coverts; iris dark brown, eyering dark grey; bill black above, pale bluish grey below, generally bluer and palest on at base of lower mandible; legs grey to black. Sexes alike. Juvenile is unmarked brown above, face tan, upper breast and flanks light brown, lower breast and belly to undertail-coverts buff, bill black; in adult plumage by 6 months. Race scutata lacks green gloss on barred flanks."
Female_Text: "Nominate racephoto has headphoto and upper breastvideo brownish black, browner on hindneck and neck-side, with variable amounts of greenish gloss on cap and face, often also some purplish gloss on cheeks and breast, rest of upperparts dull brown with strong green gloss on some outer scapulars, blackish and whitish barring on rump and uppertail-coverts; white from lower breast downwards except for a blackish patch with strong green gloss on sides of lower breast and deep brown and/or blackish barring on flanks and undertail-coverts; iris dark brown, eyering dark grey; bill black above, pale bluish grey below, generally bluer and palest on at base of lower mandible; legs grey to black. Sexes alike. Juvenile is unmarked brown above, face tan, upper breast and flanks light brown, lower breast and belly to undertail-coverts buff, bill black; in adult plumage by 6 months. Race scutata lacks green gloss on barred flanks."

Male_Text: "Male. Has forehead to eye bright yellow (appearing as a small, relatively restricted patch), rest of head down to foreneck glossy blue-black with purplish sheen; upperparts glossy blue-black; median and greater upper­wing-coverts, flight-feathers, and tertials blackish, somewhat glossed dark blue; breast, belly and undertail-coverts bright yellow, under­wing-coverts white; tail blackish, with inner webs of outer two tail feathers white (from below, showing as large oval-shaped patch on each side of tail)(1)." Female. Has forehead olive-yellow, becoming grayish on rest of crown and nape; upperparts olive, with gray tinge on back; side of head and most of underparts olive-yellow, turning to yellow on belly and undertail-coverts (1).

" Small, short-tailed euphonia with short stubby bill. Male has forehead and mid-crown to well behind eye yellow, forming large contrasting yellow crown patch; rest of head down to foreneck and entire upperparts glossy blue-black, upperwing-coverts, flight-feathers and tail blue-black (like back); breast to undertail-coverts entirely bright yellow, underwing-coverts white; iris dark brown; bill blue-grey with blackish tip; legs dark grey. Female is olive above, with yellowish tinge on forehead, plain olive-yellow below, slightly paler in centre, becoming duller on belly and undertail-coverts. Immature is like female; subadult male may have forecrown mottled olive, some black on face and throat, and has throat and chest yellowish, rest of underparts olive."

"Rather small euphonia with relatively thick bill deeper than that of most congeners. Male nominate race has yellow forehead to mid-crown (a little past eye); side of head, rear crown, nape and upperparts glossy blue-black; uppertail dark blue; upperwing-coverts and flight-feathers dusky, tinged dark blue; throat and entire underparts bright yellow; undertail dark grey, inner webs of outer 2–3 feather pairs mostly white (forming two large white ovals on undersurface of tail); iris dark brown; bill blackish, base of lower mandible blue-grey; legs dark grey. Female is yellowish olive-green above, greenish-yellow below, paler on undertail-coverts. Immature is similar to female; subadult male (second full year) is olive above, forecrown yellow with olive mottling, variable amount of black on side of head (usually forming mask), throat and chest yellow, sides, flanks and lower underparts mostly olive. Race crassirostrisphoto male is similar to nominate, but yellow of crown extends farther backwards, especially in centre; hypoxantha male differs in having whole crown lemon-yellow, and underparts lighter and brighter yellow; melanuravideo malevideo has crown like nominate, but underparts darker, orange-yellow, and undertail entirely dark grey (no white), female similar to nominate, but darker below; zopholegavideo male is similar to nominate, but white ovals on undertail smaller."

"Female. Ridgway (2) gives the full description of the female as "Forehead gamboge yellow, margined posteriorly by an indistinct dusky bar across anterior part of crown; rest of pileum, hindneck, and sides of neck uniform light greenish blue (turquoise); loral, suborbital, and auricular regions and most of malar region plain olive green; back, scapulars, wing coverts, and upper tail coverts plain deep olive green, with a slight gloss of metallic bluish green; rump yellowish olive green; remiges and rectrices blackish, the latter and the secondaries with broad edgings of olive green, the primaries with narrow edgings of the same or pale greenish gray; under parts deep olive yellow, becoming purer yellow on chin, throat, abdomen, anal region, and under tail coverts, the last with central portion more olive." Male. Lores, side of head including ear coverts, and chin and throat blackish violet, small forehead band tawny yellow, crown and nape lustrous sky blue, blue of nape extending down behind rear ear coverts; mantle and back black, glossed dark blue, rump and uppertail coverts rich tawny yellow; upper­wing coverts, flight feathers and tail dull black, wing coverts glossed dark blue, flight feathers edged slightly paler blue; underparts, including undertail coverts, rich tawny yellow."

"Small-billed euphonia, male with orange-rufous underparts. Male nominate race has rufous forehead bordered behind by pencil-thin line of black; crown and nape bright turquoise-blue, the blue extending down side of neck behind ear-coverts; side of head and throat black; upper­parts, including upperwing-coverts, flight-feathers and tail, glossy purplish-black; underparts tawny-orange, darkest on chest; underwing-coverts white; iris dark brown; bill blackish, greyish base of lower mandible; legs dusky grey. Female has forehead rufous, bright sky-blue crown and nape, blue curling down onto side of neck behind ear-coverts (as on male), side of head olive; upperparts bright olive-green; upperwing-coverts mostly olive-green, flight-feathers dusky, edged olive-green; tail dull dark olive-green; throat washed cinnamon, becoming yellowish-olive on breast and sides and greenish-yellow on centre of belly and undertail-coverts. Juvenile is like female, male with cinnamon-tinged chin and contrasting blue-black flight-feathers; immature male much like adult female, but slightly duller, and with blue restricted to crown (not reaching nape). Race rileyi male more steely-blue above, with duller hood, female greyer above and generally duller (less green and yellow) than nominate; vincens male has crown distinctly lighter blue than nominate, female intermediate between those of other races."

"9 cm; 10·1–13 g. Rather small euphonia with tawny-rufous undertail-coverts. Male nominate race has small lemon-yellow patch on forehead extending back to just above eye; rest of head, throat to central chest and upperparts, including upperwing-coverts, glossy blue-black; flight-feathers dusky, tinged blue black; uppertail blue-black with slight gloss; breast, sides and flanks bright golden-yellow, median underparts cinnamon-yellow, vent and undertail-coverts yellowish-cinnamon; undertail dark grey, inner webs of outer two feather pairs mostly white, forming large, somewhat oval-shaped white patch on each side; iris dark brown; upper mandible and tip of lower mandible dusky blackish, rest of lower mandible blue-grey; legs dark grey.
